export const TEXTBOOKS = {"qariah":"<div class=\"book\">\n\n  <div class=\"surah-header\">\n    <div class=\"surah-label\">Sūrah 101 · Makkī · 11 verses</div>\n    <div class=\"surah-title-en\">The Striking Calamity</div>\n    <div class=\"surah-title-ar\">سُورَةُ الْقَارِعَةِ</div>\n    <div class=\"surah-meta\">The surah opens with a three-verse echo structure borrowed from سُورَة الْحَاقَّة — the noun as مُبْتَدَأ, the اسْتِفْهَام sentence as its خَبَر, then the وَمَا أَدْرَاكَ formula. It then pivots to the Day itself (vv. 4–5), before the central أَمَّا-structure (vv. 6–9) delivers two parallel conditional fates. A showcase surah for the كَان نَاقِصَة, the أَمَّا-شَرْط, and هَاء السَّكْت.</div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"intro-box\">\n    Three grammatical structures dominate: (1) the self-referential nominal sentence in vv. 1–2 (noun = مُبْتَدَأ, interrogative sentence = خَبَر); (2) the كَان نَاقِصَة with the two-reading كَاف in vv. 4–5 (حَرْف or اسْم); and (3) the أَمَّا-construction in vv. 6–9 — one of the cleanest examples of how مَن as اسْم شَرْط sets up a مُبْتَدَأ whose خَبَر is the combined شَرْط-جَوَاب unit.\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"section-head\">Part I — The Opening Echo (Verses 1–3)</div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 1</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">الْقَارِعَةُ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"The Striking Calamity —\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">الْقَارِعَةُ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">مُبْتَدَأ مَرْفُوع</span> by <span class=\"term\">ضَمَّة ظَاهِرَة</span>. It stands alone — its <span class=\"term\">خَبَر</span> is the nominal sentence that follows in verse 2. This is the same pattern as the opening of سُورَة الْحَاقَّة: a weighty noun suspended as مُبْتَدَأ, its meaning unpacked by an interrogative خَبَر in the next verse.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">الْقَارِعَةُ</span><span>مُبْتَدَأ مَرْفُوع وَعَلَامَة رَفْعِهِ الضَّمَّة الظَّاهِرَة. خَبَرُهُ جُمْلَة \"مَا الْقَارِعَةُ\" فِي الْآيَة التَّالِيَة.</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 2</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">مَا الْقَارِعَةُ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"What is the Striking Calamity?\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>This verse is a <span class=\"term\">جُمْلَة اسْمِيَّة</span> functioning as the <span class=\"term\">خَبَر</span> of الْقَارِعَةُ in verse 1. <span class=\"ar-inline\">مَا</span> is an <span class=\"term\">اسْم اسْتِفْهَام</span> built on <span class=\"term\">سُكُون</span> in the position of <span class=\"term\">رَفْع</span> as the inner <span class=\"term\">مُبْتَدَأ</span>. <span class=\"ar-inline\">الْقَارِعَةُ</span> is its <span class=\"term\">خَبَر</span> in <span class=\"term\">رَفْع</span> by <span class=\"term\">ضَمَّة ظَاهِرَة</span>.</p>\n      <p>The full sentence spanning vv. 1–2 is therefore: الْقَارِعَةُ [مُبْتَدَأ] — مَا الْقَارِعَةُ [خَبَر]. This outer جُمْلَة is <span class=\"term\">ابْتِدَائِيَّة</span> — no syntactic position. The inner sentence \"مَا الْقَارِعَةُ\" is in the position of <span class=\"term\">رَفْع</span> as خَبَر of the outer مُبْتَدَأ.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">مَا</span><span>اسْم اسْتِفْهَام مَبْنِيّ عَلَى السُّكُون فِي مَحَلِّ رَفْع مُبْتَدَأ.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">الْقَارِعَةُ</span><span>خَبَر \"مَا\" مَرْفُوع بِضَمَّة ظَاهِرَة. جُمْلَة \"مَا الْقَارِعَةُ\" فِي مَحَلِّ رَفْع خَبَر الْمُبْتَدَأ (الْقَارِعَةُ) فِي الْآيَة الأُولَى.</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 3</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">وَمَآ أَدْرَىٰكَ مَا الْقَارِعَةُ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"And what will make you know what the Striking Calamity is?\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>The fixed وَمَا أَدْرَاكَ formula — identical in structure to سُورَة الْهُمَزَة v.5 and سُورَة الْحَاقَّة v.3. The وَاو is <span class=\"term\">حَرْف عَطْف</span>. The first <span class=\"ar-inline\">مَا</span> is an <span class=\"term\">اسْم اسْتِفْهَام</span> in <span class=\"term\">رَفْع</span> as <span class=\"term\">مُبْتَدَأ</span>. <span class=\"ar-inline\">أَدْرَاكَ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">فِعْل مَاضٍ</span> with <span class=\"term\">فَتْح مُقَدَّر</span> on the أَلِف (تَعَذُّر); its <span class=\"term\">فَاعِل</span> is a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر جَوَازًا</span> هُوَ referring back to مَا; the كَاف is <span class=\"term\">مَفْعُول بِهِ أَوَّل</span> in نَصْب; the clause أَدْرَاكَ is the <span class=\"term\">خَبَر</span> of the first مَا. The second <span class=\"ar-inline\">مَا</span> is another <span class=\"term\">اسْم اسْتِفْهَام</span> as inner مُبْتَدَأ, and <span class=\"ar-inline\">الْقَارِعَةُ</span> is its خَبَر — the whole second nominal sentence is the <span class=\"term\">مَفْعُول بِهِ ثَانٍ</span> of أَدْرَاكَ in the position of نَصْب.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">مَا (الأُولَى)</span><span>اسْم اسْتِفْهَام فِي مَحَلِّ رَفْع مُبْتَدَأ.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">أَدْرَاكَ</span><span>فِعْل مَاضٍ — فَتْح مُقَدَّر (تَعَذُّر). فَاعِله ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر جَوَازًا هُوَ. الْكَاف: مَفْعُول بِهِ أَوَّل. الْجُمْلَة خَبَر \"مَا\" الأُولَى.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">مَا الْقَارِعَةُ</span><span>مَا: اسْم اسْتِفْهَام مُبْتَدَأ. الْقَارِعَةُ: خَبَر. الْجُمْلَة فِي مَحَلِّ نَصْب مَفْعُول بِهِ ثَانٍ لِـ\"أَدْرَاكَ\".</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <hr class=\"divider\">\n  <div class=\"section-head\">Part II — The Day's Images (Verses 4–5)</div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 4</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">يَوْمَ يَكُونُ النَّاسُ كَالْفَرَاشِ الْمَبْثُوثِ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"The Day people will be like scattered moths —\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">يَوْمَ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">ظَرْف زَمَان</span> in <span class=\"term\">نَصْب</span> by <span class=\"term\">فَتْحَة</span>, <span class=\"term\">مُتَعَلِّق</span> by an implied verb meaning \"it strikes\" (تَقْرَعُ). <span class=\"ar-inline\">يَكُونُ</span> is the <span class=\"term\">فِعْل الْمُضَارِع النَّاقِص</span> (deficient/incomplete verb كَان) in <span class=\"term\">رَفْع</span> by <span class=\"term\">ضَمَّة ظَاهِرَة</span> — called نَاقِصَة because it does not convey a complete meaning on its own; it requires an اسْم in رَفْع and a خَبَر in نَصْب. <span class=\"ar-inline\">النَّاسُ</span> is the <span class=\"term\">اسْم يَكُونُ</span> in <span class=\"term\">رَفْع</span> by <span class=\"term\">ضَمَّة ظَاهِرَة</span>.</p>\n\n      <p>The خَبَر of يَكُونُ is <span class=\"ar-inline\">كَالْفَرَاشِ</span>. Grammarians give two valid analyses of the كَاف here: <br>\n      (1) <span class=\"term\">حَرْف جَرّ لِلتَّشْبِيه</span> — a preposition of comparison; الْفَرَاشِ is then <span class=\"term\">مَجْرُور</span> by it with كَسْرَة, and the جَارّ وَمَجْرُور is in the position of <span class=\"term\">نَصْب خَبَر يَكُونُ</span>. <br>\n      (2) <span class=\"term\">اسْم بِمَعْنَى مِثْل</span> — كَاف treated as a noun (as in سُورَة الْفِيل v.5); الْفَرَاشِ then becomes <span class=\"term\">مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ</span> in جَرّ, and كَاف itself is the <span class=\"term\">خَبَر</span> in نَصْب. Both readings are grammatically sound.</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">الْمَبْثُوثِ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">صِفَة</span> for الْفَرَاشِ in <span class=\"term\">جَرّ</span> by <span class=\"term\">كَسْرَة ظَاهِرَة</span>. The clause يَكُونُ النَّاسُ كَالْفَرَاشِ الْمَبْثُوثِ is in the position of <span class=\"term\">جَرّ</span> by إِضَافَة (as the muḍāf ilayhi of يَوْمَ).</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">يَوْمَ</span><span>ظَرْف زَمَان مَنْصُوب بِالْفَتْحَة — مُتَعَلِّق بِفِعْل مُضْمَر تَقْدِيرُهُ: تَقْرَعُ.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">يَكُونُ</span><span>فِعْل مُضَارِع نَاقِص مَرْفُوع بِضَمَّة ظَاهِرَة.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">النَّاسُ</span><span>اسْم \"يَكُونُ\" مَرْفُوع بِضَمَّة ظَاهِرَة.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">كَالْفَرَاشِ</span><span>الْكَاف: (1) حَرْف جَرّ لِلتَّشْبِيه — الْفَرَاشِ مَجْرُور، وَالْجَارّ وَالْمَجْرُور خَبَر يَكُونُ فِي مَحَلِّ نَصْب. أَو (2) اسْم بِمَعْنَى مِثْل، مَبْنِيّ عَلَى الْفَتْح فِي مَحَلِّ نَصْب خَبَر، وَالْفَرَاشِ مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">الْمَبْثُوثِ</span><span>صِفَة لِـ\"الْفَرَاشِ\" مَجْرُورَة بِكَسْرَة ظَاهِرَة.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">جُمْلَة يَكُونُ</span><span>فِي مَحَلِّ جَرّ بِالْإِضَافَة (مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ لِـ\"يَوْمَ\").</span></div>\n      </div>\n\n      <div class=\"callout\">\n        <div class=\"callout-title\">كَان النَّاقِصَة — why \"deficient\"?</div>\n        كَان and its sisters (كَان، أَصْبَحَ، أَمْسَى، صَارَ، لَيْسَ...) are called <span style=\"font-family:'Amiri',serif;font-size:15px;\">أَفْعَال نَاقِصَة</span> — deficient/incomplete verbs — because they do not convey a full predication on their own. They need both an اسْم (subject, in رَفْع) and a خَبَر (predicate, in نَصْب) to complete their meaning. The مُضَارِع يَكُونُ here works the same way as the مَاضِي كَانَ: اسْم in رَفْع + خَبَر in نَصْب.\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 5</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">وَتَكُونُ الْجِبَالُ كَالْعِهْنِ الْمَنفُوشِ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"And the mountains will be like fluffy tufts of wool.\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>Fully coordinated on verse 4 by وَاو and carries the identical iʿrāb throughout: تَكُونُ (فِعْل نَاقِص) + الْجِبَالُ (اسْم يَكُونُ في رَفْع) + كَالْعِهْنِ (خَبَر في نَصْب، same dual analysis of the كَاف) + الْمَنْفُوشِ (صِفَة في جَرّ).</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">وَتَكُونُ ... كَالْعِهْنِ الْمَنْفُوشِ</span><span>مَعْطُوفَة بِالْوَاو عَلَى الْآيَة السَّابِقَة — تُعْرَب إِعْرَابَهَا كَامِلًا.</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <hr class=\"divider\">\n  <div class=\"section-head\">Part III — The Two Fates (Verses 6–9)</div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 6</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">فَأَمَّا مَن ثَقُلَتْ مَوَٰزِينُهُۥ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"As for the one whose scales are heavy —\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>The فَاء is a <span class=\"term\">حَرْف اسْتِئْنَاف</span>. <span class=\"ar-inline\">أَمَّا</span> is a <span class=\"term\">حَرْف شَرْط وَتَفْصِيل</span> — it divides a subject into categories (\"as for...\"), but does not itself govern a verb in جَزْم. Its grammatical effect is indirect: it obligates the جَوَاب (answer clause) to begin with فَاء.</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">مَنْ</span> is an <span class=\"term\">اسْم شَرْط جَازِم</span> built on <span class=\"term\">سُكُون</span> in the position of <span class=\"term\">رَفْع</span> as <span class=\"term\">مُبْتَدَأ</span>. <span class=\"ar-inline\">ثَقُلَتْ</span> is the <span class=\"term\">فِعْل الشَّرْط</span> — a <span class=\"term\">فِعْل مَاضٍ</span> built on <span class=\"term\">فَتْح</span>; the تَاء is a <span class=\"term\">حَرْف تَأْنِيث</span> with no محل (it is in the position of جَزْم since the شَرْط clause is governed by مَن). <span class=\"ar-inline\">مَوَازِينُهُ</span> is the <span class=\"term\">فَاعِل</span> of ثَقُلَتْ in <span class=\"term\">رَفْع</span> by <span class=\"term\">ضَمَّة</span>; the هَاء is <span class=\"term\">مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ</span> in جَرّ by إِضَافَة. The whole جُمْلَة شَرْط وَجَوَابِهِ (from this verse + v.7) is in the position of <span class=\"term\">رَفْع</span> as the <span class=\"term\">خَبَر</span> of مَنْ. The outer مُبْتَدَأ-خَبَر sentence is <span class=\"term\">اسْتِئْنَافِيَّة</span> — no syntactic position.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">فَ</span><span>حَرْف اسْتِئْنَاف.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">أَمَّا</span><span>حَرْف شَرْط وَتَفْصِيل — لَا عَمَل لَهُ مُبَاشَرَةً.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">مَنْ</span><span>اسْم شَرْط جَازِم مَبْنِيّ عَلَى السُّكُون فِي مَحَلِّ رَفْع مُبْتَدَأ.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">ثَقُلَتْ</span><span>فِعْل الشَّرْط — مَاضٍ مَبْنِيّ عَلَى الْفَتْح. التَّاء: حَرْف تَأْنِيث فِي مَحَلِّ جَزْم.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">مَوَازِينُهُ</span><span>فَاعِل مَرْفُوع بِضَمَّة. الْهَاء: مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ فِي مَحَلِّ جَرّ.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">جُمْلَة الشَّرْط وَالْجَوَاب</span><span>فِي مَحَلِّ رَفْع خَبَر \"مَنْ\". جُمْلَة الْمُبْتَدَأ وَالْخَبَر اسْتِئْنَافِيَّة — لَا مَحَلَّ لَهَا.</span></div>\n      </div>\n\n      <div class=\"callout\">\n        <div class=\"callout-title\">أَمَّا + مَن — two layers of شَرْط</div>\n        This construction has two conditional layers. أَمَّا is a particle of categorisation that requires its جَوَاب to start with فَاء (seen in v.7: فَهُوَ). Inside it, مَن is the اسْم شَرْط جَازِم that technically governs both the فِعْل الشَّرْط (ثَقُلَتْ) and the جَوَاب (فَهُوَ فِي عِيشَةٍ) in جَزْم. The مُبْتَدَأ is مَن; the combined شَرْط-جَوَاب block is the خَبَر of مَن. This layering is characteristic of the أَمَّا...فَـ structure throughout the Qurʾān.\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 7</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">فَهُوَ فِى عِيشَةٍ رَّاضِيَةٍ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"He will be in a pleasing life.\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>The <span class=\"term\">فَاء</span> is a <span class=\"term\">حَرْف رَابِط</span> — it is the required فَاء that connects the جَوَاب to the أَمَّا. <span class=\"ar-inline\">هُوَ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير رَفْع مُنْفَصِل</span> in the position of <span class=\"term\">رَفْع</span> as <span class=\"term\">مُبْتَدَأ</span>. <span class=\"ar-inline\">فِي عِيشَةٍ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">جَارّ وَمَجْرُور</span> <span class=\"term\">مُتَعَلِّق</span> by the خَبَر of هُوَ. <span class=\"ar-inline\">رَاضِيَةٍ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">صِفَة</span> for عِيشَةٍ in <span class=\"term\">جَرّ</span> by <span class=\"term\">كَسْرَة ظَاهِرَة</span>. The whole clause is in the position of <span class=\"term\">جَزْم</span> as the <span class=\"term\">جَوَاب الشَّرْط</span>.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">فَ</span><span>حَرْف رَابِط وَاقِع فِي جَوَاب الشَّرْط (مَطْلُوب بَعْد أَمَّا).</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">هُوَ</span><span>ضَمِير رَفْع مُنْفَصِل فِي مَحَلِّ رَفْع مُبْتَدَأ.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">فِي عِيشَةٍ</span><span>جَارّ وَمَجْرُور مُتَعَلِّقَان بِخَبَر \"هُوَ\".</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">رَاضِيَةٍ</span><span>صِفَة لِـ\"عِيشَةٍ\" مَجْرُورَة بِكَسْرَة ظَاهِرَة.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">جُمْلَة هُوَ فِي عِيشَةٍ</span><span>فِي مَحَلِّ جَزْم جَوَاب الشَّرْط.</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verses 8–9</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">وَأَمَّا مَنْ خَفَّتْ مَوَٰزِينُهُۥ ۝ فَأُمُّهُۥ هَاوِيَةٌ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"But as for the one whose scales are light — his refuge will be an abyss.\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>Verse 8 is coordinated on verse 6 by وَاو and carries the same iʿrāb throughout: أَمَّا (حَرْف تَفْصِيل) + مَنْ (اسْم شَرْط جَازِم، مُبْتَدَأ) + خَفَّتْ (فِعْل الشَّرْط، مَاضٍ، تَاء = حَرْف تَأْنِيث) + مَوَازِينُهُ (فَاعِل في رَفْع).</p>\n\n      <p>In verse 9, the جَوَاب arrives. The فَاء is again the <span class=\"term\">حَرْف رَابِط</span>. <span class=\"ar-inline\">أُمُّهُ</span> is the <span class=\"term\">مُبْتَدَأ</span> in <span class=\"term\">رَفْع</span> by <span class=\"term\">ضَمَّة ظَاهِرَة</span>; the هَاء is a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير مُتَّصِل</span> in <span class=\"term\">جَرّ</span> by إِضَافَة. <span class=\"ar-inline\">هَاوِيَةٌ</span> is the <span class=\"term\">خَبَر</span> in <span class=\"term\">رَفْع</span> by <span class=\"term\">ضَمَّة ظَاهِرَة</span>. The whole nominal sentence \"أُمُّهُ هَاوِيَةٌ\" is in the position of <span class=\"term\">جَزْم</span> as <span class=\"term\">جَوَاب الشَّرْط</span>.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">وَأَمَّا مَنْ خَفَّتْ</span><span>مَعْطُوفَة عَلَى الْآيَة السَّادِسَة — تُعْرَب إِعْرَابَهَا كَامِلًا.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">فَأُمُّهُ</span><span>فَاء: حَرْف رَابِط. أُمُّ: مُبْتَدَأ مَرْفُوع بِضَمَّة. الْهَاء: مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ فِي مَحَلِّ جَرّ.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">هَاوِيَةٌ</span><span>خَبَر الْمُبْتَدَأ مَرْفُوع بِضَمَّة ظَاهِرَة. الْجُمْلَة فِي مَحَلِّ جَزْم جَوَاب الشَّرْط.</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 10</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">وَمَآ أَدْرَىٰكَ مَا هِيَهْ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"And what will make you know what it is?\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>The وَمَا أَدْرَاكَ formula again — identical iʿrāb to verse 3 for the first half. The difference is the second interrogative clause: instead of a noun, the خَبَر of the second مَا is <span class=\"ar-inline\">هِيَهْ</span>. <span class=\"ar-inline\">هِيَ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير رَفْع مُنْفَصِل</span> built on <span class=\"term\">فَتْح</span> in the position of <span class=\"term\">رَفْع</span> as the <span class=\"term\">خَبَر</span> of the second مَا, referring back to هَاوِيَة. The <span class=\"ar-inline\">هَاء</span> at the end is <span class=\"term\">هَاء السَّكْت</span> — a purely phonological particle added in pause to protect the final vowel of هِيَ from being dropped; it has no grammatical position (لَا مَحَلَّ لَهَا).</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">وَمَا أَدْرَاكَ</span><span>تُعْرَب إِعْرَاب الْآيَة الثَّالِثَة — نَفْس الْبِنَاء.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">هِيَ</span><span>ضَمِير رَفْع مُنْفَصِل مَبْنِيّ عَلَى الْفَتْح فِي مَحَلِّ رَفْع خَبَر \"مَا\".</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">هْ</span><span>هَاء السَّكْت — حَرْف لَا مَحَلَّ لَهُ مِن الْإِعْرَاب.</span></div>\n      </div>\n\n      <div class=\"callout\">\n        <div class=\"callout-title\">هَاء السَّكْت — what is it and why does it appear?</div>\n        Arabic pausal phonology sometimes requires a ه to be appended to a word ending in a vowel when that word is read with pause (وَقْف). Without it, the final vowel would be cut short and the word would sound abrupt. هَاء السَّكْت is purely phonological — it is never pronounced in connected speech (وَصْل) — and it has no grammatical function or syntactic position. It appears on هِيَهْ and أَنَا here; and on وَمَا أَدْرَاكَ مَا لِيَهْ in سُورَة الْحَاقَّة.\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 11</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">نَارٌ حَامِيَةٌ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"A blazing fire.\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">نَارٌ</span> is the <span class=\"term\">خَبَر مُبْتَدَأ مَحْذُوف</span> — the implied full sentence is هِيَ نَارٌ (\"it is a fire\"), answering the question of verse 10. It is in <span class=\"term\">رَفْع</span> by <span class=\"term\">ضَمَّة ظَاهِرَة</span>. <span class=\"ar-inline\">حَامِيَةٌ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">صِفَة</span> for نَارٌ in <span class=\"term\">رَفْع</span> by <span class=\"term\">ضَمَّة</span>. The sentence is <span class=\"term\">اسْتِئْنَافِيَّة</span> — no syntactic position.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">نَارٌ</span><span>خَبَر مُبْتَدَأ مَحْذُوف تَقْدِيرُهُ: هِيَ. مَرْفُوع بِضَمَّة ظَاهِرَة.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">حَامِيَةٌ</span><span>صِفَة لِـ\"نَارٌ\" مَرْفُوعَة بِضَمَّة ظَاهِرَة. الْجُمْلَة اسْتِئْنَافِيَّة — لَا مَحَلَّ لَهَا.</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <hr class=\"divider\">\n\n  <div class=\"theme-box\">\n    <h3>Structural summary</h3>\n    <div class=\"theme-grid\">\n      <div class=\"theme-card\">\n        <div class=\"theme-card-label\">Verses 1–3</div>\n        Self-referential nominal chain: اسْم = مُبْتَدَأ (v.1) → مَا + اسْم = خَبَر (v.2). Then وَمَا أَدْرَاكَ formula: dual مَا-sentences, فَتْح مُقَدَّر on أَدْرَاكَ (v.3).\n      </div>\n      <div class=\"theme-card\">\n        <div class=\"theme-card-label\">Verses 4–5</div>\n        يَكُونُ/تَكُونُ نَاقِصَة: اسْم في رَفْع + خَبَر in نَصْب. كَاف has two valid analyses (حَرْف جَرّ or اسْم مُضَاف). ظَرْف زَمَان يَوْمَ with implied مُتَعَلَّق.\n      </div>\n      <div class=\"theme-card\">\n        <div class=\"theme-card-label\">Verses 6–9</div>\n        أَمَّا + مَن (اسْم شَرْط جَازِم = مُبْتَدَأ). جُمْلَة الشَّرْط وَالْجَوَاب = خَبَر مَنْ. فَاء رَابِطَة required in الجواب. Two parallel fates with mirror iʿrāb.\n      </div>\n      <div class=\"theme-card\">\n        <div class=\"theme-card-label\">Verses 10–11</div>\n        وَمَا أَدْرَاكَ again; هِيَهْ = ضَمِير مُنْفَصِل as خَبَر + هَاء السَّكْت (no position). نَارٌ = خَبَر مُبْتَدَأ مَحْذُوف (هِيَ).\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n</div>","kafirun":"<div class=\"book\">\n\n  <div class=\"surah-header\">\n    <div class=\"surah-label\">Sūrah 109 · Makkī · 6 verses</div>\n    <div class=\"surah-title-en\">The Disbelievers</div>\n    <div class=\"surah-title-ar\">سُورَةُ الْكَافِرُونَ</div>\n    <div class=\"surah-meta\">A surah of precise grammatical symmetry. Verses 2–5 form two mirrored pairs of negation, each pair using a slightly different construction — the variation is deliberate and each carries distinct iʿrāb. The closing verse (6) introduces the <span style=\"font-family:'Amiri',serif;font-size:15px;\">مُبْتَدَأ مُؤَخَّر</span> pattern and a deleted يَاء of إِضَافَة.</div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"intro-box\">\n    The core grammatical challenge of this surah is tracking the subtle differences between the four negation clauses (vv. 2–5). Verses 2 and 5 use فِعْل مُضَارِع directly; verses 3 and 4 use a detached pronoun (أَنْتُمْ / أَنَا) as مُبْتَدَأ with an اسْم فَاعِل as خَبَر. Verse 4 is uniquely important: the مَا following عَابِدٌ is the مَفْعُول of an اسْم فَاعِل — a construction not seen in the other verses.\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 1</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">قُلْ يَـٰٓأَيُّهَا الْكَـٰفِرُونَ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"Say: O you disbelievers —\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">قُلْ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">فِعْل أَمْر مَبْنِيّ عَلَى السُّكُون</span> — a sound verb, so its أَمْر takes سُكُون. The <span class=\"term\">فَاعِل</span> is a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر وُجُوبًا</span> تَقْدِيرُهُ: أَنْتَ. The whole sentence is <span class=\"term\">ابْتِدَائِيَّة</span> — no syntactic position.</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">يَا</span> is a <span class=\"term\">حَرْف نِدَاء</span> (vocative particle). <span class=\"ar-inline\">أَيُّ</span> is the <span class=\"term\">مُنَادَى</span> (the one being called) — built on <span class=\"term\">ضَمّ</span> in the position of <span class=\"term\">نَصْب</span> as the مَفْعُول بِهِ of the deleted verb of calling (أُنَادِي). This is the standard rule: مُنَادَى is always in the position of نَصْب regardless of how it is vocalised. The attached <span class=\"ar-inline\">هَا</span> is a <span class=\"term\">حَرْف زَائِد لِلتَّنْبِيه</span> — it adds emphasis but has no grammatical position.</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">الْكَافِرُونَ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">صِفَة</span> for أَيُّ. The iʿrāb rule here is subtle: the صِفَة of أَيُّ follows its <span class=\"term\">لَفْظ</span> (its pronunciation/form) rather than its <span class=\"term\">مَحَلّ</span> (its underlying case position). Since أَيُّ is pronounced with ضَمَّة (مَبْنِيّ عَلَى الضَّمّ), the صِفَة الْكَافِرُونَ matches that and appears in رَفْع — marked by وَاو as a <span class=\"term\">جَمْع مُذَكَّر سَالِم</span>. The جُمْلَة نِدَاء is in the position of نَصْب as <span class=\"term\">مَقُول الْقَوْل</span> (what is said by قُلْ).</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">قُلْ</span><span>فِعْل أَمْر مَبْنِيّ عَلَى السُّكُون. فَاعِله ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر وُجُوبًا أَنْتَ. جُمْلَة \"قُلْ\" ابْتِدَائِيَّة — لَا مَحَلَّ لَهَا.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">يَا</span><span>حَرْف نِدَاء.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">أَيُّهَا</span><span>أَيُّ: مُنَادَى مَبْنِيّ عَلَى الضَّمّ فِي مَحَلِّ نَصْب مَفْعُول بِهِ لِفِعْل النِّدَاء الْمَحْذُوف. هَا: حَرْف زَائِد لِلتَّنْبِيه.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">الْكَافِرُونَ</span><span>صِفَة لِـ\"أَيُّ\" مَرْفُوعَة (تَبِعَهَا عَلَى اللَّفْظ). عَلَامَة رَفْعِهَا الْوَاو — جَمْع مُذَكَّر سَالِم. جُمْلَة النِّدَاء فِي مَحَلِّ نَصْب مَقُول الْقَوْل.</span></div>\n      </div>\n\n      <div class=\"callout\">\n        <div class=\"callout-title\">اتِّبَاع اللَّفْظ لَا الْمَحَلّ — following form, not position</div>\n        أَيُّ as مُنَادَى is مَبْنِيّ on ضَمَّة — it looks like رَفْع but occupies a نَصْب position. When a word following it (here: a صِفَة) must agree with it, Arabic has two options: follow the <span style=\"font-family:'Amiri',serif;font-size:15px;\">لَفْظ</span> (the actual form — ضَمَّة, so رَفْع) or follow the <span style=\"font-family:'Amiri',serif;font-size:15px;\">مَحَلّ</span> (the underlying position — نَصْب). Here the صِفَة الْكَافِرُونَ follows اللَّفْظ and appears in رَفْع. This is the standard choice for the صِفَة of أَيُّ in النِّدَاء.\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 2</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">لَآ أَعْبُدُ مَا تَعْبُدُونَ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"I do not worship what you worship —\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">لَا</span> is a <span class=\"term\">حَرْف نَفْي لَا عَمَل لَهُ</span> — a negation particle that does not govern the following verb (unlike لَمْ which apocopates). <span class=\"ar-inline\">أَعْبُدُ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">فِعْل مُضَارِع مَرْفُوع</span> by <span class=\"term\">ضَمَّة ظَاهِرَة</span>, with a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر وُجُوبًا</span> أَنَا as <span class=\"term\">فَاعِل</span> — obligatorily concealed because first-person verbs cannot take an explicit فَاعِل pronoun. The clause is in the position of نَصْب as part of <span class=\"term\">مَقُول الْقَوْل</span>.</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">مَا</span> is an <span class=\"term\">اسْم مَوْصُول</span> built on <span class=\"term\">سُكُون</span> in the position of <span class=\"term\">نَصْب</span> as <span class=\"term\">مَفْعُول بِهِ</span> of أَعْبُدُ. <span class=\"ar-inline\">تَعْبُدُونَ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">فِعْل مُضَارِع مَرْفُوع بِثُبُوتِ النُّون</span> with the وَاو as <span class=\"term\">فَاعِل</span> — this is the <span class=\"term\">صِلَة الْمَوْصُول</span>, no syntactic position.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">لَا</span><span>حَرْف نَفْي — لَا عَمَل لَهُ (لَا يَجْزِم وَلَا يَنْصِب).</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">أَعْبُدُ</span><span>فِعْل مُضَارِع مَرْفُوع بِضَمَّة ظَاهِرَة. فَاعِله ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر وُجُوبًا أَنَا. الْجُمْلَة فِي مَحَلِّ نَصْب مَقُول الْقَوْل.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">مَا</span><span>اسْم مَوْصُول مَبْنِيّ عَلَى السُّكُون فِي مَحَلِّ نَصْب مَفْعُول بِهِ.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">تَعْبُدُونَ</span><span>فِعْل مُضَارِع مَرْفُوع بِثُبُوتِ النُّون. الْوَاو: فَاعِل فِي مَحَلِّ رَفْع. الْجُمْلَة صِلَة الْمَوْصُول — لَا مَحَلَّ لَهَا.</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 3</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">وَلَآ أَنتُمْ عَـٰبِدُونَ مَآ أَعْبُدُ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"Nor are you worshippers of what I worship —\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>The structure shifts here. Instead of a direct verb, this verse uses a <span class=\"term\">جُمْلَة اسْمِيَّة</span>. <span class=\"ar-inline\">أَنْتُمْ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير رَفْع مُنْفَصِل</span> built on <span class=\"term\">سُكُون</span> in the position of <span class=\"term\">رَفْع</span> as the <span class=\"term\">مُبْتَدَأ</span>. <span class=\"ar-inline\">عَابِدُونَ</span> is the <span class=\"term\">خَبَر</span> in <span class=\"term\">رَفْع</span> — its marker is وَاو because it is a <span class=\"term\">جَمْع مُذَكَّر سَالِم</span>. <span class=\"ar-inline\">مَا أَعْبُدُ</span> carries the same iʿrāb as مَا تَعْبُدُونَ in verse 2: اسْم مَوْصُول in نَصْب as مَفْعُول بِهِ, with the clause أَعْبُدُ as its صِلَة (فَاعِل: ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر وُجُوبًا أَنَا). The whole clause \"وَلَا أَنْتُمْ عَابِدُونَ\" is coordinated on the clause of verse 2, in the position of نَصْب.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">وَلَا</span><span>وَاو: حَرْف عَطْف. لَا: حَرْف نَفْي — لَا عَمَل لَهُ.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">أَنْتُمْ</span><span>ضَمِير رَفْع مُنْفَصِل مَبْنِيّ عَلَى السُّكُون فِي مَحَلِّ رَفْع مُبْتَدَأ.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">عَابِدُونَ</span><span>خَبَر \"أَنْتُمْ\" مَرْفُوع بِالْوَاو — جَمْع مُذَكَّر سَالِم.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">مَا أَعْبُدُ</span><span>مَا: اسْم مَوْصُول فِي مَحَلِّ نَصْب مَفْعُول بِهِ. أَعْبُدُ: فِعْل مُضَارِع، فَاعِله ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر وُجُوبًا أَنَا — صِلَة الْمَوْصُول، لَا مَحَلَّ لَهَا.</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 4</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">وَلَآ أَنَا۠ عَابِدٌ مَّا عَبَدتُّمْ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"Nor will I be a worshipper of what you have worshipped —\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>The mirror image of verse 3 — but with two significant differences in iʿrāb. <span class=\"ar-inline\">أَنَا</span> is a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير رَفْع مُنْفَصِل</span> built on <span class=\"term\">سُكُون</span> as <span class=\"term\">مُبْتَدَأ</span>. <span class=\"ar-inline\">عَابِدٌ</span> is the <span class=\"term\">خَبَر</span> — but unlike عَابِدُونَ in verse 3, this is a singular <span class=\"term\">اسْم فَاعِل</span> in رَفْع by <span class=\"term\">ضَمَّة ظَاهِرَة</span> (not the plural form).</p>\n\n      <p>The crucial iʿrāb point: <span class=\"ar-inline\">مَا</span> here is an <span class=\"term\">اسْم مَوْصُول</span> in the position of <span class=\"term\">نَصْب</span> as <span class=\"term\">مَفْعُول بِهِ</span> — but of the <span class=\"term\">اسْم الْفَاعِل عَابِدٌ</span>, not of a verb. This is a key Arabic grammar rule: an اسْم فَاعِل that is used with the meaning of present or future tense can govern a مَفْعُول بِهِ in نَصْب, just as its root verb would. So عَابِدٌ acts as the agent noun of عَبَدَ and takes مَا as its object.</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">عَبَدْتُمْ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">فِعْل مَاضٍ مَبْنِيّ عَلَى السُّكُون</span> (connected to moving rafʿ pronoun تُمْ); the تَاء is <span class=\"term\">فَاعِل</span> in رَفْع; the مِيم marks plurality. This past-tense verb is the <span class=\"term\">صِلَة الْمَوْصُول</span> for مَا — no syntactic position. The whole nominal sentence \"أَنَا عَابِدٌ\" is coordinated on what preceded and carries no syntactic position.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">أَنَا</span><span>ضَمِير رَفْع مُنْفَصِل مَبْنِيّ عَلَى السُّكُون فِي مَحَلِّ رَفْع مُبْتَدَأ.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">عَابِدٌ</span><span>خَبَر \"أَنَا\" مَرْفُوع بِضَمَّة ظَاهِرَة. اسْم فَاعِل يَعْمَل عَمَل فِعْلِهِ.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">مَا</span><span>اسْم مَوْصُول مَبْنِيّ عَلَى السُّكُون فِي مَحَلِّ نَصْب مَفْعُول بِهِ لِاسْم الْفَاعِل \"عَابِدٌ\".</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">عَبَدْتُمْ</span><span>فِعْل مَاضٍ مَبْنِيّ عَلَى السُّكُون لِاتِّصَالِهِ بِضَمِير رَفْع مُتَحَرِّك. التَّاء: فَاعِل فِي مَحَلِّ رَفْع. الْمِيم: لِلْجَمَاعَة. الْجُمْلَة صِلَة الْمَوْصُول — لَا مَحَلَّ لَهَا.</span></div>\n      </div>\n\n      <div class=\"callout\">\n        <div class=\"callout-title\">اسْم الْفَاعِل يَعْمَل عَمَل فِعْلِهِ — the active participle as verb</div>\n        An اسْم فَاعِل (active participle) can govern a مَفْعُول بِهِ in نَصْب — exactly like its root verb — under two conditions: it must refer to present or future time (not past), and it should carry the definite article أَلْ or be used in context that implies the present/future. عَابِدٌ here refers to a state the speaker will never enter (\"I am not one who will worship\"), so it governs مَا as its مَفْعُول. This is distinct from verses 2–3 where the verb أَعْبُدُ / عَابِدُونَ is used — there the مَفْعُول belongs to the verb directly.\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 5</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">وَلَآ أَنتُمْ عَـٰبِدُونَ مَآ أَعْبُدُ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"Nor are you worshippers of what I worship.\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>This verse is identical to verse 3 in wording and carries the same full iʿrāb: وَلَا (عَطْف + نَفْي) + أَنْتُمْ (مُبْتَدَأ) + عَابِدُونَ (خَبَر، رَفْع بِالْوَاو، جَمْع مُذَكَّر سَالِم) + مَا أَعْبُدُ (اسْم مَوْصُول فِي نَصْب مَفْعُول بِهِ + صِلَة). The repetition here is rhetorical, not grammatical — it seals the declaration with a final statement directed at the disbelievers.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">الْآيَة كَامِلَة</span><span>تُعْرَب إِعْرَاب الْآيَة الثَّالِثَة — نَفْس الْبِنَاء الإِعْرَابِيّ بِالْكَامِل.</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 6</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">لَكُمْ دِينُكُمْ وَلِىَ دِينِ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"For you is your religion, and for me is my religion.\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>The closing verse is a pair of <span class=\"term\">جُمَل اسْمِيَّة</span> with a deliberately inverted word order. In normal Arabic, the مُبْتَدَأ comes first and the خَبَر second. Here the order is reversed: the <span class=\"term\">جَارّ وَمَجْرُور</span> comes first as a <span class=\"term\">خَبَر مُقَدَّم</span> (fronted predicate), and the noun that is logically the subject comes second as a <span class=\"term\">مُبْتَدَأ مُؤَخَّر</span> (deferred subject).</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">لَكُمْ</span> is the <span class=\"term\">خَبَر مُقَدَّم</span> — جَارّ وَمَجْرُور related to the deleted verb of existence. <span class=\"ar-inline\">دِينُكُمْ</span> is the <span class=\"term\">مُبْتَدَأ مُؤَخَّر</span> in <span class=\"term\">رَفْع</span> by <span class=\"term\">ضَمَّة ظَاهِرَة</span>; the كَاف is a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير مُتَّصِل</span> in <span class=\"term\">جَرّ</span> by إِضَافَة; the مِيم marks plurality.</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">وَلِيَ دِينِ</span> is coordinated on the first clause by وَاو and carries the same iʿrāb. The critical point: <span class=\"ar-inline\">دِينِ</span> is written and read with a كَسْرَة at the end — this is the <span class=\"term\">يَاء الْإِضَافَة الْمَحْذُوفَة</span>. The full form is دِينِي (my religion), but the يَاء is deleted in the written text of the Qurʾān while the كَسْرَة remains as its trace. The يَاء itself is a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير مُتَّصِل</span> in <span class=\"term\">جَرّ</span> by إِضَافَة. The whole clause is <span class=\"term\">اسْتِئْنَافِيَّة</span> — no syntactic position.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">لَكُمْ</span><span>جَارّ وَمَجْرُور — خَبَر مُقَدَّم مُتَعَلِّق بِمَحْذُوف.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">دِينُكُمْ</span><span>مُبْتَدَأ مُؤَخَّر مَرْفُوع بِضَمَّة ظَاهِرَة. الْكَاف: ضَمِير مُتَّصِل فِي مَحَلِّ جَرّ بِالْإِضَافَة. الْمِيم: لِلْجَمَاعَة.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">وَلِيَ دِينِ</span><span>مَعْطُوفَة بِالْوَاو — تُعْرَب إِعْرَابَهَا. الْيَاء الْمَحْذُوفَة مِن \"دِينِ\": ضَمِير مُتَّصِل فِي مَحَلِّ جَرّ بِالْإِضَافَة — تَقْدِيرُهَا: دِينِي.</span></div>\n      </div>\n\n      <div class=\"callout\">\n        <div class=\"callout-title\">يَاء الْإِضَافَة الْمَحْذُوفَة — the deleted possessive يَاء</div>\n        In Qurʾānic orthography, the first-person possessive يَاء (my) is sometimes written and sometimes deleted, with only the كَسْرَة left as a trace. دِينِ = دِينِي with the يَاء dropped. The كَسْرَة on the نُون is not the جَرّ marker of the noun — دِين itself is the مُبْتَدَأ مُؤَخَّر in رَفْع — but rather the remaining vowel of the deleted يَاء الْإِضَافَة. This deletion is common in Qurʾānic Arabic and appears elsewhere (e.g. يَا عِبَادِ، وَلِيَ نَعْجَةٌ).\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <hr class=\"divider\">\n\n  <div class=\"theme-box\">\n    <h3>Structural summary</h3>\n    <div class=\"theme-grid\">\n      <div class=\"theme-card\">\n        <div class=\"theme-card-label\">Verse 1</div>\n        فِعْل أَمْر + نِدَاء: أَيُّهَا (مُنَادَى مَبْنِيّ عَلَى الضَّمّ، فِي مَحَلِّ نَصْب) + صِفَة تَبِعَتْ عَلَى اللَّفْظ (رَفْع by وَاو). جُمْلَة النِّدَاء = مَقُول الْقَوْل.\n      </div>\n      <div class=\"theme-card\">\n        <div class=\"theme-card-label\">Verses 2 & 5</div>\n        لَا + فِعْل مُضَارِع directly. مَا = اسْم مَوْصُول, مَفْعُول بِهِ of the verb. فَاعِل: ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر وُجُوبًا.\n      </div>\n      <div class=\"theme-card\">\n        <div class=\"theme-card-label\">Verses 3 & 4</div>\n        لَا + ضَمِير مُنْفَصِل (مُبْتَدَأ) + اسْم فَاعِل (خَبَر). Key contrast: v.3 عَابِدُونَ (جَمْع — مَفْعُول of plural noun); v.4 عَابِدٌ (مُفْرَد اسْم فَاعِل governing مَا as its own مَفْعُول بِهِ).\n      </div>\n      <div class=\"theme-card\">\n        <div class=\"theme-card-label\">Verse 6</div>\n        خَبَر مُقَدَّم + مُبْتَدَأ مُؤَخَّر (inverted nominal sentence). يَاء الْإِضَافَة مَحْذُوفَة in دِينِ — كَسْرَة is its trace, not the noun's own جَرّ marker.\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n</div>","kawthar":"<div class=\"book\">\n\n  <div class=\"surah-header\">\n    <div class=\"surah-label\">Sūrah 108 · Makkī · 3 verses</div>\n    <div class=\"surah-title-en\">Abundance</div>\n    <div class=\"surah-title-ar\">سُورَةُ الْكَوْثَرِ</div>\n    <div class=\"surah-meta\">The shortest sūrah in the Qurʾān and a grammatical gem. Each verse introduces a distinct structure: an إِنَّ-sentence with a verbal خَبَر and two مَفْعُولَيْن (v.1); two فِعْل أَمْر verbs — one built on حَذْف حَرْف الْعِلَّة, the other on سُكُون (v.2); and an إِنَّ-sentence where هُوَ serves as a ضَمِير فَصْل before the خَبَر (v.3).</div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"intro-box\">\n    The surah moves from divine gift (v.1) to commanded gratitude (v.2) to divine verdict on the enemy (v.3). Grammatically: gift = إِنَّ + فِعْل مَاضٍ as خَبَر; command = two أَمْر verbs; verdict = إِنَّ + ضَمِير فَصْل + خَبَر. The ضَمِير فَصْل هُوَ in verse 3 is the single most important iʿrāb point to master here.\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 1</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">إِنَّآ أَعْطَيْنَـٰكَ الْكَوْثَرَ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"Indeed We have given you abundance —\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">إِنَّا</span> is composed of <span class=\"term\">إِنَّ</span> — a <span class=\"term\">حَرْف تَوْكِيد مُشَبَّه بِالْفِعْل</span> — and the attached <span class=\"ar-inline\">نَا</span>, which is a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير مُتَّصِل</span> built on <span class=\"term\">سُكُون</span> in the position of <span class=\"term\">نَصْب</span> as the <span class=\"term\">اسْم إِنَّ</span>. This نَا is the pronoun of the royal/majestic plural, referring to God.</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">أَعْطَيْنَاكَ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">فِعْل مَاضٍ مَبْنِيّ عَلَى السُّكُون</span> — the sukūn because it is connected to the moving rafʿ pronoun نَا (same rule as رَأَيْتَ in Sūrat al-Māʿūn). The attached <span class=\"ar-inline\">نَا</span> here is the <span class=\"term\">فَاعِل</span> in <span class=\"term\">رَفْع</span> position. The attached <span class=\"ar-inline\">كَاف</span> is a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير مُتَّصِل</span> built on <span class=\"term\">فَتْح</span> in the position of <span class=\"term\">نَصْب</span> as the <span class=\"term\">مَفْعُول بِهِ أَوَّل</span>.</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">الْكَوْثَرَ</span> is the <span class=\"term\">مَفْعُول بِهِ ثَانٍ</span> in <span class=\"term\">نَصْب</span> by <span class=\"term\">فَتْحَة ظَاهِرَة</span>. The verb أَعْطَى is one of the verbs that governs two objects in Arabic (<span class=\"term\">يَنْصِب مَفْعُولَيْن</span>): the recipient (كَاف = you) and the thing given (الْكَوْثَرَ = abundance). The verbal clause أَعْطَيْنَاكَ الْكَوْثَرَ is in the position of <span class=\"term\">رَفْع</span> as the <span class=\"term\">خَبَر إِنَّ</span>. The whole إِنَّ-sentence is <span class=\"term\">ابْتِدَائِيَّة</span> — no syntactic position.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">إِنَّا</span><span>إِنَّ: حَرْف تَوْكِيد مُشَبَّه بِالْفِعْل. نَا: ضَمِير مُتَّصِل مَبْنِيّ عَلَى السُّكُون فِي مَحَلِّ نَصْب اسْم \"إِنَّ\".</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">أَعْطَيْنَاكَ</span><span>فِعْل مَاضٍ مَبْنِيّ عَلَى السُّكُون لِاتِّصَالِهِ بِضَمِير رَفْع مُتَحَرِّك. نَا: فَاعِل فِي مَحَلِّ رَفْع. الْكَاف: مَفْعُول بِهِ أَوَّل فِي مَحَلِّ نَصْب.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">الْكَوْثَرَ</span><span>مَفْعُول بِهِ ثَانٍ مَنْصُوب بِفَتْحَة ظَاهِرَة.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">جُمْلَة أَعْطَيْنَاكَ</span><span>فِي مَحَلِّ رَفْع خَبَر \"إِنَّ\". جُمْلَة \"إِنَّ\" وَاسْمُهَا وَخَبَرُهَا ابْتِدَائِيَّة — لَا مَحَلَّ لَهَا.</span></div>\n      </div>\n\n      <div class=\"callout\">\n        <div class=\"callout-title\">نَا — اسْم إِنَّ here, فَاعِل in the خَبَر — two نَا in one sentence</div>\n        Notice that نَا appears twice in this verse with two different grammatical roles. The first نَا (in إِنَّا) is the اسْم إِنَّ in نَصْب. The second نَا (in أَعْطَيْنَا) is the فَاعِل of the verb in رَفْع. Both refer to God. The distinction is essential: إِنَّ governs its own اسْم; the verbal خَبَر then has its own فَاعِل separately.\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 2</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">فَصَلِّ لِرَبِّكَ وَانْحَرْ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"So pray to your Lord and sacrifice.\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>The <span class=\"term\">فَاء</span> is a <span class=\"term\">حَرْف اسْتِئْنَاف</span> opening a fresh command that follows naturally from the gift announced in verse 1. The verse contains two <span class=\"term\">فِعْل أَمْر</span> verbs — and crucially, each is built differently.</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">صَلِّ</span> comes from the root صَلَّى (a defective verb whose final root letter is يَاء). When the فِعْل أَمْر is formed from a defective verb (<span class=\"term\">الْفِعْل النَّاقِص</span>), its building-block is <span class=\"term\">حَذْف حَرْف الْعِلَّة</span> — the weak letter is deleted. So صَلِّ is مَبْنِيّ on this deletion. Compare to تَرَ in Sūrat al-Fīl — the same principle of حَذْف applies, but there it was triggered by لَمْ (جَزْم), while here it is the inherent form of the أَمْر from a ناقص verb. The <span class=\"term\">فَاعِل</span> is a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر وُجُوبًا</span> — obligatorily concealed — تَقْدِيرُهُ: أَنْتَ, because فِعْل أَمْر always addresses the second person. <span class=\"ar-inline\">لِرَبِّكَ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">جَارّ وَمَجْرُور</span> <span class=\"term\">مُتَعَلِّق</span> بِـ\"صَلِّ\"; the كَاف is a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير مُتَّصِل</span> in <span class=\"term\">جَرّ</span> by <span class=\"term\">إِضَافَة</span>.</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">وَانْحَرْ</span>: the <span class=\"term\">وَاو</span> is a <span class=\"term\">حَرْف عَطْف</span>. <span class=\"ar-inline\">انْحَرْ</span> comes from نَحَرَ, a sound verb (<span class=\"term\">الْفِعْل الصَّحِيح</span>). The فِعْل أَمْر from a sound verb is built on <span class=\"term\">سُكُون</span> on the final letter. The فَاعِل is again a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر وُجُوبًا</span> أَنْتَ. Both verb clauses are <span class=\"term\">اسْتِئْنَافِيَّة</span> / coordinated — no syntactic position.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">فَ</span><span>حَرْف اسْتِئْنَاف.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">صَلِّ</span><span>فِعْل أَمْر مَبْنِيّ عَلَى حَذْف حَرْف الْعِلَّة (الْفِعْل النَّاقِص). فَاعِله ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر وُجُوبًا تَقْدِيرُهُ: أَنْتَ. الْجُمْلَة اسْتِئْنَافِيَّة — لَا مَحَلَّ لَهَا.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">لِرَبِّكَ</span><span>جَارّ وَمَجْرُور مُتَعَلِّقَان بِـ\"صَلِّ\". الْكَاف: ضَمِير مُتَّصِل فِي مَحَلِّ جَرّ بِالْإِضَافَة.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">وَانْحَرْ</span><span>وَاو: حَرْف عَطْف. انْحَرْ: فِعْل أَمْر مَبْنِيّ عَلَى السُّكُون (الْفِعْل الصَّحِيح). فَاعِله ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر وُجُوبًا أَنْتَ. الْجُمْلَة مَعْطُوفَة عَلَى \"صَلِّ\" — لَا مَحَلَّ لَهَا.</span></div>\n      </div>\n\n      <div class=\"callout\">\n        <div class=\"callout-title\">بِنَاء فِعْل الْأَمْر — sound verb vs defective verb</div>\n        The فِعْل أَمْر is مَبْنِيّ (indeclinable) — it does not change for case. But its building-block differs by verb type:\n        <br>الصَّحِيح (sound): built on سُكُون — اكْتُبْ، انْحَرْ، اجْلِسْ.\n        <br>النَّاقِص (defective, ending in وَاو/يَاء): built on حَذْف حَرْف الْعِلَّة — صَلِّ (from صَلَّى)، ادْعُ (from دَعَا)، اقْضِ (from قَضَى).\n        <br>الْمُضَعَّف (doubled): built on سُكُون — مُدَّ، رُدَّ.\n        This verse gives you both the صَحِيح and النَّاقِص types side by side.\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 3</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">إِنَّ شَانِئَكَ هُوَ الْأَبْتَرُ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"Indeed your enemy — he is the one cut off.\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">إِنَّ</span> is again the <span class=\"term\">حَرْف تَوْكِيد مُشَبَّه بِالْفِعْل</span>. <span class=\"ar-inline\">شَانِئَكَ</span> is the <span class=\"term\">اسْم إِنَّ</span> in <span class=\"term\">نَصْب</span> by <span class=\"term\">فَتْحَة ظَاهِرَة</span>; it is a <span class=\"term\">اسْم فَاعِل</span> (active participle) from شَنَأَ (to hate/despise), and is a <span class=\"term\">مُضَاف</span>; the attached <span class=\"ar-inline\">كَاف</span> is a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير مُتَّصِل</span> in <span class=\"term\">جَرّ</span> by <span class=\"term\">إِضَافَة</span>.</p>\n\n      <p>Now the most important iʿrāb point: <span class=\"ar-inline\">هُوَ</span>. This is a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير رَفْع مُنْفَصِل</span> built on <span class=\"term\">فَتْح</span>, but it is NOT a مُبْتَدَأ here — it is a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير فَصْل</span> (separating/emphasising pronoun). A ضَمِير فَصْل has no syntactic position of its own (لَا مَحَلَّ لَهُ مِن الْإِعْرَاب). Its function is purely rhetorical and structural: it separates the اسْم إِنَّ from its خَبَر, preventing the reader from parsing the خَبَر as a صِفَة, and adding the emphasis \"he — specifically, exclusively — is the one cut off.\"</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">الْأَبْتَرُ</span> is the <span class=\"term\">خَبَر إِنَّ</span> in <span class=\"term\">رَفْع</span> by <span class=\"term\">ضَمَّة ظَاهِرَة</span>. The whole إِنَّ-sentence is <span class=\"term\">اسْتِئْنَافِيَّة</span> — no syntactic position.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">إِنَّ</span><span>حَرْف تَوْكِيد مُشَبَّه بِالْفِعْل.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">شَانِئَكَ</span><span>اسْم \"إِنَّ\" مَنْصُوب بِفَتْحَة ظَاهِرَة. مُضَاف. الْكَاف: ضَمِير مُتَّصِل فِي مَحَلِّ جَرّ بِالْإِضَافَة.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">هُوَ</span><span>ضَمِير فَصْل مَبْنِيّ عَلَى الْفَتْح — لَا مَحَلَّ لَهُ مِن الْإِعْرَاب. وَظِيفَتُهُ: التَّوْكِيد وَالْفَصْل بَيْن الاسم وَالْخَبَر.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">الْأَبْتَرُ</span><span>خَبَر \"إِنَّ\" مَرْفُوع بِضَمَّة ظَاهِرَة. الْجُمْلَة اسْتِئْنَافِيَّة — لَا مَحَلَّ لَهَا.</span></div>\n      </div>\n\n      <div class=\"callout\">\n        <div class=\"callout-title\">ضَمِير الْفَصْل — what it is and why it has no grammatical position</div>\n        A ضَمِير فَصْل appears between a مُبْتَدَأ and its خَبَر (or between اسْم إِنَّ and its خَبَر) when both are definite. It does three things:\n        <br>1. Confirms the following word is the خَبَر, not a صِفَة.\n        <br>2. Adds restriction: \"he — and no one else.\"\n        <br>3. Signals that the خَبَر is a new piece of information, not a description already known.\n        <br>Because it performs a structural function rather than filling a syntactic slot, it has no محل إعراب — it is analysed as مَبْنِيّ without a position. Compare هُوَ as مُبْتَدَأ in Sūrat al-Māʿūn vv. 5–6, where it genuinely occupies a رَفْع position inside the صِلَة — that is different.\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <hr class=\"divider\">\n\n  <div class=\"theme-box\">\n    <h3>Structural summary</h3>\n    <div class=\"theme-grid\">\n      <div class=\"theme-card\">\n        <div class=\"theme-card-label\">Verse 1</div>\n        إِنَّ + نَا (اسْم في نَصْب) + فِعْل مَاضٍ as خَبَر (in رَفْع position). فِعْل مَبْنِيّ عَلَى السُّكُون (moving rafʿ pronoun). أَعْطَى governs two مَفْعُولَيْن: كَاف (recipient) + الْكَوْثَرَ (thing given).\n      </div>\n      <div class=\"theme-card\">\n        <div class=\"theme-card-label\">Verse 2</div>\n        Two فِعْل أَمْر side by side: صَلِّ (ناقص → حَذْف حَرْف الْعِلَّة) and انْحَرْ (صَحِيح → سُكُون). Both with ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر وُجُوبًا أَنْتَ.\n      </div>\n      <div class=\"theme-card\">\n        <div class=\"theme-card-label\">Verse 3</div>\n        إِنَّ + اسْم فَاعِل as اسْم إِنَّ + ضَمِير فَصْل هُوَ (لَا مَحَلَّ لَهُ) + خَبَر مَرْفُوع. The ضَمِير فَصْل is the key iʿrāb point of the surah.\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n</div>","quraysh":"<div class=\"book\">\n\n  <div class=\"surah-header\">\n    <div class=\"surah-label\">Sūrah 106 · Makkī · 4 verses</div>\n    <div class=\"surah-title-en\">Quraysh</div>\n    <div class=\"surah-title-ar\">سُورَةُ قُرَيْشٍ</div>\n    <div class=\"surah-meta\">One of the most syntactically unusual sūrahs in the Qurʾān. The first two verses are a single <span style=\"font-family:'Amiri',serif;font-size:15px;\">جَارّ وَمَجْرُور</span> suspended in the air — its anchor verb does not appear until verse 3. This long-range grammatical dependency, spanning two full verses, is the central iʿrāb challenge of the surah.</div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"intro-box\">\n    The surah is essentially one conditional-response structure: \"For the familiarity of Quraysh... let them worship.\" Verses 1–2 are the motivating cause (expressed as a جَارّ وَمَجْرُور with a بَدَل), and verse 3 is the commanded response (لَام الْأَمْر). Verse 4 then qualifies the object of worship with a صِلَة describing God's two great blessings.\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 1</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">لِإِيلَٰفِ قُرَيْشٍ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"For the familiarity of Quraysh —\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">لِإِيلَافِ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">جَارّ وَمَجْرُور</span> — the لَام is a <span class=\"term\">حَرْف جَرّ</span> and <span class=\"ar-inline\">إِيلَافِ</span> is the noun in <span class=\"term\">جَرّ</span> by it. The critical iʿrāb question is: what is this prepositional phrase related to? Its <span class=\"term\">مُتَعَلَّق</span> is the verb <span class=\"ar-inline\">فَلْيَعْبُدُوا</span> which does not appear until verse 3. This is one of the most striking examples of <span class=\"term\">تَقْدِيم</span> (fronting) in the Qurʾān — the cause is stated before the commanded response, for rhetorical emphasis on the reason. The implied logic: \"Because of this blessing, let them worship.\"</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">إِيلَافِ</span> is itself a <span class=\"term\">مُضَاف</span>, and <span class=\"ar-inline\">قُرَيْشٍ</span> is its <span class=\"term\">مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ</span> in <span class=\"term\">جَرّ</span> by <span class=\"term\">كَسْرَة ظَاهِرَة</span>. Note that قُرَيْش is a proper noun (<span class=\"term\">اسْم عَلَم</span>) that is <span class=\"term\">مَصْرُوف</span> (fully declinable, taking tanwīn) — it does not fall under the rules of <span class=\"term\">الْمَمْنُوع مِن الصَّرْف</span>.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">لِإِيلَافِ</span><span>لَام: حَرْف جَرّ. إِيلَافِ: اسْم مَجْرُور بِاللَّام. الْجَارّ وَالْمَجْرُور مُتَعَلِّقَان بِـ\"فَلْيَعْبُدُوا\" فِي الْآيَة الثَّالِثَة. إِيلَافِ: مُضَاف.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">قُرَيْشٍ</span><span>مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ مَجْرُور بِكَسْرَة ظَاهِرَة.</span></div>\n      </div>\n\n      <div class=\"callout\">\n        <div class=\"callout-title\">لِإِيلَافِ — a جَارّ وَمَجْرُور suspended across two verses</div>\n        The لَام here is called <span style=\"font-family:'Amiri',serif;font-size:15px;\">لَام التَّعْلِيل</span> — the lām of cause or reason (\"for the sake of / because of\"). Its مُتَعَلَّق (the word it grammatically hangs on) is فَلْيَعْبُدُوا in verse 3. Classical grammarians note this as an intentional rhetorical delay — by stating the reason first and commanding worship second, the surah forces the listener to hold the motivation in mind before the command lands.\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 2</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">إِۦلَٰفِهِمْ رِحْلَةَ الشِّتَآءِ وَالصَّيْفِ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"Their familiarity with the journey of winter and summer —\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">إِيلَافِهِمْ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">بَدَل</span> from <span class=\"ar-inline\">إِيلَافِ</span> in verse 1, following it in <span class=\"term\">جَرّ</span> by <span class=\"term\">كَسْرَة</span>. The substitution here is <span class=\"term\">بَدَل كُلٍّ مِن كُلٍّ</span> — a full appositive that re-states the same noun with added specification (the pronoun هِم clarifies whose familiarity is meant). The attached <span class=\"ar-inline\">هَاء</span> is a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير مُتَّصِل</span> in <span class=\"term\">جَرّ</span> by <span class=\"term\">إِضَافَة</span>; the <span class=\"term\">مِيم</span> marks plurality.</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">رِحْلَةَ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">مَفْعُول بِهِ لِلْمَصْدَر</span> — a direct object of the verbal noun <span class=\"ar-inline\">إِيلَافِ</span>. This is one of the properties of Arabic <span class=\"term\">مَصَادِر</span>: they retain the ability of their root verb to take objects. Since إِيلَاف comes from the verb آلَفَ (to make familiar with / to habituate to), it can take a مَفْعُول بِهِ just as the verb would. <span class=\"ar-inline\">رِحْلَةَ</span> is therefore in <span class=\"term\">نَصْب</span> by <span class=\"term\">فَتْحَة ظَاهِرَة</span>, and is itself a <span class=\"term\">مُضَاف</span>.</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">الشِّتَاءِ</span> is the <span class=\"term\">مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ</span> of رِحْلَةَ in <span class=\"term\">جَرّ</span> by <span class=\"term\">كَسْرَة ظَاهِرَة</span>. <span class=\"ar-inline\">وَالصَّيْفِ</span> is coordinated on الشِّتَاءِ by <span class=\"term\">وَاو عَطْف</span>, matching it in <span class=\"term\">جَرّ</span> by <span class=\"term\">كَسْرَة</span>.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">إِيلَافِهِمْ</span><span>بَدَل مِن \"إِيلَافِ\" الأُولَى مَجْرُور بِكَسْرَة. الْهَاء: ضَمِير مُتَّصِل فِي مَحَلِّ جَرّ بِالْإِضَافَة. الْمِيم: لِلْجَمَاعَة.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">رِحْلَةَ</span><span>مَفْعُول بِهِ لِلْمَصْدَر \"إِيلَاف\" مَنْصُوب بِفَتْحَة ظَاهِرَة. مُضَاف.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">الشِّتَاءِ</span><span>مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ مَجْرُور بِكَسْرَة ظَاهِرَة.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">وَالصَّيْفِ</span><span>وَاو: حَرْف عَطْف. الصَّيْف: اسْم مَعْطُوف عَلَى \"الشِّتَاء\" مَجْرُور بِكَسْرَة.</span></div>\n      </div>\n\n      <div class=\"callout\">\n        <div class=\"callout-title\">الْمَصْدَر يَعْمَل عَمَل فِعْلِهِ — the verbal noun takes objects</div>\n        In Arabic, a <span style=\"font-family:'Amiri',serif;font-size:15px;\">مَصْدَر</span> (verbal noun) inherits the grammatical behaviour of its root verb, including the ability to take a <span style=\"font-family:'Amiri',serif;font-size:15px;\">مَفْعُول بِهِ</span> in نَصْب and a فَاعِل in رَفْع (or as a مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ). So إِيلَافِهِمْ رِحْلَةَ is grammatically equivalent to: أَنْ يُؤَلِّفَهُمُ اللَّهُ الرِّحْلَةَ — \"that God habituated them to the journey.\" The مَصْدَر takes رِحْلَةَ as its object (مَفْعُول بِهِ) and هِمْ as its مَفْعُول أَوَّل embedded in the إِضَافَة.\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 3</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">فَلْيَعْبُدُوا رَبَّ هَٰذَا الْبَيْتِ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"Let them worship the Lord of this House —\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>The <span class=\"term\">فَاء</span> is a <span class=\"term\">حَرْف</span> occurring in the answer to an implied condition (<span class=\"term\">جَوَاب شَرْط مُقَدَّر</span>). The full implied logic: \"If God's blessings upon them are innumerable — and if they cannot worship Him for all blessings — then let them at least worship Him for this one.\" The فَاء signals that the command is the natural consequence of what preceded.</p>\n\n      <p>The <span class=\"term\">لَام</span> of <span class=\"ar-inline\">لْيَعْبُدُوا</span> is <span class=\"term\">لَام الْأَمْر</span> — a <span class=\"term\">حَرْف جَزْم</span> that makes the following مُضَارِع an imperative. <span class=\"ar-inline\">يَعْبُدُوا</span> is a <span class=\"term\">فِعْل مُضَارِع مَجْزُوم</span> by لَام الْأَمْر; its <span class=\"term\">عَلَامَة جَزْم</span> is <span class=\"term\">حَذْف النُّون</span> — the نُون of the masculine sound plural (which is present in the indicative يَعْبُدُونَ) is deleted under جَزْم. The <span class=\"ar-inline\">وَاو</span> is the <span class=\"term\">فَاعِل</span> in <span class=\"term\">رَفْع</span> position; the <span class=\"ar-inline\">أَلِف</span> is <span class=\"term\">أَلِف فَارِقَة</span>.</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">رَبَّ</span> is the <span class=\"term\">مَفْعُول بِهِ</span> of يَعْبُدُوا in <span class=\"term\">نَصْب</span> by <span class=\"term\">فَتْحَة ظَاهِرَة</span>, and is a <span class=\"term\">مُضَاف</span>. Its <span class=\"term\">مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ</span> is the demonstrative phrase <span class=\"ar-inline\">هَذَا</span>: the <span class=\"term\">هَاء</span> is a <span class=\"term\">حَرْف تَنْبِيه</span> (an attention-drawing particle), and <span class=\"ar-inline\">ذَا</span> is the <span class=\"term\">اسْم إِشَارَة</span> built on <span class=\"term\">سُكُون</span> in the position of <span class=\"term\">جَرّ</span> by <span class=\"term\">إِضَافَة</span>.</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">الْبَيْتِ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">بَدَل</span> from the اسْم إِشَارَة <span class=\"ar-inline\">ذَا</span>, matching it in <span class=\"term\">جَرّ</span> by <span class=\"term\">كَسْرَة</span>. The substitution clarifies what the demonstrative points to.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">فَ</span><span>حَرْف وَاقِع فِي جَوَاب شَرْط مُقَدَّر.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">لْـ</span><span>لَام الْأَمْر — حَرْف جَزْم.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">يَعْبُدُوا</span><span>فِعْل مُضَارِع مَجْزُوم بِلَام الْأَمْر. عَلَامَة جَزْمِهِ: حَذْف النُّون. الْوَاو: فَاعِل فِي مَحَلِّ رَفْع. الْأَلِف: فَارِقَة.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">رَبَّ</span><span>مَفْعُول بِهِ مَنْصُوب بِفَتْحَة ظَاهِرَة. مُضَاف.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">هَذَا</span><span>هَا: حَرْف تَنْبِيه. ذَا: اسْم إِشَارَة مَبْنِيّ عَلَى السُّكُون فِي مَحَلِّ جَرّ بِالْإِضَافَة.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">الْبَيْتِ</span><span>بَدَل مِن اسْم الْإِشَارَة مَجْرُور بِكَسْرَة.</span></div>\n      </div>\n\n      <div class=\"callout\">\n        <div class=\"callout-title\">لَام الْأَمْر — جَزْم by حَذْف النُّون</div>\n        When لَام الْأَمْر apocopates a sound masculine plural verb (on the pattern يَفْعَلُونَ), the نُون of the plural is deleted: يَعْبُدُونَ → يَعْبُدُوا. This is exactly parallel to what happens when the subjunctive أَنْ apocopates the same verb. The وَاو remains as the فَاعِل; the أَلِف فَارِقَة is added orthographically. Compare this to حَذْف حَرْف الْعِلَّة in defective verbs (Sūrat al-Fīl v.1) — both are forms of حَذْف as a marker of جَزْم, but the deleted element differs.\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 4</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">الَّذِىٓ أَطْعَمَهُم مِّن جُوعٍ وَءَامَنَهُم مِّنْ خَوْفٍ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"Who fed them against hunger and made them safe from fear.\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">الَّذِي</span> is an <span class=\"term\">اسْم مَوْصُول</span> built on <span class=\"term\">سُكُون</span>, in the position of <span class=\"term\">نَصْب</span> as a <span class=\"term\">صِفَة</span> for <span class=\"ar-inline\">رَبَّ</span> — it qualifies the Lord with two defining attributes. The <span class=\"term\">صِلَة الْمَوْصُول</span> that follows it has no syntactic position of its own.</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">أَطْعَمَهُمْ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">فِعْل مَاضٍ</span> built on <span class=\"term\">فَتْح</span>, with a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر جَوَازًا</span> هُوَ as <span class=\"term\">فَاعِل</span>. The attached <span class=\"ar-inline\">هَاء</span> is a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير مُتَّصِل</span> in <span class=\"term\">نَصْب</span> as <span class=\"term\">مَفْعُول بِهِ</span>; the <span class=\"term\">مِيم</span> marks plurality. <span class=\"ar-inline\">مِن جُوعٍ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">جَارّ وَمَجْرُور</span> <span class=\"term\">مُتَعَلِّق</span> بِـ\"أَطْعَمَهُمْ\" — the مِن here indicates the cause or the state they were rescued from (\"fed them against/from hunger\").</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">وَآمَنَهُمْ مِنْ خَوْفٍ</span> is fully coordinated on <span class=\"ar-inline\">أَطْعَمَهُمْ مِنْ جُوعٍ</span> by <span class=\"term\">وَاو عَطْف</span> and carries the identical iʿrāb throughout. Both clauses are the <span class=\"term\">صِلَة الْمَوْصُول</span> — the first (أَطْعَمَهُمْ) and its coordinate (آمَنَهُمْ) together — each with no syntactic position.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">الَّذِي</span><span>اسْم مَوْصُول مَبْنِيّ عَلَى السُّكُون فِي مَحَلِّ نَصْب صِفَة لِـ\"رَبَّ\".</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">أَطْعَمَهُمْ</span><span>فِعْل مَاضٍ مَبْنِيّ عَلَى الْفَتْح. فَاعِله ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر جَوَازًا هُوَ. الْهَاء: مَفْعُول بِهِ فِي مَحَلِّ نَصْب. الْمِيم: لِلْجَمَاعَة. الْجُمْلَة صِلَة الْمَوْصُول — لَا مَحَلَّ لَهَا.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">مِن جُوعٍ</span><span>جَارّ وَمَجْرُور مُتَعَلِّقَان بِـ\"أَطْعَمَهُمْ\".</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">وَآمَنَهُمْ مِنْ خَوْفٍ</span><span>مَعْطُوفَة بِالْوَاو عَلَى \"أَطْعَمَهُمْ مِن جُوعٍ\" — تُعْرَب إِعْرَابَهَا. جُمْلَة \"آمَنَهُمْ\" مَعْطُوفَة عَلَى جُمْلَة \"أَطْعَمَهُمْ\" — لَا مَحَلَّ لَهَا.</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <hr class=\"divider\">\n\n  <div class=\"theme-box\">\n    <h3>Structural summary</h3>\n    <div class=\"theme-grid\">\n      <div class=\"theme-card\">\n        <div class=\"theme-card-label\">Verses 1–2</div>\n        Long-range لَام التَّعْلِيل: the جَارّ وَمَجْرُور لِإِيلَافِ spans two verses before reaching its مُتَعَلَّق in v.3. Verse 2 adds a بَدَل (إِيلَافِهِمْ) + مَفْعُول بِهِ لِلْمَصْدَر (رِحْلَةَ) + iḍāfa chain with عَطْف.\n      </div>\n      <div class=\"theme-card\">\n        <div class=\"theme-card-label\">Verses 3–4</div>\n        فَاء جَوَاب الشَّرْط + لَام الْأَمْر + مُضَارِع مَجْزُوم بِحَذْف النُّون (v.3). اسْم مَوْصُول as صِفَة for رَبَّ, with twin صِلَة clauses coordinated by وَاو (v.4).\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n</div>","feel":"<div class=\"book\">\n\n  <div class=\"surah-header\">\n    <div class=\"surah-label\">Sūrah 105 · Makkī · 5 verses</div>\n    <div class=\"surah-title-en\">The Elephant</div>\n    <div class=\"surah-title-ar\">سُورَةُ الْفِيلِ</div>\n    <div class=\"surah-meta\">A tightly constructed narrative surah built almost entirely from verbal sentences. Watch how the iʿrāb traces the chain of action: two rhetorical questions (vv. 1–2), two past-tense verbs of divine action (vv. 3, 5), and a present-tense verb describing the birds mid-flight (v. 4) — each clause grammatically dependent on or coordinated with what came before.</div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"intro-box\">\n    Three grammatical points dominate this surah: (1) the <span style=\"font-family:'Amiri',serif;\">لَمْ</span> particle and its effect on the مُضَارِع (apocopation / حَذْف حَرْف الْعِلَّة); (2) كَيْفَ as an اسْم اسْتِفْهَام functioning as a حَال; and (3) the كَاف of تَشْبِيه treated as an اسْم (not a حَرْف) — making it a مُضَاف. Each is worth mastering as a recurring Qurʾānic pattern.\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"section-head\">Part I — The Two Rhetorical Questions (Verses 1–2)</div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 1</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">أَلَمْ تَرَ كَيْفَ فَعَلَ رَبُّكَ بِأَصْحَابِ الْفِيلِ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"Have you not seen how your Lord dealt with the People of the Elephant?\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>The <span class=\"term\">هَمْزَة</span> opens the verse as a <span class=\"term\">حَرْف اسْتِفْهَام</span> — here used rhetorically, not to seek information but to draw the listener into vivid recollection. <span class=\"term\">لَمْ</span> is a triple-function particle: it negates (<span class=\"term\">نَفْي</span>), apocopates the following مُضَارِع (<span class=\"term\">جَزْم</span>), and flips the tense from present to past (<span class=\"term\">قَلْب</span>).</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">تَرَ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">فِعْل مُضَارِع</span> <span class=\"term\">مَجْزُوم</span> by لَمْ. Its <span class=\"term\">عَلَامَة جَزْم</span> (marker of apocopation) is <span class=\"term\">حَذْف حَرْف الْعِلَّة</span> — the final يَاء of the root (أَرَى) has been deleted rather than receiving a sukūn, because Arabic does not put sukūn on weak letters. This is one of the most important rules for defective verbs (<span class=\"term\">الْفِعْل النَّاقِص</span>). The <span class=\"term\">فَاعِل</span> is a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر وُجُوبًا</span> — a pronoun concealed by grammatical necessity (not by choice) — تَقْدِيرُهُ: أَنْتَ. \"Obligatorily concealed\" because the verb is in the second person; there is no way to express أَنْتَ explicitly alongside تَرَ without awkwardness.</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">كَيْفَ</span> is an <span class=\"term\">اسْم اسْتِفْهَام</span> built on <span class=\"term\">فَتْح</span>, functioning here as a <span class=\"term\">حَال</span> (circumstantial accusative) in the position of <span class=\"term\">نَصْب</span>. It asks about the manner of the action — \"in what state/manner did your Lord act?\" The clause <span class=\"ar-inline\">كَيْفَ فَعَلَ رَبُّكَ</span> as a whole occupies the position of <span class=\"term\">نَصْب</span> as the <span class=\"term\">مَفْعُول بِهِ</span> of <span class=\"ar-inline\">تَرَ</span>.</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">فَعَلَ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">فِعْل مَاضٍ</span> built on <span class=\"term\">فَتْح</span>. <span class=\"ar-inline\">رَبُّكَ</span> is its <span class=\"term\">فَاعِل</span> in <span class=\"term\">رَفْع</span> by <span class=\"term\">ضَمَّة ظَاهِرَة</span>; the attached <span class=\"ar-inline\">كَاف</span> is a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير مُتَّصِل</span> in <span class=\"term\">جَرّ</span> by <span class=\"term\">إِضَافَة</span>. <span class=\"ar-inline\">بِأَصْحَابِ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">جَارّ وَمَجْرُور</span> <span class=\"term\">مُتَعَلِّق</span> بِـ\"فَعَلَ\"; and <span class=\"ar-inline\">الْفِيلِ</span> is the <span class=\"term\">مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ</span> in <span class=\"term\">جَرّ</span> by <span class=\"term\">كَسْرَة ظَاهِرَة</span>.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">أَلَمْ</span><span>الْهَمْزَة: حَرْف اسْتِفْهَام. لَمْ: حَرْف نَفْي وَجَزْم وَقَلْب.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">تَرَ</span><span>فِعْل مُضَارِع مَجْزُوم بِلَمْ. عَلَامَة جَزْمِهِ: حَذْف حَرْف الْعِلَّة (الْيَاء). الْفَاعِل ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر وُجُوبًا تَقْدِيرُهُ: أَنْتَ.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">كَيْفَ</span><span>اسْم اسْتِفْهَام مَبْنِيّ عَلَى الْفَتْح فِي مَحَلِّ نَصْب حَال.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">جُمْلَة كَيْفَ فَعَلَ</span><span>فِي مَحَلِّ نَصْب مَفْعُول بِهِ لِـ\"تَرَ\".</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">رَبُّكَ</span><span>فَاعِل مَرْفُوع بِضَمَّة ظَاهِرَة. الْكَاف: ضَمِير مُتَّصِل فِي مَحَلِّ جَرّ بِالْإِضَافَة.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">بِأَصْحَابِ الْفِيلِ</span><span>جَارّ وَمَجْرُور مُتَعَلِّقَان بِـ\"فَعَلَ\". الْفِيلِ: مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ مَجْرُور بِكَسْرَة.</span></div>\n      </div>\n\n      <div class=\"callout\">\n        <div class=\"callout-title\">ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر وُجُوبًا vs جَوَازًا — what is the difference?</div>\n        A <span style=\"font-family:'Amiri',serif;font-size:15px;\">ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر جَوَازًا</span> (optionally concealed) is one that could theoretically be expressed as an explicit noun — you could say هُوَ فَعَلَ and the sentence still works. A <span style=\"font-family:'Amiri',serif;font-size:15px;\">ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر وُجُوبًا</span> (obligatorily concealed) cannot be made explicit without breaking grammar — second-person and first-person verb pronouns in Arabic must remain hidden. So أَنْتَ as فَاعِل of تَرَ is وُجُوبًا; هُوَ as فَاعِل of فَعَلَ is جَوَازًا.\n      </div>\n\n      <div class=\"callout\">\n        <div class=\"callout-title\">حَذْف حَرْف الْعِلَّة — the weak-letter rule for جَزْم</div>\n        When a defective verb (الْفِعْل النَّاقِص — one whose final root letter is وَاو or يَاء) is apocopated by لَمْ، لَا النَّاهِيَة، or a جَازِم, it cannot receive sukūn on the weak letter. Instead, the weak letter itself is deleted. So يَرَى → يَرَ (not يَرَيْ). The deletion is the marker of جَزْم, not sukūn.\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 2</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">أَلَمْ يَجْعَلْ كَيْدَهُمْ فِى تَضْلِيلٍ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"Did He not make their scheming go astray?\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">أَلَمْ</span> carries the same iʿrāb as verse 1. <span class=\"ar-inline\">يَجْعَلْ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">فِعْل مُضَارِع</span> <span class=\"term\">مَجْزُوم</span> by لَمْ — but here the <span class=\"term\">عَلَامَة جَزْم</span> is <span class=\"term\">سُكُون آخِرِهِ</span>, because يَجْعَل is a sound verb (not defective), so it simply receives sukūn on its final letter. The <span class=\"term\">فَاعِل</span> is a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر جَوَازًا</span> هُوَ referring to God.</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">يَجْعَلَ</span> here is the verb \"to make/render something [into something]\" — a verb that takes <span class=\"term\">مَفْعُولَيْن</span> (two objects). The first is <span class=\"ar-inline\">كَيْدَهُمْ</span> in <span class=\"term\">نَصْب</span> by <span class=\"term\">فَتْحَة ظَاهِرَة</span>; the attached <span class=\"ar-inline\">هَاء</span> is a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير مُتَّصِل</span> in <span class=\"term\">جَرّ</span> by <span class=\"term\">إِضَافَة</span>, and the <span class=\"term\">مِيم</span> marks plurality. The second مَفْعُول is supplied by <span class=\"ar-inline\">فِي تَضْلِيلٍ</span> — a <span class=\"term\">جَارّ وَمَجْرُور</span> standing in the position of the second مَفْعُول بِهِ.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">يَجْعَلْ</span><span>فِعْل مُضَارِع مَجْزُوم بِلَمْ. عَلَامَة جَزْمِهِ: سُكُون آخِرِهِ. الْفَاعِل ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر جَوَازًا هُوَ. الْجُمْلَة اسْتِئْنَافِيَّة.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">كَيْدَهُمْ</span><span>مَفْعُول بِهِ أَوَّل مَنْصُوب بِفَتْحَة ظَاهِرَة. الْهَاء: مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ. الْمِيم: لِلْجَمَاعَة.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">فِي تَضْلِيلٍ</span><span>جَارّ وَمَجْرُور فِي مَقَام الْمَفْعُول الثَّانِي لِـ\"يَجْعَل\".</span></div>\n      </div>\n\n      <div class=\"callout\">\n        <div class=\"callout-title\">سُكُون vs حَذْف — the two markers of جَزْم</div>\n        When لَمْ apocopates a verb: sound verbs (الصَّحِيح) receive <span style=\"font-family:'Amiri',serif;font-size:15px;\">سُكُون</span> on the final letter (يَجْعَلْ here). Defective verbs (النَّاقِص) lose their final weak letter entirely — <span style=\"font-family:'Amiri',serif;font-size:15px;\">حَذْف حَرْف الْعِلَّة</span> (تَرَ in v.1). Hollow verbs (الْأَجْوَف) lose their middle weak letter. This distinction is essential for parsing جَزْم correctly.\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <hr class=\"divider\">\n  <div class=\"section-head\">Part II — The Divine Action (Verses 3–5)</div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 3</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">وَأَرْسَلَ عَلَيْهِمْ طَيْرًا أَبَابِيلَ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"And He sent against them birds in flocks —\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>The <span class=\"term\">وَاو</span> is a <span class=\"term\">حَرْف عَطْف</span> coordinating this on verse 2. <span class=\"ar-inline\">أَرْسَلَ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">فِعْل مَاضٍ</span> built on <span class=\"term\">فَتْح</span>, with a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر جَوَازًا</span> هُوَ as <span class=\"term\">فَاعِل</span>. The coordinated clause جملة \"أَرْسَلَ\" has no syntactic position — it is a continuation of the sequence.</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">عَلَيْهِمْ</span>: عَلَى is a <span class=\"term\">حَرْف جَرّ</span>; the <span class=\"ar-inline\">هَاء</span> is a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير مُتَّصِل</span> in <span class=\"term\">جَرّ</span> by عَلَى; the <span class=\"term\">مِيم</span> marks plurality. The <span class=\"term\">جَارّ وَمَجْرُور</span> is <span class=\"term\">مُتَعَلِّق</span> بِـ\"أَرْسَلَ\". <span class=\"ar-inline\">طَيْرًا</span> is the <span class=\"term\">مَفْعُول بِهِ</span> in <span class=\"term\">نَصْب</span> by <span class=\"term\">فَتْحَة ظَاهِرَة</span>.</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">أَبَابِيلَ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">صِفَة</span> for <span class=\"ar-inline\">طَيْرًا</span> in <span class=\"term\">نَصْب</span> by <span class=\"term\">فَتْحَة</span>. Notably, أَبَابِيل is a word that has no singular form in Arabic — it exists only as a plural — and it is on the pattern of words that are <span class=\"term\">غَيْر مُنْصَرِف</span> (diptote) in some readings, though here the fatḥa as its naṣb marker still holds.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">وَأَرْسَلَ</span><span>وَاو: حَرْف عَطْف. أَرْسَلَ: فِعْل مَاضٍ مَبْنِيّ عَلَى الْفَتْح. فَاعِله ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر جَوَازًا هُوَ.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">عَلَيْهِمْ</span><span>عَلَى: حَرْف جَرّ. الْهَاء: ضَمِير مُتَّصِل فِي مَحَلِّ جَرّ. الْمِيم: لِلْجَمَاعَة. الْجَارّ وَالْمَجْرُور مُتَعَلِّقَان بِـ\"أَرْسَلَ\".</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">طَيْرًا</span><span>مَفْعُول بِهِ مَنْصُوب بِفَتْحَة ظَاهِرَة.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">أَبَابِيلَ</span><span>صِفَة لِـ\"طَيْرًا\" مَنْصُوبَة بِالْفَتْحَة. لَا وَاحِد لَهَا مِن لَفْظِهَا.</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 4</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">تَرْمِيهِم بِحِجَارَةٍ مِّن سِجِّيلٍ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"Pelting them with stones of hard clay —\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>This verse is a <span class=\"term\">صِفَة ثَانِيَة</span> for <span class=\"ar-inline\">طَيْرًا</span> — a second adjectival clause further describing the birds. The verb <span class=\"ar-inline\">تَرْمِي</span> is a <span class=\"term\">فِعْل مُضَارِع</span> in <span class=\"term\">رَفْع</span>, but its <span class=\"term\">ضَمَّة</span> is <span class=\"term\">مُقَدَّرَة عَلَى الْيَاء لِلثِّقَل</span> — hidden on the يَاء because it is phonologically heavy (the ياء resists bearing a ḍamma). This is the standard rule for يَاء-ending مُضَارِع verbs in the indicative.</p>\n\n      <p>The <span class=\"term\">فَاعِل</span> is a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر جَوَازًا</span> هِيَ, referring back to <span class=\"ar-inline\">طَيْرًا</span>. The attached <span class=\"ar-inline\">هَاء</span> of <span class=\"ar-inline\">تَرْمِيهِمْ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير مُتَّصِل</span> in <span class=\"term\">نَصْب</span> as <span class=\"term\">مَفْعُول بِهِ</span>; the <span class=\"term\">مِيم</span> is for plurality.</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">بِحِجَارَةٍ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">جَارّ وَمَجْرُور</span> <span class=\"term\">مُتَعَلِّق</span> بِـ\"تَرْمِيهِمْ\". The following <span class=\"ar-inline\">مِن سِجِّيلٍ</span> is a second <span class=\"term\">جَارّ وَمَجْرُور</span> <span class=\"term\">مُتَعَلِّق</span> by a <span class=\"term\">صِفَة مَحْذُوفَة</span> for حِجَارَةٍ — the implied full reading is: حِجَارَةٍ كَائِنَةٍ مِن سِجِّيلٍ (\"stones that are from sijjīl\"). The <span class=\"term\">مِن</span> here is used to indicate the material of origin.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">تَرْمِيهِمْ</span><span>فِعْل مُضَارِع مَرْفُوع بِضَمَّة مُقَدَّرَة عَلَى الْيَاء لِلثِّقَل. الْفَاعِل ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر هِيَ. الْهَاء: مَفْعُول بِهِ فِي مَحَلِّ نَصْب. الْمِيم: لِلْجَمَاعَة. الْجُمْلَة فِي مَحَلِّ نَصْب صِفَة ثَانِيَة لِـ\"طَيْرًا\".</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">بِحِجَارَةٍ</span><span>جَارّ وَمَجْرُور مُتَعَلِّقَان بِـ\"تَرْمِيهِمْ\".</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">مِن سِجِّيلٍ</span><span>جَارّ وَمَجْرُور مُتَعَلِّقَان بِصِفَة مَحْذُوفَة لِـ\"حِجَارَةٍ\" — تَقْدِيرُهَا: كَائِنَةٍ مِن سِجِّيلٍ.</span></div>\n      </div>\n\n      <div class=\"callout\">\n        <div class=\"callout-title\">ضَمَّة مُقَدَّرَة لِلثِّقَل — why يَاء resists ḍamma</div>\n        Arabic phonology distinguishes between two reasons a short vowel can be \"hidden\": تَعَذُّر (impossibility — the alif literally cannot bear any vowel) and ثِقَل (heaviness — the يَاء and وَاو can technically bear vowels but it is phonologically heavy and resisted by the language). So يَرْمِي in رَفْع carries a ḍamma that is there grammatically but hidden for phonological comfort. This same rule applies to all يَاء-final مُضَارِع verbs in the indicative.\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 5</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">فَجَعَلَهُمْ كَعَصْفٍ مَّأْكُولٍ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"And He made them like devoured chaff.\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">فَجَعَلَهُمْ</span> is coordinated on <span class=\"ar-inline\">أَرْسَلَ</span> in verse 3 by <span class=\"term\">فَاء</span> (which indicates swift consequence — no sooner did He send the birds than this result followed). The verb <span class=\"ar-inline\">جَعَلَ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">فِعْل مَاضٍ</span> built on <span class=\"term\">فَتْح</span> with a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر جَوَازًا</span> هُوَ as <span class=\"term\">فَاعِل</span>. The attached <span class=\"ar-inline\">هَاء</span> is the <span class=\"term\">مَفْعُول بِهِ أَوَّل</span> in <span class=\"term\">نَصْب</span>; the <span class=\"term\">مِيم</span> marks plurality.</p>\n\n      <p>The most important iʿrāb point in this verse is <span class=\"ar-inline\">كَعَصْفٍ</span>. The <span class=\"term\">كَاف</span> here is not a <span class=\"term\">حَرْف</span> but an <span class=\"term\">اسْم</span> — it carries the meaning مِثْل (\"like/resembling\"), making it a noun. As an <span class=\"term\">اسْم</span>, it is built on <span class=\"term\">فَتْح</span> and sits in the position of <span class=\"term\">نَصْب</span> as the <span class=\"term\">مَفْعُول بِهِ ثَانٍ</span> of جَعَلَ. Because it is an <span class=\"term\">اسْم</span>, it can take a <span class=\"term\">مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ</span> — and <span class=\"ar-inline\">عَصْفٍ</span> is exactly that: a <span class=\"term\">مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ</span> in <span class=\"term\">جَرّ</span> by <span class=\"term\">إِضَافَة</span>, marked by <span class=\"term\">كَسْرَة</span>. <span class=\"ar-inline\">مَأْكُولٍ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">صِفَة</span> for عَصْفٍ, matching it in <span class=\"term\">جَرّ</span> by <span class=\"term\">كَسْرَة ظَاهِرَة</span>.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">فَجَعَلَهُمْ</span><span>فَاء: حَرْف عَطْف. جَعَلَ: فِعْل مَاضٍ مَبْنِيّ عَلَى الْفَتْح. فَاعِله ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر جَوَازًا هُوَ. الْهَاء: مَفْعُول بِهِ أَوَّل فِي مَحَلِّ نَصْب. الْمِيم: لِلْجَمَاعَة.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">كَعَصْفٍ</span><span>الْكَاف: اسْم بِمَعْنَى \"مِثْل\" مَبْنِيّ عَلَى الْفَتْح فِي مَحَلِّ نَصْب مَفْعُول بِهِ ثَانٍ. وَهُوَ مُضَاف. عَصْفٍ: مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ مَجْرُور بِكَسْرَة.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">مَأْكُولٍ</span><span>صِفَة لِـ\"عَصْفٍ\" مَجْرُورَة بِكَسْرَة ظَاهِرَة.</span></div>\n      </div>\n\n      <div class=\"callout\">\n        <div class=\"callout-title\">الْكَاف — حَرْف أَمْ اسْم؟</div>\n        The كَاف of comparison (كَاف التَّشْبِيه) appears in two grammatical roles. When it is a <span style=\"font-family:'Amiri',serif;font-size:15px;\">حَرْف</span>, it governs the following noun in جَرّ and cannot itself be إعراب'ed. When it is an <span style=\"font-family:'Amiri',serif;font-size:15px;\">اسْم</span> (as here), it has its own محل إعراب — here نَصْب as the second مَفْعُول — and takes a مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ. The signal that it is an اسْم is that it functions as a مَفْعُول within the sentence structure of جَعَلَ, which requires a noun in that slot, not a preposition.\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <hr class=\"divider\">\n\n  <div class=\"theme-box\">\n    <h3>Structural summary</h3>\n    <div class=\"theme-grid\">\n      <div class=\"theme-card\">\n        <div class=\"theme-card-label\">Verses 1–2</div>\n        Two rhetorical questions with أَلَمْ. Verse 1: جَزْم by حَذْف حَرْف الْعِلَّة (الْفِعْل النَّاقِص); كَيْفَ as حَال; كَيْفَ فَعَلَ as مَفْعُول بِهِ. Verse 2: جَزْم by سُكُون (الصَّحِيح); جَارّ وَمَجْرُور standing as مَفْعُول ثَانٍ.\n      </div>\n      <div class=\"theme-card\">\n        <div class=\"theme-card-label\">Verses 3–5</div>\n        Chain of مَاضِي verbs: أَرْسَلَ (v.3) → صِفَة clause تَرْمِيهِمْ with ضَمَّة مُقَدَّرَة لِلثِّقَل (v.4) → فَجَعَلَهُمْ with كَاف اسْمِيَّة as مَفْعُول ثَانٍ + مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ + صِفَة (v.5).\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n</div>","humazah":"<div class=\"book\">\n\n  <div class=\"surah-header\">\n    <div class=\"surah-label\">Sūrah 104 · Makkī · 9 verses</div>\n    <div class=\"surah-title-en\">The Scorner</div>\n    <div class=\"surah-title-ar\">سُورَةُ الْهُمَزَةِ</div>\n    <div class=\"surah-meta\">The sūrah opens with a striking <span style=\"font-family:'Amiri',serif;font-size:15px;\">مُبْتَدَأ</span> without an explicit <span style=\"font-family:'Amiri',serif;font-size:15px;\">خَبَر</span> — both are present but the <span style=\"font-family:'Amiri',serif;font-size:15px;\">خَبَر</span> is deleted (maḥdhūf). It then builds a precise portrait of the scorner through three relative structures, before pivoting to the punishment with كَلَّا and a vivid description of the Ḥuṭama.</div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"intro-box\">\n    Notice how the surah stacks sentence types: a nominal sentence with deleted khabar (v.1), a relative clause used as a ṣifa (v.2), a verbal sentence used as badal from a ṣila (v.3), a passive oath-answer with nūn al-tawkīd (v.4), then a rhetorical question (v.5), and finally Inna-sentences closing the surah. Each verse introduces a distinct grammatical structure.\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"section-head\">Part I — The Portrait of the Scorner (Verses 1–3)</div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 1</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">وَيْلٌ لِّكُلِّ هُمَزَةٍ لُّمَزَةٍ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"Woe to every scorner and mocker —\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>This verse opens with a <span class=\"term\">جُمْلَة اسْمِيَّة</span> — a nominal sentence — whose <span class=\"term\">مُبْتَدَأ</span> is <span class=\"ar-inline\">وَيْلٌ</span> and whose <span class=\"term\">خَبَر</span> is deleted (<span class=\"term\">مَحْذُوف</span>). <span class=\"ar-inline\">وَيْلٌ</span> is a noun of punishment or lamentation, here <span class=\"term\">مَرْفُوع</span> by <span class=\"term\">ضَمَّة ظَاهِرَة</span> as the <span class=\"term\">مُبْتَدَأ</span>. It carries <span class=\"term\">تَنْوِين</span>, making it indefinite — this indefiniteness here conveys vastness and gravity (\"woe of the most severe kind\").</p>\n      <p>The <span class=\"term\">خَبَر</span> is understood as an implied verb of affliction — something like \"is decreed\" or \"has fallen.\" The <span class=\"term\">جَارّ وَمَجْرُور</span> <span class=\"ar-inline\">لِكُلِّ</span> is <span class=\"term\">مُتَعَلِّق</span> (related) to this deleted <span class=\"term\">خَبَر</span>. <span class=\"ar-inline\">كُلِّ</span> is itself a <span class=\"term\">مُضَاف</span>, and <span class=\"ar-inline\">هُمَزَةٍ</span> is its <span class=\"term\">مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ</span> in <span class=\"term\">جَرّ</span> by <span class=\"term\">كَسْرَة ظَاهِرَة</span>.</p>\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">لُمَزَةٍ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">بَدَل</span> (substitute/appositive) from <span class=\"ar-inline\">هُمَزَةٍ</span>, following it in <span class=\"term\">جَرّ</span> by <span class=\"term\">كَسْرَة</span>. A <span class=\"term\">بَدَل</span> always matches the case of the word it substitutes. The whole <span class=\"term\">جُمْلَة مُبْتَدَأ وَخَبَر</span> is <span class=\"term\">ابْتِدَائِيَّة</span> — no syntactic position.</p>\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">وَيْلٌ</span><span>مُبْتَدَأ مَرْفُوع بِضَمَّة ظَاهِرَة. الخبر محذوف تقديره: كَائِنٌ أو مُسْتَقِرٌّ.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">لِكُلِّ</span><span>جَارّ وَمَجْرُور مُتَعَلِّقَان بِالْخَبَرِ الْمَحْذُوف. كُلِّ: مُضَاف.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">هُمَزَةٍ</span><span>مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ مَجْرُور بِكَسْرَة ظَاهِرَة.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">لُمَزَةٍ</span><span>بَدَل مِن \"هُمَزَةٍ\" مَجْرُور وَعَلَامَة جَرِّهِ الْكَسْرَة.</span></div>\n      </div>\n      <div class=\"callout\">\n        <div class=\"callout-title\">هُمَزَة vs لُمَزَة — are these the same?</div>\n        Both are intensifying verbal noun patterns (صِيغَة مُبَالَغَة) on the scale فُعَلَة. هُمَزَة refers to one who mocks with gestures or actions; لُمَزَة refers to one who mocks with speech or facial expressions. Classical grammarians who take لُمَزَة as بَدَل understand the two as so close in meaning that one substitutes for the other — not contradicting it, but restating with a nuance.\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 2</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">الَّذِى جَمَعَ مَالًا وَعَدَّدَهُۥ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"Who amassed wealth and tallied it —\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">الَّذِي</span> is an <span class=\"term\">اسْم مَوْصُول</span> built on <span class=\"term\">سُكُون</span>. Its syntactic position here is a <span class=\"term\">خَبَر مُبْتَدَأ مَحْذُوف</span> — the implied full sentence is هُوَ الَّذِي (he is the one who). This implied sentence هُوَ الَّذِي sits in the position of <span class=\"term\">جَرّ</span> as a <span class=\"term\">صِفَة</span> (adjective/qualifier) for <span class=\"ar-inline\">هُمَزَةٍ</span> in verse 1.</p>\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">جَمَعَ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">فِعْل مَاضٍ</span> built on <span class=\"term\">فَتْح</span>, with a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر جَوَازًا</span> (an optionally concealed pronoun هُوَ) as its <span class=\"term\">فَاعِل</span>. <span class=\"ar-inline\">مَالًا</span> is the <span class=\"term\">مَفْعُول بِهِ</span> in <span class=\"term\">نَصْب</span> by <span class=\"term\">فَتْحَة ظَاهِرَة</span>. The whole clause <span class=\"ar-inline\">جَمَعَ مَالًا</span> is the <span class=\"term\">صِلَة الْمَوْصُول</span> — it has no syntactic position of its own.</p>\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">وَعَدَّدَهُ</span> is coordinated on <span class=\"ar-inline\">جَمَعَ</span> by <span class=\"term\">وَاو</span> and carries the same <span class=\"term\">إِعْرَاب</span>. The attached <span class=\"ar-inline\">هُ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير مُتَّصِل</span> in <span class=\"term\">نَصْب</span> position as <span class=\"term\">مَفْعُول بِهِ</span>, referring back to <span class=\"ar-inline\">مَالًا</span>.</p>\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">الَّذِي</span><span>اسْم مَوْصُول مَبْنِيّ عَلَى السُّكُون. فِي مَحَلِّ رَفْع خَبَر مُبْتَدَأ مَحْذُوف (هُوَ). وَالْجُمْلَة \"هُوَ الَّذِي\" فِي مَحَلِّ جَرّ صِفَة لِـ\"هُمَزَة\".</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">جَمَعَ</span><span>فِعْل مَاضٍ مَبْنِيّ عَلَى الْفَتْح. الْفَاعِل ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر جَوَازًا تَقْدِيرُهُ: هُوَ. جُمْلَة \"جَمَعَ\" صِلَة الْمَوْصُول — لَا مَحَلَّ لَهَا.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">مَالًا</span><span>مَفْعُول بِهِ مَنْصُوب بِفَتْحَة ظَاهِرَة.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">وَعَدَّدَهُ</span><span>مَعْطُوفَة بِالْوَاو عَلَى \"جَمَعَ\"، وَتُعْرَب إِعْرَابَهَا. الْهَاء: ضَمِير مُتَّصِل فِي مَحَلِّ نَصْب مَفْعُول بِهِ.</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 3</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">يَحْسَبُ أَنَّ مَالَهُۥٓ أَخْلَدَهُۥ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"He supposes that his wealth will make him immortal —\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">يَحْسَبُ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">فِعْل مُضَارِع</span> in <span class=\"term\">رَفْع</span> by <span class=\"term\">ضَمَّة ظَاهِرَة</span>, with a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر جَوَازًا</span> هُوَ as its <span class=\"term\">فَاعِل</span>. Crucially, the whole verbal clause <span class=\"ar-inline\">يَحْسَبُ</span> and what follows it is a <span class=\"term\">بَدَل</span> from the <span class=\"term\">صِلَة</span> of <span class=\"ar-inline\">الَّذِي</span> in verse 2 — it elaborates and specifies the defining quality of the scorner beyond mere wealth-hoarding.</p>\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">أَنَّ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">حَرْف تَوْكِيد مُشَبَّه بِالْفِعْل</span>. Together with its <span class=\"term\">اسْم</span> and <span class=\"term\">خَبَر</span>, it forms a <span class=\"term\">مَصْدَر مُؤَوَّل</span> — an implied verbal noun — that fills the position of the <span class=\"term\">مَفْعُول بِهِ</span> of <span class=\"ar-inline\">يَحْسَبُ</span>. Since <span class=\"ar-inline\">يَحْسَبُ</span> is a verb of thinking/supposing that takes two objects (<span class=\"term\">فِعْل يَنْصِب مَفْعُولَيْن</span>), the <span class=\"ar-inline\">أَنَّ</span>-clause substitutes for both — it \"stands in place of\" (<span class=\"term\">سَدَّ مَسَدَّ</span>) both مَفْعُولَيْن.</p>\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">مَالَهُ</span> is the <span class=\"term\">اسْم أَنَّ</span> in <span class=\"term\">نَصْب</span> by <span class=\"term\">فَتْحَة ظَاهِرَة</span>; the attached <span class=\"ar-inline\">هُ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير مُتَّصِل</span> in <span class=\"term\">جَرّ</span> by <span class=\"term\">إِضَافَة</span>. <span class=\"ar-inline\">أَخْلَدَهُ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">فِعْل مَاضٍ</span> with <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر</span> هُوَ as <span class=\"term\">فَاعِل</span> and the attached <span class=\"ar-inline\">هُ</span> as <span class=\"term\">مَفْعُول بِهِ</span> in <span class=\"term\">نَصْب</span>; the clause <span class=\"ar-inline\">أَخْلَدَهُ</span> is the <span class=\"term\">خَبَر أَنَّ</span>.</p>\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">يَحْسَبُ</span><span>فِعْل مُضَارِع مَرْفُوع بِضَمَّة. فَاعِله ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر هُوَ. الْجُمْلَة بَدَل مِن صِلَة الْمَوْصُول — لَا مَحَلَّ لَهَا.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">أَنَّ</span><span>حَرْف تَوْكِيد مُشَبَّه بِالْفِعْل. أَنَّ وَمَعْمُولَاهَا فِي مَحَلِّ نَصْب سَدَّتْ مَسَدَّ مَفْعُولَيْ \"يَحْسَبُ\".</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">مَالَهُ</span><span>اسْم \"أَنَّ\" مَنْصُوب بِفَتْحَة. الْهَاء: ضَمِير مُتَّصِل فِي مَحَلِّ جَرّ بِالْإِضَافَة.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">أَخْلَدَهُ</span><span>فِعْل مَاضٍ مَبْنِيّ عَلَى الْفَتْح. فَاعِله ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر هُوَ. الْهَاء: مَفْعُول بِهِ فِي مَحَلِّ نَصْب. الْجُمْلَة خَبَر \"أَنَّ\".</span></div>\n      </div>\n      <div class=\"callout\">\n        <div class=\"callout-title\">سَدَّ مَسَدَّ الْمَفْعُولَيْن — what does this mean?</div>\n        Verbs of cognition like يَحْسَبُ، يَظُنُّ، يَعْلَمُ normally take two objects in Arabic (he thinks [it] [to be such]). When an أَنَّ-clause follows them, the whole clause is compressed into a single implied verbal noun that fills both object slots simultaneously. Grammarians describe this as the أَنَّ-clause \"blocking the path\" (سَدَّ مَسَدَّ) of both مَفْعُولَيْن.\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <hr class=\"divider\">\n  <div class=\"section-head\">Part II — The Punishment (Verses 4–9)</div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 4</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">كَلَّا لَيُنۢبَذَنَّ فِى الْحُطَمَةِ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"No indeed! He will surely be flung into the Crusher —\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">كَلَّا</span> is a <span class=\"term\">حَرْف رَدْع وَزَجْر</span> — a particle of sharp deterrence — with no grammatical effect (<span class=\"term\">لَا عَمَل لَهُ</span>). It closes the door on the scorner's delusion emphatically.</p>\n      <p>The <span class=\"term\">لَام</span> of <span class=\"ar-inline\">لَيُنْبَذَنَّ</span> is the <span class=\"term\">لَام الْقَسَم</span> — it occurs in the answer to an implied deleted oath, exactly as in Sūrat al-Takāthur. The verb <span class=\"ar-inline\">يُنْبَذَنَّ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">فِعْل مُضَارِع لِلْمَجْهُول</span> (passive present) made <span class=\"term\">مَبْنِيّ</span> (indeclinable) by the attachment of <span class=\"term\">نُون التَّوْكِيد الثَّقِيلَة</span>. The <span class=\"term\">نَائِب الْفَاعِل</span> (passive subject) is a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر جَوَازًا</span> هُوَ, referring back to the scorner. The emphatic نُون is a <span class=\"term\">حَرْف تَوْكِيد</span> with no grammatical position of its own.</p>\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">فِي الْحُطَمَةِ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">جَارّ وَمَجْرُور</span> <span class=\"term\">مُتَعَلِّق</span> with <span class=\"ar-inline\">يُنْبَذَنَّ</span>. The whole clause is <span class=\"term\">اسْتِئْنَافِيَّة</span> — no syntactic position.</p>\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">كَلَّا</span><span>حَرْف رَدْع وَزَجْر — لَا عَمَل لَهُ.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">لَـ</span><span>لَام الْقَسَم — وَاقِعَة فِي جَوَاب قَسَم مَحْذُوف.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">يُنْبَذَنَّ</span><span>فِعْل مُضَارِع لِلْمَجْهُول مَبْنِيّ عَلَى الْفَتْح لِاتِّصَالِهِ بِنُون التَّوْكِيد الثَّقِيلَة. نَائِب الْفَاعِل ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر جَوَازًا هُوَ. النُّون: حَرْف تَوْكِيد.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">فِي الْحُطَمَةِ</span><span>جَارّ وَمَجْرُور مُتَعَلِّقَان بِـ\"يُنْبَذَنَّ\".</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 5</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">وَمَآ أَدْرَىٰكَ مَا الْحُطَمَةُ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"And what will make you know what the Crusher is?\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>This is the classical Qurʾānic rhetorical question formula (وَمَا أَدْرَاكَ مَا...) that recurs across multiple sūrahs. Its iʿrāb is fixed and worth memorising as a pattern.</p>\n      <p>The <span class=\"term\">وَاو</span> is a <span class=\"term\">حَرْف عَطْف</span>. The first <span class=\"ar-inline\">مَا</span> is an <span class=\"term\">اسْم اسْتِفْهَام</span> built on <span class=\"term\">سُكُون</span> in the position of <span class=\"term\">رَفْع</span> as a <span class=\"term\">مُبْتَدَأ</span>. <span class=\"ar-inline\">أَدْرَاكَ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">فِعْل مَاضٍ</span> with <span class=\"term\">فَتْح مُقَدَّر</span> on the <span class=\"term\">أَلِف</span> (hidden because <span class=\"term\">أَلِف</span> cannot bear a short vowel — <span class=\"term\">تَعَذُّر</span>); its <span class=\"term\">فَاعِل</span> is a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر</span> هُوَ referring to مَا; and the <span class=\"ar-inline\">كَاف</span> is a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير مُتَّصِل</span> built on <span class=\"term\">فَتْح</span> in <span class=\"term\">نَصْب</span> as <span class=\"term\">مَفْعُول بِهِ</span>. The clause <span class=\"ar-inline\">أَدْرَاكَ</span> is the <span class=\"term\">خَبَر</span> of the first مَا.</p>\n      <p>The second <span class=\"ar-inline\">مَا</span> is again an <span class=\"term\">اسْم اسْتِفْهَام</span> in <span class=\"term\">رَفْع</span> as a <span class=\"term\">مُبْتَدَأ</span>, and <span class=\"ar-inline\">الْحُطَمَةُ</span> is its <span class=\"term\">خَبَر</span> in <span class=\"term\">رَفْع</span> by <span class=\"term\">ضَمَّة ظَاهِرَة</span>. This second nominal sentence (مَا الْحُطَمَةُ) is itself the second <span class=\"term\">مَفْعُول بِهِ</span> of <span class=\"ar-inline\">أَدْرَاكَ</span>, in the position of <span class=\"term\">نَصْب</span>.</p>\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">مَا (الأولى)</span><span>اسْم اسْتِفْهَام مَبْنِيّ عَلَى السُّكُون فِي مَحَلِّ رَفْع مُبْتَدَأ.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">أَدْرَاكَ</span><span>فِعْل مَاضٍ — فَتْح مُقَدَّر عَلَى الْأَلِف (تَعَذُّر). فَاعِله ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر هُوَ. الْكَاف: مَفْعُول بِهِ أَوَّل فِي مَحَلِّ نَصْب. الْجُمْلَة خَبَر \"مَا\" الأولى.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">مَا (الثانية)</span><span>اسْم اسْتِفْهَام فِي مَحَلِّ رَفْع مُبْتَدَأ.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">الْحُطَمَةُ</span><span>خَبَر \"مَا\" مَرْفُوع بِضَمَّة. الْجُمْلَة الاسْمِيَّة (مَا الْحُطَمَةُ) فِي مَحَلِّ نَصْب مَفْعُول بِهِ ثَانٍ لِـ\"أَدْرَاكَ\".</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 6</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">نَارُ اللَّهِ الْمُوقَدَةُ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"It is the kindled Fire of God —\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">نَارُ</span> is analysed in one of two ways: either as a <span class=\"term\">بَدَل</span> from <span class=\"ar-inline\">الْحُطَمَةِ</span> (verse 4), following it in <span class=\"term\">رَفْع</span>; or as the <span class=\"term\">خَبَر مُبْتَدَأ مَحْذُوف</span>, the implied sentence being هِيَ نَارُ اللَّهِ — \"it is the fire of God.\" Both readings are valid.</p>\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">اللَّهِ</span> is the <span class=\"term\">مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ</span> in <span class=\"term\">جَرّ</span> by <span class=\"term\">كَسْرَة ظَاهِرَة</span>. <span class=\"ar-inline\">الْمُوقَدَةُ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">صِفَة</span> (adjective) for <span class=\"ar-inline\">نَارُ</span>, matching it in <span class=\"term\">رَفْع</span> by <span class=\"term\">ضَمَّة</span>.</p>\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">نَارُ</span><span>بَدَل مِن \"الْحُطَمَةِ\" مَرْفُوع — أَو خَبَر مُبْتَدَأ مَحْذُوف (هِيَ). نَارُ: مُضَاف.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">اللَّهِ</span><span>لَفْظ الْجَلَالَة: مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ مَجْرُور بِكَسْرَة ظَاهِرَة.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">الْمُوقَدَةُ</span><span>صِفَة لِـ\"نَارُ\" مَرْفُوعَة بِضَمَّة ظَاهِرَة.</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 7</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">الَّتِى تَطَّلِعُ عَلَى الْأَفْـِٔدَةِ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"Which rises over the hearts —\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">الَّتِي</span> is an <span class=\"term\">اسْم مَوْصُول</span> built on <span class=\"term\">سُكُون</span>, in the position of <span class=\"term\">رَفْع</span> as a <span class=\"term\">صِفَة ثَانِيَة</span> (second adjective) for <span class=\"ar-inline\">النَّارِ</span> — adding a further quality after <span class=\"ar-inline\">الْمُوقَدَةُ</span>.</p>\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">تَطَّلِعُ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">فِعْل مُضَارِع</span> in <span class=\"term\">رَفْع</span> by <span class=\"term\">ضَمَّة ظَاهِرَة</span>, with a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر جَوَازًا</span> هِيَ as its <span class=\"term\">فَاعِل</span>. The clause is the <span class=\"term\">صِلَة الْمَوْصُول</span> — no syntactic position. <span class=\"ar-inline\">عَلَى الْأَفْئِدَةِ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">جَارّ وَمَجْرُور</span> <span class=\"term\">مُتَعَلِّق</span> with <span class=\"ar-inline\">تَطَّلِعُ</span>.</p>\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">الَّتِي</span><span>اسْم مَوْصُول مَبْنِيّ عَلَى السُّكُون فِي مَحَلِّ رَفْع صِفَة ثَانِيَة لِـ\"النَّار\".</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">تَطَّلِعُ</span><span>فِعْل مُضَارِع مَرْفُوع بِضَمَّة. فَاعِله ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر هِيَ. الْجُمْلَة صِلَة الْمَوْصُول — لَا مَحَلَّ لَهَا.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">عَلَى الْأَفْئِدَةِ</span><span>جَارّ وَمَجْرُور مُتَعَلِّقَان بِـ\"تَطَّلِعُ\".</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 8</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">إِنَّهَا عَلَيْهِم مُّؤْصَدَةٌ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"Indeed it will be closed down upon them —\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">إِنَّ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">حَرْف تَوْكِيد مُشَبَّه بِالْفِعْل</span>. The attached <span class=\"ar-inline\">هَا</span> is a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير مُتَّصِل</span> built on <span class=\"term\">سُكُون</span> in the position of <span class=\"term\">نَصْب</span> as the <span class=\"term\">اسْم إِنَّ</span>, referring to the fire/Ḥuṭama.</p>\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">عَلَيْهِمْ</span> consists of <span class=\"ar-inline\">عَلَى</span> as a <span class=\"term\">حَرْف جَرّ</span> and the attached <span class=\"ar-inline\">هُم</span> — the <span class=\"ar-inline\">هَاء</span> is a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير مُتَّصِل</span> in <span class=\"term\">جَرّ</span> by <span class=\"ar-inline\">عَلَى</span>, and the <span class=\"term\">مِيم</span> marks plurality. The <span class=\"term\">جَارّ وَمَجْرُور</span> is <span class=\"term\">مُتَعَلِّق</span> with the <span class=\"term\">خَبَر</span> of إِنَّ.</p>\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">مُؤْصَدَةٌ</span> is the <span class=\"term\">خَبَر إِنَّ</span> in <span class=\"term\">رَفْع</span> by <span class=\"term\">ضَمَّة ظَاهِرَة</span>. The whole <span class=\"term\">جُمْلَة إِنَّ</span> is <span class=\"term\">اسْتِئْنَافِيَّة</span> — no syntactic position.</p>\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">إِنَّهَا</span><span>إِنَّ: حَرْف تَوْكِيد مُشَبَّه بِالْفِعْل. هَا: ضَمِير مُتَّصِل مَبْنِيّ عَلَى السُّكُون فِي مَحَلِّ نَصْب اسْم \"إِنَّ\".</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">عَلَيْهِمْ</span><span>عَلَى: حَرْف جَرّ. الْهَاء: ضَمِير مُتَّصِل فِي مَحَلِّ جَرّ. الْمِيم: لِلْجَمَاعَة. الْجَارّ وَالْمَجْرُور مُتَعَلِّقَان بِخَبَر \"إِنَّ\".</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">مُؤْصَدَةٌ</span><span>خَبَر \"إِنَّ\" مَرْفُوع بِضَمَّة ظَاهِرَة.</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 9</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">فِى عَمَدٍ مُّمَدَّدَةٍ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"In columns outstretched.\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>A short but complete grammatical unit. <span class=\"ar-inline\">فِي عَمَدٍ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">جَارّ وَمَجْرُور</span> <span class=\"term\">مُتَعَلِّق</span> with <span class=\"ar-inline\">مُؤْصَدَةٌ</span> in verse 8 — the fire is closed over them in/with outstretched columns. <span class=\"ar-inline\">مُمَدَّدَةٍ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">صِفَة</span> for <span class=\"ar-inline\">عَمَدٍ</span>, matching it in <span class=\"term\">جَرّ</span> by <span class=\"term\">كَسْرَة ظَاهِرَة</span>.</p>\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">فِي عَمَدٍ</span><span>جَارّ وَمَجْرُور مُتَعَلِّقَان بِـ\"مُؤْصَدَةٌ\" فِي الْآيَة السَّابِقَة.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">مُمَدَّدَةٍ</span><span>صِفَة لِـ\"عَمَدٍ\" مَجْرُورَة بِكَسْرَة ظَاهِرَة.</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <hr class=\"divider\">\n\n  <div class=\"theme-box\">\n    <h3>Structural summary</h3>\n    <div class=\"theme-grid\">\n      <div class=\"theme-card\">\n        <div class=\"theme-card-label\">Verses 1–3</div>\n        Portrait of the scorner: مُبْتَدَأ + خَبَر مَحْذُوف (v.1) → اسْم مَوْصُول as صِفَة (v.2) → يَحْسَبُ + أَنَّ-clause سَدَّ مَسَدَّ مَفْعُولَيْن (v.3). The بَدَل chain: لُمَزَة ← همزة; يَحْسَبُ ← صِلَة الَّذِي.\n      </div>\n      <div class=\"theme-card\">\n        <div class=\"theme-card-label\">Verses 4–9</div>\n        Punishment: كَلَّا + لَام الْقَسَم + passive مَبْنِيّ with نُون التَّوْكِيد (v.4) → وَمَا أَدْرَاكَ formula with dual مَا-sentences (v.5) → بَدَل / خَبَر مَحْذُوف for نَارُ (v.6) → dual صِفَة with اسْم مَوْصُول (v.7) → إِنَّ-sentence (v.8) → trailing جَارّ وَمَجْرُور + صِفَة (v.9).\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n</div>","asr":"<div class=\"book\">\n\n  <div class=\"surah-header\">\n    <div class=\"surah-label\">Sūrah 103 · Makkī · 3 verses</div>\n    <div class=\"surah-title-en\">The Declining Day</div>\n    <div class=\"surah-title-ar\">سُورَةُ الْعَصْرِ</div>\n    <div class=\"surah-meta\">Despite its brevity, this surah contains the full architecture of a classical Arabic oath: a sworn oath (verse 1), its answer (verse 2), and a single sweeping exception that is itself a four-part clause (verse 3). Almost every major sentence-type in Arabic grammar appears within these three verses.</div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"intro-box\">\n    The entire surah is grammatically one sentence. Verse 1 is the oath; verse 2 is its answer — a complete Inna-sentence; verse 3 is an exception clause hanging off verse 2. Imām al-Shāfiʿī reportedly said: if people pondered only this surah, it would suffice them. Study it accordingly.\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 1</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">وَالْعَصْرِ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"By the declining day —\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>The <span class=\"ar-inline\">وَ</span> is not the conjunction \"and\" — it is the <span class=\"term\">wāw al-qasam</span>, a preposition meaning \"by,\" one of three letters in Arabic used exclusively to introduce oaths (alongside <span class=\"ar-inline\">بـ</span> and <span class=\"ar-inline\">تـ</span>). It governs the following noun in jarr.</p>\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">الْعَصْرُ</span> is therefore an <span class=\"term\">ism majrūr</span> by the wāw al-qasam, its marker of jarr being the visible <span class=\"term\">kasra</span>. The full prepositional phrase (jārr wa-majrūr) is related to a deleted verb of swearing — the implied full expression is أُقْسِمُ بِالْعَصْرِ. This is standard for Qurʾānic oaths: the verb of swearing is always omitted. The entire oath-clause is <span class=\"term\">ibtidāʾiyya</span> — an opening sentence — and thus carries no syntactic position (lā maḥalla lahā min al-iʿrāb).</p>\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">وَ</span><span>Wāw al-qasam — ḥarf jarr used for oaths; not the conjunction wāw.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">الْعَصْرِ</span><span>Ism majrūr by wāw al-qasam; marker of jarr = kasra ẓāhira. Jārr wa-majrūr related to the deleted verb of swearing (fiʿl al-qasam al-maḥdhūf).</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">Jumlat al-qasam</span><span>Ibtidāʾiyya — no syntactic position.</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 2</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">إِنَّ الْإِنسَانَ لَفِى خُسْرٍ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"Indeed, mankind is in loss —\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>This is the <span class=\"term\">jawāb al-qasam</span> — the answer to the oath sworn in verse 1. In Arabic, when an oath is answered by an Inna-sentence, the lām al-tawkīd typically appears in the predicate. Both are present here, making this a doubly emphatic statement.</p>\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">إِنَّ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">ḥarf tawkīd mushabbah bi-l-fiʿl</span> — a particle of emphasis that resembles a verb in that it governs its subject in naṣb (like an accusative) and its predicate remains in rafʿ. <span class=\"ar-inline\">الْإِنسَانَ</span> is the <span class=\"term\">ism Inna</span> in naṣb, marked by visible fatḥa.</p>\n      <p>The predicate (<span class=\"term\">khabar Inna</span>) is the prepositional phrase <span class=\"ar-inline\">لَفِي خُسْرٍ</span>. The lām before it is <span class=\"term\">lām al-tawkīd</span> (the emphatic lām, also called lām al-ibtidāʾ). <span class=\"ar-inline\">فِي خُسْرٍ</span> is a jārr wa-majrūr: <span class=\"ar-inline\">فِي</span> is a preposition and <span class=\"ar-inline\">خُسْرٍ</span> is its object in jarr by kasra, with tanwīn (indefinite). The prepositional phrase together forms the khabar — it hangs on the understood predicate \"is/exists in loss.\" The full Inna-sentence, as jawāb al-qasam, carries no syntactic position.</p>\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">إِنَّ</span><span>Ḥarf tawkīd mushabbah bi-l-fiʿl (governs ism in naṣb, khabar in rafʿ).</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">الْإِنسَانَ</span><span>Ism Inna manṣūb bi-fatḥa ẓāhira.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">لَـ</span><span>Lām al-tawkīd (emphatic lām in the khabar).</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">فِي خُسْرٍ</span><span>Jārr wa-majrūr; together = khabar Inna. خُسْرٍ in jarr by kasra + tanwīn.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">Jumlat Inna</span><span>Jawāb qasam maḥdhūf — no syntactic position.</span></div>\n      </div>\n      <div class=\"callout\">\n        <div class=\"callout-title\">Why is the khabar a prepositional phrase?</div>\n        Arabic predicates are not always nouns or adjectives. A jārr wa-majrūr (prepositional phrase) can serve as the khabar directly — it implies an underlying verb like \"is settled\" or \"exists.\" So لَفِي خُسْرٍ literally means \"[existing] in loss.\" This is extremely common in Qurʾānic predication.\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 3</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">إِلَّا الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا وَعَمِلُوا الصَّالِحَاتِ وَتَوَاصَوْا بِالْحَقِّ وَتَوَاصَوْا بِالصَّبْرِ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"— except those who believe, do righteous deeds, enjoin one another to truth, and enjoin one another to patience.\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">إِلَّا</span> is a <span class=\"term\">ḥarf istithhnāʾ</span> — a particle of exception. It excepts <span class=\"ar-inline\">الَّذِينَ</span> from the universal statement of verse 2 (all of mankind is in loss).</p>\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">الَّذِينَ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">ism mawṣūl</span> (relative pronoun) built on fatḥ — it is indeclinable in itself but occupies the position of naṣb as the <span class=\"term\">mustathnā</span> (the excepted noun). After an affirmative sentence, the mustathnā with إِلَّا takes naṣb.</p>\n\n      <p>The four verbs that follow are the <span class=\"term\">ṣilat al-mawṣūl</span> — the relative clause defining who الَّذِينَ refers to. Relative clauses in Arabic always have no syntactic position of their own (lā maḥalla lahā min al-iʿrāb).</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">آمَنُوا</span> is a fiʿl māḍī built on ḍamma — the sign that wāw al-jamāʿa is attached. The <span class=\"ar-inline\">وَاو</span> is the <span class=\"term\">fāʿil</span> in rafʿ position, and the final <span class=\"ar-inline\">أَلِف</span> is the <span class=\"term\">alif fāriqa</span> — a purely orthographic marker that distinguishes the wāw al-jamāʿa from a regular final wāw. It has no grammatical function and is not pronounced.</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">وَعَمِلُوا</span> is coordinated on آمَنُوا by wāw and carries the identical iʿrāb. Its object is <span class=\"ar-inline\">الصَّالِحَاتِ</span>, which is a <span class=\"term\">mafʿūl bihi</span> — but here marked by <span class=\"term\">kasra</span> rather than the expected fatḥa. This is because الصَّالِحَاتِ is a <span class=\"term\">jamʿ muʾannath sālim</span> (sound feminine plural), and the grammatical rule is that this pattern takes kasra as its naṣb marker instead of fatḥa. This is one of the four exceptional naṣb markers in Arabic.</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">وَتَوَاصَوْا</span> introduces a subtler morphological point. The base form is تَوَاصَوْا, a fiʿl māḍī on the scale of تَفَاعَلَ. Its final vowel is a ḍamma <span class=\"term\">muqaddara</span> — a hidden ḍamma on the original alif of the root, which was deleted because of التقاء الساكنين (the meeting of two sukūns: the sukūn of the alif + the sukūn of the wāw al-jamāʿa that followed it). So the alif drops and the wāw al-jamāʿa directly follows the sīn. The fāʿil is again the wāw in rafʿ position; the alif fāriqa follows. <span class=\"ar-inline\">بِالْحَقِّ</span> is a jārr wa-majrūr related to تواصوا.</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">وَتَوَاصَوْا بِالصَّبْرِ</span> is coordinated on the preceding تَوَاصَوْا بِالْحَقِّ by wāw and carries the same iʿrāb throughout.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">إِلَّا</span><span>Ḥarf istithhnāʾ (particle of exception).</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">الَّذِينَ</span><span>Ism mawṣūl mabni ʿalā al-fatḥ; in naṣb position as mustathnā.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">آمَنُوا</span><span>Fiʿl māḍī mabni ʿalā al-ḍamma; wāw = fāʿil in rafʿ; alif = alif fāriqa (orthographic only). Ṣilat al-mawṣūl — no syntactic position.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">وَعَمِلُوا</span><span>Maʿṭūfa on آمَنُوا by wāw; identical iʿrāb.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">الصَّالِحَاتِ</span><span>Mafʿūl bihi — naṣb marked by kasra (not fatḥa) because it is jamʿ muʾannath sālim.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">وَتَوَاصَوْا</span><span>Fiʿl māḍī; ḍamma muqaddara on the deleted alif (removed due to التقاء الساكنين with wāw al-jamāʿa); wāw = fāʿil in rafʿ; alif fāriqa.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">بِالْحَقِّ / بِالصَّبْرِ</span><span>Jārr wa-majrūr mutaʿalliqān bi-\"tawāṣaw\" in each case.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">وَتَوَاصَوْا بِالصَّبْرِ</span><span>Maʿṭūfa on تَوَاصَوْا بِالْحَقِّ; same iʿrāb throughout.</span></div>\n      </div>\n\n      <div class=\"callout\">\n        <div class=\"callout-title\">The four exceptional naṣb markers — a reference point</div>\n        Arabic has four patterns where naṣb is NOT marked by fatḥa:\n        <br>1. Jamʿ muʾannath sālim → kasra (e.g. الصَّالِحَاتِ here)\n        <br>2. Jamʿ taksīr ghayr munsarif (diptote plurals) → fatḥa standing in for kasra\n        <br>3. Asmāʾ al-sitta (the six nouns: أَب، أَخ، etc.) → alif in naṣb\n        <br>4. Muthannā (dual) → yāʾ in naṣb\n        <br>الصَّالِحَاتِ in this verse is the cleanest classroom example of rule 1.\n      </div>\n\n      <div class=\"callout\">\n        <div class=\"callout-title\">Alif fāriqa — what is it for?</div>\n        After a wāw al-jamāʿa at the end of a verb (آمَنُوا، عَمِلُوا، تَوَاصَوْا), Arabic orthography adds a silent alif. It has no grammatical function and is never pronounced — it exists solely to distinguish the verbal wāw al-jamāʿa from a wāw that is part of the root. A helpful rule: any final alif after a verbal wāw is fāriqa.\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <hr class=\"divider\">\n\n  <div class=\"theme-box\">\n    <h3>Structural summary</h3>\n    <div class=\"theme-grid\">\n      <div class=\"theme-card\">\n        <div class=\"theme-card-label\">Verse 1</div>\n        Wāw al-qasam + ism majrūr (kasra). Jārr wa-majrūr related to deleted fiʿl al-qasam. Jumlah ibtidāʾiyya — no position.\n      </div>\n      <div class=\"theme-card\">\n        <div class=\"theme-card-label\">Verse 2</div>\n        Jawāb al-qasam: Inna (ism in naṣb) + lām al-tawkīd + khabar as jārr wa-majrūr. Jumlah Inna = jawāb qasam — no position.\n      </div>\n      <div class=\"theme-card\">\n        <div class=\"theme-card-label\">Verse 3</div>\n        Istithhnāʾ: إِلَّا + ism mawṣūl (mustathnā in naṣb). Four-verb ṣila (no position). Key points: ḍamma muqaddara on تَوَاصَوْا; kasra as naṣb-marker on الصَّالِحَاتِ (JMS); alif fāriqa throughout.\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n</div>","takathur":"<div class=\"book\">\n\n  <div class=\"surah-header\">\n    <div class=\"surah-label\">Sūrah 102 · Makkī · 8 verses</div>\n    <div class=\"surah-title-en\">Rivalry in World Increase</div>\n    <div class=\"surah-title-ar\">سُورَةُ التَّكَاثُرِ</div>\n    <div class=\"surah-meta\">Named after the opening theme of mutual rivalry in amassing wealth and children. The sūrah moves from a blunt accusation (verses 1–2), through an escalating triple warning (3–5), to a solemn oath-backed threat of seeing Hell (6–7), and closes with the ultimate accountability before God (8).</div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"intro-box\">\n    The surah has a stark two-part movement: verses 1–5 address the heedless in the second person (you), and verses 6–8 shift to the solemn register of oaths and the passive voice of divine judgment. Watch how كَلَّا appears three times — each time with greater weight — before the scene pivots to the Hereafter.\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"section-head\">Part I — The Indictment (Verses 1–2)</div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 1</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">أَلْهَاكُمُ التَّكَاثُرُ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"Rivalry in worldly increase has distracted you —\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>This is a verbally-launched sentence (<span class=\"term\">jumlah fiʿliyya</span>) that opens the surah without preamble. <span class=\"ar-inline\">أَلْهَاكُمُ</span> is a past-tense verb (<span class=\"term\">fiʿl māḍī</span>) built on an implicit <span class=\"term\">fatḥ muqaddar</span> — the usual fatḥa that marks the past tense is \"hidden\" (muqaddar) on the final alif, because Arabic does not pronounce a short vowel on alif. This is called <span class=\"term\">taʿadhdhur</span> (impossibility of pronunciation).</p>\n      <p>The attached <span class=\"ar-inline\">كُمُ</span> is a bound pronoun (<span class=\"term\">ḍamīr muttaṣil</span>) built on ḍamma, serving as the <span class=\"term\">mafʿūl bihi muqaddam</span> — the direct object placed before its subject for rhetorical emphasis. The mīm marks plural. <span class=\"ar-inline\">التَّكَاثُرُ</span> is the <span class=\"term\">fāʿil</span> (subject) in rafʿ, marked by visible ḍamma. The entire sentence is <span class=\"term\">ibtidāʾiyya</span> — an opening sentence with no syntactic position.</p>\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">أَلْهَاكُمُ</span><span>Fiʿl māḍī; fatḥ muqaddar on the alif (taʿadhdhur); كُمُ = ḍamīr muttaṣil in naṣb position as mafʿūl bihi muqaddam; mīm = plurality.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">التَّكَاثُرُ</span><span>Fāʿil marfūʿ bi-ḍamma ẓāhira.</span></div>\n      </div>\n      <div class=\"callout\">\n        <div class=\"callout-title\">What is mafʿūl bihi muqaddam?</div>\n        Normally the order is: verb → subject → object. Here the object كُمُ comes before the subject التَّكَاثُرُ. This front-placement is a rhetorical choice — it puts the accusation directly at \"you\" before naming the culprit. Classical grammarians call this تقديم المفعول (advancing the object).\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 2</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">حَتَّىٰ زُرْتُمُ الْمَقَابِرَ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"— until you visited the graves.\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">حَتَّى</span> here is a <span class=\"term\">ḥarf ibtidāʾ wa-ghāya</span> — a particle of inception and limit, marking the terminal point of the distraction described in verse 1. It introduces a new clause rather than governing a following verb in the subjunctive (as the conjunction ḥattā does).</p>\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">زُرْتُمُ</span> is a fiʿl māḍī built on sukūn, because it is connected to a moving (<span class=\"term\">mutaḥarrik</span>) rafʿ pronoun — the <span class=\"ar-inline\">تُمُ</span>. The tāʾ is the <span class=\"term\">fāʿil</span> in rafʿ position; the mīm marks plurality. <span class=\"ar-inline\">الْمَقَابِرَ</span> is the <span class=\"term\">mafʿūl bihi</span> in naṣb, marked by visible fatḥa.</p>\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">حَتَّى</span><span>Ḥarf ibtidāʾ wa-ghāya (particle of limit/inception).</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">زُرْتُمُ</span><span>Fiʿl māḍī built on sukūn; تُمُ = fāʿil in rafʿ position; mīm = plurality.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">الْمَقَابِرَ</span><span>Mafʿūl bihi manṣūb bi-fatḥa ẓāhira.</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <hr class=\"divider\">\n  <div class=\"section-head\">Part II — The Triple Warning (Verses 3–5)</div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 3</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">كَلَّا سَوْفَ تَعْلَمُونَ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"No indeed! You will come to know.\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">كَلَّا</span> is a particle of sharp rebuke and deterrence (<span class=\"term\">ḥarf radʿ wa-zajr</span>) — it negates and reprimands what preceded in a single word. It is one of the most emphatic refutation-particles in the Qurʾān.</p>\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">سَوْفَ</span> is a particle of the future (<span class=\"term\">ḥarf istiqbāl</span>) that draws a verb into the future tense. <span class=\"ar-inline\">تَعْلَمُونَ</span> is a fiʿl muḍāriʿ in rafʿ — its marker of rafʿ is the <span class=\"term\">thubūt al-nūn</span> (retention of the nūn), the sign of the sound masculine plural verb in the indicative. The <span class=\"ar-inline\">وَاو</span> is the bound subject pronoun in rafʿ. The clause is <span class=\"term\">istinnaāfiyya</span> with no syntactic position.</p>\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">كَلَّا</span><span>Ḥarf radʿ wa-zajr (deterrence particle).</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">سَوْفَ</span><span>Ḥarf istiqbāl (future particle).</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">تَعْلَمُونَ</span><span>Fiʿl muḍāriʿ marfūʿ bi-thubūt al-nūn; wāw = fāʿil in rafʿ.</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 4</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">ثُمَّ كَلَّا سَوْفَ تَعْلَمُونَ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"Again, no indeed! You will come to know.\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">ثُمَّ</span> is a conjunction indicating sequence and additional emphasis. This entire verse is coordinated on verse 3 and carries the identical iʿrāb: كَلَّا (radʿ wa-zajr) + سَوْفَ (ḥarf istiqbāl) + تَعْلَمُونَ (muḍāriʿ marfūʿ bi-thubūt al-nūn, wāw = fāʿil). The repetition is itself a rhetorical device — the warning is doubled, then further escalated in verse 5.</p>\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">ثُمَّ</span><span>Ḥarf ʿaṭf (conjunction of sequence/addition).</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">Rest of verse</span><span>Identical iʿrāb to verse 3 — coordinated (maʿṭūfa) on it in full.</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 5</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">كَلَّا لَوْ تَعْلَمُونَ عِلْمَ الْيَقِينِ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"No indeed! If only you knew with the knowledge of certainty —\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>The third and most weighty use of كَلَّا. Here <span class=\"ar-inline\">لَوْ</span> shifts the register entirely. Classically it is analyzed as a <span class=\"term\">ḥarf sharṭ ghayr jāzim</span> — a conditional particle that does not make its verb apocopate — whose answer is deleted. The implied answer (jawāb al-sharṭ al-maḥdhūf) would be something like \"you would do what cannot be described\" (لَفَعَلْتُمْ مَا لَا يُوصَفُ). Some grammarians read لَوْ here as a particle of wishing (<span class=\"term\">ḥarf tamannī</span>) — either reading is valid.</p>\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">تَعْلَمُونَ</span> is again fiʿl muḍāriʿ marfūʿ bi-thubūt al-nūn. <span class=\"ar-inline\">عِلْمَ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">mafʿūl muṭlaq</span> (cognate/absolute accusative) in naṣb by fatḥa, and it is a muḍāf. <span class=\"ar-inline\">الْيَقِينِ</span> is its <span class=\"term\">muḍāf ilayhi</span> in jarr by kasra. The whole conditional clause is <span class=\"term\">istinnaāfiyya</span> with no syntactic position.</p>\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">لَوْ</span><span>Ḥarf sharṭ ghayr jāzim; jawāb al-sharṭ deleted (implied: \"you would do the indescribable\"). Alternatively: ḥarf tamannī (wish particle).</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">تَعْلَمُونَ</span><span>Fiʿl muḍāriʿ marfūʿ bi-thubūt al-nūn; wāw = fāʿil.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">عِلْمَ</span><span>Mafʿūl muṭlaq manṣūb bi-fatḥa; muḍāf.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">الْيَقِينِ</span><span>Muḍāf ilayhi majrūr bi-kasra ẓāhira.</span></div>\n      </div>\n      <div class=\"callout\">\n        <div class=\"callout-title\">Mafʿūl muṭlaq — the cognate accusative</div>\n        عِلْمَ is derived from the same root as تَعْلَمُونَ (ع-ل-م). When a verbal noun of the same root as the verb follows it in naṣb, it is called a mafʿūl muṭlaq. It intensifies the action — not just \"if you knew\" but \"if you knew with a knowing,\" i.e. with true, deep knowledge. The iḍāfa to الْيَقِينِ further specifies the quality of that knowledge.\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <hr class=\"divider\">\n  <div class=\"section-head\">Part III — The Oath and the Reckoning (Verses 6–8)</div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 6</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">لَتَرَوُنَّ الْجَحِيمَ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"You will surely see the Blazing Fire —\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>The opening lām (<span class=\"ar-inline\">لَـ</span>) is the <span class=\"term\">lām al-qasam</span> — it occurs in the answer to an implicit, deleted oath. The full implied expression is: \"By God, you will surely see Hell.\" This lām is called <span class=\"term\">wāqiʿ fī jawāb qasam maḥdhūf</span>.</p>\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">تَرَوُنَّ</span> has a layered morphology. The base verb is <span class=\"ar-inline\">تَرَوْنَ</span> (you [pl.] see), but the <span class=\"term\">nūn al-tawkīd al-thaqīla</span> (heavy emphatic nūn) has been attached, which causes several changes: (1) the wāw and nūn of the original plural suffix clash with the emphatic nūn — the wāw is deleted to avoid two sukūns meeting, and (2) what remains is the emphatic nūn alone as a marker of emphasis. The wāw of the plural (deleted) was the <span class=\"term\">fāʿil</span> in rafʿ position; the emphatic nūn is simply a <span class=\"term\">ḥarf tawkīd</span>. The verb itself is <span class=\"term\">mabni</span> (indeclinable) due to its attachment to the emphatic nūn. The sentence (as part of the oath-answer) is <span class=\"term\">istinnaāfiyya</span> with no syntactic position.</p>\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">الْجَحِيمَ</span> is the mafʿūl bihi in naṣb by visible fatḥa.</p>\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">لَـ</span><span>Lām al-qasam — answer to a deleted oath (\"By God...\"). Called wāqiʿ fī jawāb qasam maḥdhūf.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">تَرَوُنَّ</span><span>Fiʿl muḍāriʿ mabni (due to nūn al-tawkīd); wāw al-jamāʿa deleted (clash of sākinayn); deleted wāw = fāʿil in rafʿ position; نَّ = ḥarf tawkīd.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">الْجَحِيمَ</span><span>Mafʿūl bihi manṣūb bi-fatḥa ẓāhira.</span></div>\n      </div>\n      <div class=\"callout\">\n        <div class=\"callout-title\">Why is the wāw deleted?</div>\n        Arabic avoids two consecutive sukūns (التقاء الساكنين). The wāw of تَرَوْنَ carries sukūn; the emphatic nūن also arrives on sukūn. Arabic resolves this by deleting the wāw. The original plural marker is therefore only \"remembered\" — it remains as the logical fāʿil even though it has been dropped phonologically.\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 7</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">ثُمَّ لَتَرَوُنَّهَا عَيْنَ الْيَقِينِ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"Then you will see it with the eye of certainty.\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>The <span class=\"ar-inline\">ثُمَّ</span> sequences this on verse 6 — a second, even more immersive seeing. The verb <span class=\"ar-inline\">لَتَرَوُنَّ</span> carries the same iʿrāb as verse 6, with one addition: the attached <span class=\"ar-inline\">هَا</span> is a bound pronoun in the position of naṣb as the <span class=\"term\">mafʿūl bihi</span>, referring to the Jaḥīm (Hell) mentioned previously. It is built on sukūn.</p>\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">عَيْنَ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">mafʿūl muṭlaq</span> in naṣb (by fatḥa), parallel to <span class=\"ar-inline\">عِلْمَ الْيَقِينِ</span> in verse 5 — both are cognate-style accusatives intensifying the manner of the action. <span class=\"ar-inline\">الْيَقِينِ</span> is again the muḍāf ilayhi in jarr by kasra.</p>\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">ثُمَّ</span><span>Ḥarf ʿaṭf.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">لَتَرَوُنَّ</span><span>Same iʿrāb as verse 6; coordinated on it.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">هَا</span><span>Ḍamīr muttaṣil mabni ʿalā al-sukūn in naṣb position as mafʿūl bihi (referring to الْجَحِيمَ).</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">عَيْنَ</span><span>Mafʿūl muṭlaq manṣūb bi-fatḥa; muḍāf.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">الْيَقِينِ</span><span>Muḍāf ilayhi majrūr bi-kasra ẓāhira.</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 8</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">ثُمَّ لَتُسْأَلُنَّ يَوْمَئِذٍ عَنِ النَّعِيمِ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"Then on that Day you will surely be questioned about the blessings.\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>The closing verse shifts from active seeing to passive being-questioned — a deliberate grammatical choice. <span class=\"ar-inline\">لَتُسْأَلُنَّ</span> is a passive verb (<span class=\"term\">fiʿl muḍāriʿ li-l-majhūl</span>) made indeclinable (<span class=\"term\">mabni</span>) by the attachment of nūn al-tawkīd al-thaqīla. The wāw al-jamāʿa (deleted for the same phonological reason as verse 6 — التقاء الساكنين) remains as the implicit <span class=\"term\">nāʾib al-fāʿil</span> in rafʿ position. The emphatic nūn is again a ḥarf tawkīd.</p>\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">يَوْمَئِذٍ</span> carries the same complex iʿrāb as in Sūrat al-ʿĀdiyāt (verse 11): a ẓarf zamān in naṣb by fatḥa, itself the muḍāf; <span class=\"ar-inline\">إِذٍ</span> is an indeclinable noun built on sukūn but given kasra to break the double-sukūn clash (its own sukūn meets the sukūn of its tanwīn), in the position of jarr as muḍāf ilayhi; and the tanwīn compensates for the deleted sentence it stands for (\"the day when the graves are scattered…\").</p>\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">عَنِ النَّعِيمِ</span> is a prepositional phrase related to <span class=\"ar-inline\">تُسْأَلُنَّ</span>, the natural complement of \"being questioned about.\" The verse is coordinated on the oath-sequence started in verse 6 and carries no syntactic position.</p>\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">لَتُسْأَلُنَّ</span><span>Fiʿl muḍāriʿ li-l-majhūl mabni (due to nūn al-tawkīd); deleted wāw al-jamāʿa = nāʾib fāʿil in rafʿ position; نَّ = ḥarf tawkīd.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">يَوْمَئِذٍ</span><span>Ẓarf zamān manṣūb; يَوْم (muḍāf) + إِذٍ (muḍāf ilayhi in jarr position, kasra to break double sukūn, tanwīn compensates deleted clause).</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">عَنِ النَّعِيمِ</span><span>Jārr wa-majrūr mutaʿalliqān bi-\"tusʾalan.\"</span></div>\n      </div>\n      <div class=\"callout\">\n        <div class=\"callout-title\">Active → passive: the rhetorical shift</div>\n        Verses 6–7 use active verbs (you will see). Verse 8 switches to the passive (you will be questioned). This is not accidental — it places the human beings in a position of complete subjection before God on that Day. They are no longer agents; they are the ones acted upon.\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <hr class=\"divider\">\n\n  <div class=\"theme-box\">\n    <h3>Structural summary</h3>\n    <div class=\"theme-grid\">\n      <div class=\"theme-card\">\n        <div class=\"theme-card-label\">Verses 1–2</div>\n        Opening indictment: jumlah fiʿliyya with mafʿūl muqaddam (كُمُ before subject). ḥattā marks the terminal point — rivalry ends only at the grave.\n      </div>\n      <div class=\"theme-card\">\n        <div class=\"theme-card-label\">Verses 3–4</div>\n        Double warning: كَلَّا + سَوْفَ + تَعْلَمُونَ, repeated with ثُمَّ. Verb: muḍāriʿ marfūʿ bi-thubūt al-nūn.\n      </div>\n      <div class=\"theme-card\">\n        <div class=\"theme-card-label\">Verse 5</div>\n        Escalation: لَوْ introduces a conditional (jawāb maḥdhūf). عِلْمَ الْيَقِينِ = mafʿūl muṭlaq + iḍāfa — deepens the emphasis on the quality of knowing.\n      </div>\n      <div class=\"theme-card\">\n        <div class=\"theme-card-label\">Verses 6–8</div>\n        Oath-answer sequence (lām al-qasam). Verb mabni due to nūn al-tawkīd; wāw deleted (التقاء الساكنين). Verse 8 shifts to passive (majhūl) — humanity as object of divine questioning.\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n</div>","burooj":"<div class=\"book\">\n\n  <div class=\"surah-header\">\n    <div class=\"surah-label\">Sūrah 85 · Makkī · 22 verses</div>\n    <div class=\"surah-title-en\">The Constellations</div>\n    <div class=\"surah-title-ar\">سُورَةُ الْبُرُوجِ</div>\n    <div class=\"surah-meta\">A longer Makkī surah with a rich variety of structures. It opens with a multi-item oath whose جَوَاب is deleted (vv. 1–3), narrates the People of the Trench (vv. 4–9), then delivers a sequence of إِنَّ-sentences and nominal chains praising God (vv. 10–16), before closing with the story of the armies (vv. 17–22).</div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"intro-box\">\n    Key iʿrāb points to watch: (1) the deleted جَوَاب الْقَسَم spanning vv. 1–4; (2) بَدَل اشْتِمَال in v.5; (3) إِذْ as مَفْعُول بِهِ of a deleted اذْكُر in v.6; (4) the أَنْ مَصْدَرِيَّة construction in v.8; (5) the الْمَمْنُوع مِن الصَّرْف nouns (جَهَنَّمَ، فِرْعَوْنَ، ثَمُود) marked by فَتْحَة instead of كَسْرَة; (6) multiple خَبَر stacking on هُوَ in vv. 14–16; and (7) هُوَ as تَوْكِيد (not ضَمِير فَصْل) in v.13.\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"section-head\">Part I — The Oath and the Trench (Verses 1–9)</div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verses 1–3</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">وَالسَّمَآءِ ذَاتِ الْبُرُوجِ ۝ وَالْيَوْمِ الْمَوْعُودِ ۝ وَشَاهِدٍ وَمَشْهُودٍ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"By the sky possessing the constellations — and by the Promised Day — and by the witness and the witnessed —\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>All three verses form a single oath-sequence. The <span class=\"term\">وَاو</span> in each is <span class=\"term\">وَاو الْقَسَم</span> — a حَرْف جَرّ for oaths. <span class=\"ar-inline\">السَّمَاءِ</span> is the <span class=\"term\">مُقْسَم بِهِ</span>, in <span class=\"term\">جَرّ</span> by وَاو الْقَسَم; the جَارّ وَمَجْرُور is مُتَعَلِّق by the deleted <span class=\"term\">فِعْل الْقَسَم</span> (أُقْسِمُ).</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">ذَاتِ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">صِفَة</span> for السَّمَاءِ in <span class=\"term\">جَرّ</span> by <span class=\"term\">كَسْرَة ظَاهِرَة</span>; it is itself a <span class=\"term\">مُضَاف</span>. <span class=\"ar-inline\">الْبُرُوجِ</span> is its <span class=\"term\">مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ</span> in جَرّ. The remaining oath-nouns — <span class=\"ar-inline\">الْيَوْمِ الْمَوْعُودِ</span>, <span class=\"ar-inline\">شَاهِدٍ</span>, <span class=\"ar-inline\">مَشْهُودٍ</span> — are all <span class=\"term\">مَعْطُوف</span> on السَّمَاءِ by وَاو and carry the same iʿrāb: مجرور as part of the oath-chain.</p>\n\n      <p>Critically, the <span class=\"term\">جَوَاب الْقَسَم</span> is <span class=\"term\">مَحْذُوف</span> — deleted. It is inferred from verse 4 (قُتِلَ) — the implied full answer is something like: \"I swear by all these — they (the persecutors) are accursed.\" The oath-clause is <span class=\"term\">اسْتِئْنَافِيَّة</span> — no syntactic position.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">وَالسَّمَاءِ</span><span>وَاو: حَرْف جَرّ لِلْقَسَم. السَّمَاء: مُقْسَم بِهِ مَجْرُور — جَارّ وَمَجْرُور مُتَعَلِّقَان بِفِعْل الْقَسَم الْمَحْذُوف.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">ذَاتِ الْبُرُوجِ</span><span>ذَاتِ: صِفَة لِـ\"السَّمَاء\" مَجْرُورَة بِكَسْرَة — مُضَاف. الْبُرُوجِ: مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ مَجْرُور بِكَسْرَة.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">وَالْيَوْمِ الْمَوْعُودِ</span><span>مَعْطُوف عَلَى \"السَّمَاء\" — تُعْرَب إِعْرَابَهَا. الْمَوْعُودِ: صِفَة مَجْرُورَة بِكَسْرَة.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">وَشَاهِدٍ وَمَشْهُودٍ</span><span>كِلَاهُمَا مَعْطُوف عَلَى \"السَّمَاء\" — مَجْرُور بِكَسْرَة.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">جَوَاب الْقَسَم</span><span>مَحْذُوف — يَدُلُّ عَلَيْهِ \"قُتِلَ أَصْحَابُ الْأُخْدُودِ\" فِي الْآيَة الرَّابِعَة. التَّقْدِير: إِنَّهُمْ مَلْعُونُونَ.</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 4</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">قُتِلَ أَصْحَابُ الْأُخْدُودِ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"Condemned are the People of the Trench —\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">قُتِلَ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">فِعْل مَاضٍ لِلْمَجْهُول</span> — passive past — built on <span class=\"term\">فَتْح</span>. <span class=\"ar-inline\">أَصْحَابُ</span> is the <span class=\"term\">نَائِب الْفَاعِل</span> in <span class=\"term\">رَفْع</span> by <span class=\"term\">ضَمَّة ظَاهِرَة</span>; it is a <span class=\"term\">مُضَاف</span>. <span class=\"ar-inline\">الْأُخْدُودِ</span> is the <span class=\"term\">مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ</span> in <span class=\"term\">جَرّ</span> by <span class=\"term\">كَسْرَة</span>. The sentence is <span class=\"term\">اسْتِئْنَافِيَّة</span> — it also serves as the implied جَوَاب of the oath.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">قُتِلَ</span><span>فِعْل مَاضٍ لِلْمَجْهُول مَبْنِيّ عَلَى الْفَتْح.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">أَصْحَابُ</span><span>نَائِب فَاعِل مَرْفُوع بِضَمَّة ظَاهِرَة — مُضَاف.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">الْأُخْدُودِ</span><span>مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ مَجْرُور بِكَسْرَة.</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 5</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">النَّارِ ذَاتِ الْوَقُودِ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"The fire with plentiful fuel —\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">النَّارِ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">بَدَل اشْتِمَال</span> from <span class=\"ar-inline\">الْأُخْدُودِ</span> in verse 4 — not a simple substitution but a \"containment substitute\": the trench contained the fire, so النَّار elaborates a key attribute of الْأُخْدُود. It follows in <span class=\"term\">جَرّ</span> by كَسْرَة. <span class=\"ar-inline\">ذَاتِ الْوَقُودِ</span> carries the same iʿrāb as ذَاتِ الْبُرُوجِ in verse 1: صِفَة مَجْرُورَة + مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">النَّارِ</span><span>بَدَل اشْتِمَال مِن \"الْأُخْدُودِ\" مَجْرُور بِكَسْرَة.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">ذَاتِ الْوَقُودِ</span><span>تُعْرَب إِعْرَاب \"ذَاتِ الْبُرُوجِ\" — صِفَة مَجْرُورَة + مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ.</span></div>\n      </div>\n\n      <div class=\"callout\">\n        <div class=\"callout-title\">بَدَل اشْتِمَال — the containment substitute</div>\n        Arabic grammar identifies four types of بَدَل. بَدَل اشْتِمَال (containment substitution) occurs when the بَدَل names something contained within or associated with the مُبْدَل مِنْهُ — not the same thing (بَدَل كُلٍّ) nor a part of it (بَدَل بَعْض). Here النَّار is an attribute/component of the Trench, not identical to it or a mere portion. The key test: could you say \"the trench, specifically its fire\"? Yes — so it is اشْتِمَال.\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verses 6–7</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">إِذْ هُمْ عَلَيْهَا قُعُودٌ ۝ وَهُمْ عَلَىٰ مَا يَفْعَلُونَ بِالْمُؤْمِنِينَ شُهُودٌ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"When they sat by it — and were witnesses to what they did to the believers.\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">إِذْ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">ظَرْف زَمَان</span> built on <span class=\"term\">سُكُون</span>, here in the position of <span class=\"term\">نَصْب</span> as <span class=\"term\">مَفْعُول بِهِ</span> for a deleted verb <span class=\"ar-inline\">اذْكُرْ</span> (\"remember when...\"). This is a common Qurʾānic use of إِذْ — not strictly temporal but acting as the object of an implied imperative of remembrance.</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">هُمْ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير رَفْع مُنْفَصِل</span> in <span class=\"term\">رَفْع</span> as <span class=\"term\">مُبْتَدَأ</span>. <span class=\"ar-inline\">عَلَيْهَا</span> is a <span class=\"term\">جَارّ وَمَجْرُور</span> مُتَعَلِّق by the خَبَر. <span class=\"ar-inline\">قُعُودٌ</span> is the <span class=\"term\">خَبَر</span> in رَفْع by ضَمَّة. The nominal sentence is in the position of <span class=\"term\">جَرّ</span> as the <span class=\"term\">مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ</span> of إِذْ.</p>\n\n      <p>Verse 7 is coordinated on verse 6. <span class=\"ar-inline\">مَا</span> is an <span class=\"term\">اسْم مَوْصُول</span> in <span class=\"term\">جَرّ</span> by عَلَى; the جَارّ وَمَجْرُور is مُتَعَلِّق by the خَبَر <span class=\"ar-inline\">شُهُودٌ</span>. <span class=\"ar-inline\">يَفْعَلُونَ</span> is the <span class=\"term\">صِلَة الْمَوْصُول</span> — رَفْع by ثُبُوت النُّون, وَاو = فَاعِل. <span class=\"ar-inline\">بِالْمُؤْمِنِينَ</span> is مُتَعَلِّق by يَفْعَلُونَ; its جَرّ marker is <span class=\"term\">يَاء</span> — جَمْع مُذَكَّر سَالِم.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">إِذْ</span><span>ظَرْف زَمَان مَبْنِيّ عَلَى السُّكُون فِي مَحَلِّ نَصْب مَفْعُول بِهِ لِـ\"اذْكُرْ\" الْمَحْذُوف.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">هُمْ / قُعُودٌ</span><span>مُبْتَدَأ + خَبَر. الْجُمْلَة فِي مَحَلِّ جَرّ بِالْإِضَافَة (مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ لِـ\"إِذْ\").</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">بِالْمُؤْمِنِينَ</span><span>جَارّ وَمَجْرُور — عَلَامَة جَرِّهِ الْيَاء (جَمْع مُذَكَّر سَالِم).</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">شُهُودٌ</span><span>خَبَر \"هُمْ\" مَرْفُوع بِضَمَّة. الْجُمْلَة مَعْطُوفَة عَلَى \"هُمْ عَلَيْهَا قُعُودٌ\" فِي مَحَلِّ جَرّ.</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 8</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">وَمَا نَقَمُوا مِنْهُمْ إِلَّآ أَن يُؤْمِنُوا بِاللَّهِ الْعَزِيزِ الْحَمِيدِ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"And they resented them for nothing other than that they believed in God, the Almighty, the Praiseworthy —\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">مَا</span> is a <span class=\"term\">حَرْف نَفْي لَا عَمَل لَهُ</span>. <span class=\"ar-inline\">نَقَمُوا</span> is a <span class=\"term\">فِعْل مَاضٍ مَبْنِيّ عَلَى الضَّمّ</span> — connected to وَاو الْجَمَاعَة; the وَاو is فَاعِل in رَفْع; the أَلِف is <span class=\"term\">فَارِقَة</span>. <span class=\"ar-inline\">مِنْهُمْ</span> is جَارّ وَمَجْرُور مُتَعَلِّق بِـ\"نَقَمُوا\". The sentence is <span class=\"term\">اسْتِئْنَافِيَّة</span>.</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">إِلَّا</span> is a <span class=\"term\">حَرْف حَصْر لَا عَمَل لَهُ</span> (here used for restriction, not exception after a positive sentence). <span class=\"ar-inline\">أَنْ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">حَرْف مَصْدَرِيَّة وَنَصْب</span>. <span class=\"ar-inline\">يُؤْمِنُوا</span> is a <span class=\"term\">فِعْل مُضَارِع مَنْصُوب بِأَنْ</span> — its <span class=\"term\">عَلَامَة نَصْب</span> is <span class=\"term\">حَذْف النُّون</span>; the وَاو is فَاعِل. Together, أَنْ + يُؤْمِنُوا forms a <span class=\"term\">مَصْدَر مُؤَوَّل</span> (implied verbal noun: \"their believing\") — the implied مَفْعُول لِأَجْلِهِ or the limited cause of the persecution. <span class=\"ar-inline\">الْعَزِيزِ الْحَمِيدِ</span> are two <span class=\"term\">صِفَتَان</span> for لَفْظ الْجَلَالَة in جَرّ by كَسْرَة.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">نَقَمُوا</span><span>فِعْل مَاضٍ مَبْنِيّ عَلَى الضَّمّ — وَاو الْجَمَاعَة فَاعِل. الْأَلِف: فَارِقَة.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">إِلَّا</span><span>حَرْف حَصْر — لَا عَمَل لَهُ.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">أَنْ يُؤْمِنُوا</span><span>أَنْ: حَرْف مَصْدَرِيَّة وَنَصْب. يُؤْمِنُوا: مُضَارِع مَنْصُوب بِحَذْف النُّون. وَاو: فَاعِل. الْمَصْدَر الْمُؤَوَّل (إِيمَانُهُمْ) = الْمَفْعُول الضِّمْنِيّ لِلنَّفْي.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">الْعَزِيزِ الْحَمِيدِ</span><span>صِفَتَان لِلَفْظِ الْجَلَالَة مَجْرُورَتَان بِكَسْرَة.</span></div>\n      </div>\n\n      <div class=\"callout\">\n        <div class=\"callout-title\">أَنْ الْمَصْدَرِيَّة — the implied verbal noun</div>\n        أَنْ + مُضَارِع منصوب creates a مَصْدَر مُؤَوَّل — an implied verbal noun. أَنْ يُؤْمِنُوا = إِيمَانُهُمْ (\"their believing\"). This مَصْدَر مُؤَوَّل then slots into the sentence structure as a noun would — here functioning as the thing resented (the object implied by the negation + إِلَّا restriction). The نُون is deleted as the standard عَلَامَة نَصْب for sound masculine plural مُضَارِع.\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 9</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">الَّذِى لَهُۥ مُلْكُ السَّمَـٰوَاتِ وَالْأَرْضِ وَاللَّهُ عَلَىٰ كُلِّ شَىْءٍ شَهِيدٌ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"To whom belongs the dominion of the heavens and the earth — and God is witness over all things.\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">الَّذِي</span> is an <span class=\"term\">اسْم مَوْصُول</span> in the position of <span class=\"term\">رَفْع</span> as <span class=\"term\">خَبَر مُبْتَدَأ مَحْذُوف</span> — the implied sentence: هُوَ الَّذِي. This implied sentence is <span class=\"term\">اسْتِئْنَافِيَّة</span>. Inside the صِلَة: <span class=\"ar-inline\">لَهُ</span> is <span class=\"term\">خَبَر مُقَدَّم</span>; <span class=\"ar-inline\">مُلْكُ</span> is <span class=\"term\">مُبْتَدَأ مُؤَخَّر</span> in رَفْع — a مُضَاف; <span class=\"ar-inline\">السَّمَاوَاتِ</span> is مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ in جَرّ; <span class=\"ar-inline\">وَالْأَرْضِ</span> is مَعْطُوف on it. The صِلَة clause has no syntactic position.</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">وَاللَّهُ</span> opens a fresh <span class=\"term\">اسْتِئْنَافِيَّة</span> nominal sentence: لَفْظ الْجَلَالَة as مُبْتَدَأ in رَفْع; <span class=\"ar-inline\">عَلَى كُلِّ شَيْءٍ</span> as جَارّ وَمَجْرُور مُتَعَلِّق by <span class=\"ar-inline\">شَهِيدٌ</span>; <span class=\"ar-inline\">شَهِيدٌ</span> as خَبَر in رَفْع by ضَمَّة.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">الَّذِي</span><span>اسْم مَوْصُول فِي مَحَلِّ رَفْع خَبَر مُبْتَدَأ مَحْذُوف (هُوَ).</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">لَهُ مُلْكُ</span><span>خَبَر مُقَدَّم + مُبْتَدَأ مُؤَخَّر (مُضَاف). جُمْلَة \"لَهُ مُلْكُ...\" صِلَة الْمَوْصُول — لَا مَحَلَّ لَهَا.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">وَاللَّهُ ... شَهِيدٌ</span><span>جُمْلَة اسْمِيَّة اسْتِئْنَافِيَّة: مُبْتَدَأ + جَارّ وَمَجْرُور مُتَعَلِّق بِالْخَبَر + خَبَر مَرْفُوع.</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <hr class=\"divider\">\n  <div class=\"section-head\">Part II — The Two Groups and God's Attributes (Verses 10–16)</div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 10</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">إِنَّ الَّذِينَ فَتَنُوا الْمُؤْمِنِينَ وَالْمُؤْمِنَاتِ ثُمَّ لَمْ يَتُوبُوا فَلَهُمْ عَذَابُ جَهَنَّمَ وَلَهُمْ عَذَابُ الْحَرِيقِ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"Indeed those who persecuted the believing men and women, then did not repent — for them is the punishment of Hell, and for them is the punishment of burning.\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">إِنَّ</span> is the <span class=\"term\">حَرْف تَوْكِيد مُشَبَّه بِالْفِعْل</span>. <span class=\"ar-inline\">الَّذِينَ</span> is its <span class=\"term\">اسْم</span> in <span class=\"term\">نَصْب</span>, built on سُكُون. <span class=\"ar-inline\">فَتَنُوا</span> is <span class=\"term\">فِعْل مَاضٍ مَبْنِيّ عَلَى الضَّمّ</span> (وَاو الْجَمَاعَة attached); وَاو = فَاعِل; أَلِف = فَارِقَة. Its صِلَة has no position.</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">الْمُؤْمِنِينَ</span> is <span class=\"term\">مَفْعُول بِهِ مَنْصُوب بِالْيَاء</span> — جَمْع مُذَكَّر سَالِم. <span class=\"ar-inline\">وَالْمُؤْمِنَاتِ</span> is مَعْطُوف, <span class=\"term\">مَنْصُوب بِالْكَسْرَة</span> — because it is a <span class=\"term\">جَمْع مُؤَنَّث سَالِم</span>, which takes كَسْرَة instead of فَتْحَة as its naṣb marker.</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">ثُمَّ لَمْ يَتُوبُوا</span>: ثُمَّ = حَرْف عَطْف; لَمْ = حَرْف نَفْي وَجَزْم وَقَلْب; <span class=\"ar-inline\">يَتُوبُوا</span> = مُضَارِع مَجْزُوم بِحَذْف النُّون; وَاو = فَاعِل; أَلِف = فَارِقَة.</p>\n\n      <p>The <span class=\"term\">فَاء</span> of <span class=\"ar-inline\">فَلَهُمْ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">حَرْف وَاقِع فِي جَوَاب الَّذِينَ</span> — because الَّذِينَ carries an implied conditional meaning (\"those who... then...\"), its جَوَاب is introduced by فَاء. <span class=\"ar-inline\">لَهُمْ</span> is خَبَر مُقَدَّم; <span class=\"ar-inline\">عَذَابُ</span> is <span class=\"term\">مُبْتَدَأ مُؤَخَّر</span> in رَفْع. <span class=\"ar-inline\">جَهَنَّمَ</span> is مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ, but its جَرّ marker is <span class=\"term\">فَتْحَة</span> — because جَهَنَّم is <span class=\"term\">مَمْنُوع مِن الصَّرْف</span> (a diptote, non-declinable: it is feminine and foreign in origin). The جَرّ of الْمَمْنُوع مِن الصَّرْف is always فَتْحَة. The whole clause \"لَهُمْ عَذَابُ جَهَنَّمَ\" is in the position of <span class=\"term\">رَفْع</span> as <span class=\"term\">خَبَر إِنَّ</span>.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">الَّذِينَ</span><span>اسْم \"إِنَّ\" مَبْنِيّ عَلَى السُّكُون فِي مَحَلِّ نَصْب.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">الْمُؤْمِنِينَ</span><span>مَفْعُول بِهِ مَنْصُوب بِالْيَاء — جَمْع مُذَكَّر سَالِم.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">وَالْمُؤْمِنَاتِ</span><span>مَعْطُوف — مَنْصُوب بِالْكَسْرَة (جَمْع مُؤَنَّث سَالِم).</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">لَمْ يَتُوبُوا</span><span>لَمْ: نَفْي وَجَزْم وَقَلْب. يَتُوبُوا: مَجْزُوم بِحَذْف النُّون. وَاو: فَاعِل. أَلِف: فَارِقَة.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">فَلَهُمْ عَذَابُ</span><span>فَاء: وَاقِعَة فِي جَوَاب \"الَّذِينَ\" (لِمَعْنَى الشَّرْط). خَبَر مُقَدَّم + مُبْتَدَأ مُؤَخَّر. جُمْلَة \"لَهُمْ عَذَابُ\" فِي مَحَلِّ رَفْع خَبَر \"إِنَّ\".</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">جَهَنَّمَ</span><span>مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ — مَجْرُور بِالْفَتْحَة (مَمْنُوع مِن الصَّرْف: مُؤَنَّث أَعْجَمِيّ).</span></div>\n      </div>\n\n      <div class=\"callout\">\n        <div class=\"callout-title\">الْمَمْنُوع مِن الصَّرْف — diptote nouns and their جَرّ by فَتْحَة</div>\n        Certain Arabic nouns are \"prevented from full declension\" — they never take tanwīn and, crucially, their جَرّ marker is فَتْحَة instead of كَسْرَة. The main categories include: proper nouns of foreign origin (جَهَنَّمَ، إِبْرَاهِيمَ), proper feminine nouns (فَاطِمَةَ), certain patterns like أَفْعَل (أَحْمَرَ), and plurals on the مَفَاعِل/مَفَاعِيل pattern. When these appear as مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ or after a preposition, look for فَتْحَة — not كَسْرَة — as the جَرّ marker.\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 11</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">إِنَّ الَّذِينَ آمَنُوا وَعَمِلُوا الصَّـٰلِحَاتِ لَهُمْ جَنَّـٰتٌ تَجْرِى مِن تَحْتِهَا الْأَنْهَـٰرُ ذَٰلِكَ الْفَوْزُ الْكَبِيرُ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"Indeed those who believed and did righteous deeds — for them are gardens beneath which rivers flow. That is the great attainment.\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>إِنَّ + الَّذِينَ carries the same iʿrāb as verse 10. <span class=\"ar-inline\">آمَنُوا وَعَمِلُوا</span> are the صِلَة-verbs (past, built on ضَمَّة, وَاو = فَاعِل, أَلِف = فَارِقَة). <span class=\"ar-inline\">الصَّالِحَاتِ</span> is <span class=\"term\">مَفْعُول بِهِ مَنْصُوب بِالْكَسْرَة</span> — جَمْع مُؤَنَّث سَالِم.</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">لَهُمْ</span> is خَبَر مُقَدَّم مَحْذُوف (related to a deleted predicate). <span class=\"ar-inline\">جَنَّاتٌ</span> is <span class=\"term\">مُبْتَدَأ مُؤَخَّر</span> in رَفْع by ضَمَّة. The clause <span class=\"ar-inline\">تَجْرِي مِنْ تَحْتِهَا الْأَنْهَارُ</span> is in the position of <span class=\"term\">رَفْع</span> as a <span class=\"term\">صِفَة</span> for جَنَّاتٌ. Inside it: <span class=\"ar-inline\">تَجْرِي</span> is مُضَارِع مَرْفُوع by <span class=\"term\">ضَمَّة مُقَدَّرَة عَلَى الْيَاء لِلثِّقَل</span>; <span class=\"ar-inline\">مِنْ تَحْتِهَا</span> is جَارّ وَمَجْرُور مُتَعَلِّق by تَجْرِي; <span class=\"ar-inline\">الْأَنْهَارُ</span> is فَاعِل in رَفْع.</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">ذَلِكَ الْفَوْزُ الْكَبِيرُ</span>: ذَا = اسْم إِشَارَة in رَفْع as مُبْتَدَأ; اللَّام = حَرْف بُعْد; كَاف = حَرْف خِطَاب. <span class=\"ar-inline\">الْفَوْزُ</span> is خَبَر in رَفْع; <span class=\"ar-inline\">الْكَبِيرُ</span> is صِفَة in رَفْع. The sentence is <span class=\"term\">اسْتِئْنَافِيَّة</span>.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">الصَّالِحَاتِ</span><span>مَفْعُول بِهِ مَنْصُوب بِالْكَسْرَة — جَمْع مُؤَنَّث سَالِم.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">لَهُمْ جَنَّاتٌ</span><span>خَبَر مُقَدَّم + مُبْتَدَأ مُؤَخَّر. فِي مَحَلِّ رَفْع خَبَر \"إِنَّ\".</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">تَجْرِي</span><span>مَرْفُوع بِضَمَّة مُقَدَّرَة لِلثِّقَل. الْجُمْلَة فِي مَحَلِّ رَفْع صِفَة لِـ\"جَنَّاتٌ\".</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">ذَلِكَ الْفَوْزُ الْكَبِيرُ</span><span>اسْم إِشَارَة (مُبْتَدَأ) + خَبَر + صِفَة. اسْتِئْنَافِيَّة.</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 12</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">إِنَّ بَطْشَ رَبِّكَ لَشَدِيدٌ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"Indeed the grip of your Lord is severe.\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>A clean إِنَّ-sentence. <span class=\"ar-inline\">بَطْشَ</span> is the <span class=\"term\">اسْم إِنَّ</span> in <span class=\"term\">نَصْب</span> by <span class=\"term\">فَتْحَة ظَاهِرَة</span>, and is a <span class=\"term\">مُضَاف</span>. <span class=\"ar-inline\">رَبِّكَ</span>: رَبِّ = مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ in جَرّ by كَسْرَة; itself a مُضَاف; the كَاف = ضَمِير مُتَّصِل in جَرّ by إِضَافَة. <span class=\"ar-inline\">لَشَدِيدٌ</span>: اللَّام = لَام تَوْكِيد; شَدِيدٌ = <span class=\"term\">خَبَر إِنَّ</span> in رَفْع by ضَمَّة ظَاهِرَة. Sentence is <span class=\"term\">اسْتِئْنَافِيَّة</span>.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">بَطْشَ رَبِّكَ</span><span>اسْم \"إِنَّ\" مَنْصُوب بِفَتْحَة — مُضَاف. رَبِّ: مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ مَجْرُور. الْكَاف: مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ ثَانٍ.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">لَشَدِيدٌ</span><span>لَام تَوْكِيد + خَبَر \"إِنَّ\" مَرْفُوع بِضَمَّة ظَاهِرَة.</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 13</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">إِنَّهُۥ هُوَ يُبْدِئُ وَيُعِيدُ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"Indeed He — it is He who originates and repeats.\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">إِنَّهُ</span>: إِنَّ + هَاء (ضَمِير مُتَّصِل مَبْنِيّ عَلَى الضَّمّ in نَصْب position as اسْم إِنَّ). <span class=\"ar-inline\">هُوَ</span> here is a <span class=\"term\">ضَمِير مُنْفَصِل</span> in the position of <span class=\"term\">نَصْب تَوْكِيد</span> — reinforcing the attached هَاء; it is NOT a ضَمِير فَصْل here (because a ضَمِير فَصْل requires both the noun before it and the خَبَر after it to be definite and it separates them — the structure here is different). <span class=\"ar-inline\">يُبْدِئُ</span> is the <span class=\"term\">خَبَر إِنَّ</span> (a verbal clause in the position of رَفْع); مَرْفُوع by ضَمَّة; فَاعِله ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر هُوَ. <span class=\"ar-inline\">وَيُعِيدُ</span> is مَعْطُوف on يُبْدِئُ.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">إِنَّهُ</span><span>إِنَّ: حَرْف تَوْكِيد. الْهَاء: اسْم \"إِنَّ\" فِي مَحَلِّ نَصْب.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">هُوَ</span><span>ضَمِير مُنْفَصِل فِي مَحَلِّ نَصْب تَوْكِيد لِـ\"الْهَاء\" — لَيْسَ ضَمِير فَصْل هُنَا.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">يُبْدِئُ وَيُعِيدُ</span><span>جُمْلَة فِعْلِيَّة فِي مَحَلِّ رَفْع خَبَر \"إِنَّ\". كِلَاهُمَا مَرْفُوع بِضَمَّة — فَاعِل ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر هُوَ.</span></div>\n      </div>\n\n      <div class=\"callout\">\n        <div class=\"callout-title\">هُوَ as تَوْكِيد vs ضَمِير فَصْل</div>\n        In سُورَة الْكَوْثَر v.3 (إِنَّ شَانِئَكَ هُوَ الْأَبْتَرُ), هُوَ is a ضَمِير فَصْل — it stands between the اسْم إِنَّ and the definite خَبَر, separating them and restricting the predication. Here in v.13, هُوَ instead reinforces the attached هَاء pronoun — both refer to the same referent and the خَبَر is a verbal clause (يُبْدِئُ), not a definite noun. The test: if removing هُوَ leaves إِنَّهُ يُبْدِئُ — a grammatically complete sentence — then هُوَ is emphatic تَوْكِيد, not فَصْل.\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verses 14–16</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">وَهُوَ الْغَفُورُ الْوَدُودُ ۝ ذُو الْعَرْشِ الْمَجِيدُ ۝ فَعَّالٌ لِّمَا يُرِيدُ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"And He is the All-Forgiving, the All-Loving — Lord of the Throne, the Glorious — Doer of whatever He wills.\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>These three verses pile four <span class=\"term\">أَخْبَار</span> (predicates) onto the one مُبْتَدَأ <span class=\"ar-inline\">هُوَ</span>. <span class=\"ar-inline\">هُوَ</span> is a ضَمِير رَفْع مُنْفَصِل as مُبْتَدَأ. <span class=\"ar-inline\">الْغَفُورُ</span> is خَبَر أَوَّل in رَفْع by ضَمَّة; <span class=\"ar-inline\">الْوَدُودُ</span> is خَبَر ثَانٍ in رَفْع.</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">ذُو</span> (verse 15) is <span class=\"term\">خَبَر ثَالِث</span> for هُوَ, in <span class=\"term\">رَفْع</span> — but its marker of رَفْع is <span class=\"term\">وَاو</span>, not ضَمَّة. This is because ذُو is one of the <span class=\"term\">أَسْمَاء السِّتَّة</span> (the six nouns) which use letters (وَاو/يَاء/أَلِف) as their case markers instead of short vowels. ذُو is a مُضَاف; <span class=\"ar-inline\">الْعَرْشِ</span> is مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ in جَرّ; <span class=\"ar-inline\">الْمَجِيدُ</span> is صِفَة for ذُو in رَفْع by ضَمَّة.</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">فَعَّالٌ</span> (verse 16) is <span class=\"term\">خَبَر رَابِع</span> for هُوَ — or alternatively خَبَر مُبْتَدَأ مَحْذُوف (هُوَ). <span class=\"ar-inline\">لِمَا</span>: اللَّام = حَرْف جَرّ; مَا = اسْم مَوْصُول in جَرّ, مُتَعَلِّق by فَعَّالٌ. <span class=\"ar-inline\">يُرِيدُ</span> = مُضَارِع مَرْفُوع, فَاعِله ضَمِير مُسْتَتِر هُوَ — صِلَة الْمَوْصُول.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">الْغَفُورُ الْوَدُودُ</span><span>خَبَر أَوَّل وَخَبَر ثَانٍ لِـ\"هُوَ\" — مَرْفُوعَان بِضَمَّة ظَاهِرَة.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">ذُو</span><span>خَبَر ثَالِث — مَرْفُوع بِالْوَاو (مِن الْأَسْمَاء السِّتَّة). مُضَاف. الْعَرْشِ: مُضَاف إِلَيْهِ. الْمَجِيدُ: صِفَة مَرْفُوعَة.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">فَعَّالٌ</span><span>خَبَر رَابِع — أَو خَبَر مُبْتَدَأ مَحْذُوف (هُوَ). مَرْفُوع بِضَمَّة.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">لِمَا يُرِيدُ</span><span>لِ: حَرْف جَرّ. مَا: اسْم مَوْصُول فِي جَرّ — مُتَعَلِّق بِـ\"فَعَّالٌ\". يُرِيدُ: صِلَة الْمَوْصُول — لَا مَحَلَّ لَهَا.</span></div>\n      </div>\n\n      <div class=\"callout\">\n        <div class=\"callout-title\">أَسْمَاء السِّتَّة — رَفْع by وَاو</div>\n        The six nouns (أَب، أَخ، حَم، فُو، هَن، ذُو) use letters as case markers when they are مُضَاف to something other than the يَاء pronoun: رَفْع = وَاو (ذُو)، نَصْب = أَلِف (ذَا)، جَرّ = يَاء (ذِي). Here ذُو الْعَرْشِ is in رَفْع position (as خَبَر) so its marker is وَاو — not ضَمَّة.\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <hr class=\"divider\">\n  <div class=\"section-head\">Part III — The Armies and the Close (Verses 17–22)</div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verses 17–18</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">هَلْ أَتَىٰكَ حَدِيثُ الْجُنُودِ ۝ فِرْعَوْنَ وَثَمُودَ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"Has the story of the armies reached you — Pharaoh and Thamūd?\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">هَلْ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">حَرْف اسْتِفْهَام بِمَعْنَى قَدْ</span> — here conveying affirmation (\"Has it not indeed reached you?\"). <span class=\"ar-inline\">أَتَاكَ</span> is فِعْل مَاضٍ with <span class=\"term\">فَتْح مُقَدَّر</span> on the أَلِف (تَعَذُّر); the كَاف is <span class=\"term\">مَفْعُول بِهِ مُقَدَّم</span> in نَصْب; <span class=\"ar-inline\">حَدِيثُ</span> is the <span class=\"term\">فَاعِل</span> in رَفْع. The sentence is <span class=\"term\">اسْتِئْنَافِيَّة</span>.</p>\n\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">فِرْعَوْنَ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">بَدَل</span> from الْجُنُودِ, in the position of <span class=\"term\">جَرّ</span> — but its جَرّ marker is <span class=\"term\">فَتْحَة</span> because فِرْعَوْن is <span class=\"term\">مَمْنُوع مِن الصَّرْف</span> (foreign proper noun). <span class=\"ar-inline\">وَثَمُودَ</span> is مَعْطُوف on فِرْعَوْنَ — also مَمْنُوع مِن الصَّرْف, جَرّ by فَتْحَة.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">هَلْ</span><span>حَرْف اسْتِفْهَام — هُنَا بِمَعْنَى \"قَدْ\" (لِلتَّحْقِيق).</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">أَتَاكَ</span><span>فَتْح مُقَدَّر (تَعَذُّر). الْكَاف: مَفْعُول بِهِ مُقَدَّم فِي مَحَلِّ نَصْب. حَدِيثُ: فَاعِل مَرْفُوع.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">فِرْعَوْنَ وَثَمُودَ</span><span>بَدَل مِن \"الْجُنُود\" فِي مَحَلِّ جَرّ — مَجْرُور بِالْفَتْحَة (مَمْنُوع مِن الصَّرْف).</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verses 19–20</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">بَلِ الَّذِينَ كَفَرُوا فِى تَكْذِيبٍ ۝ وَاللَّهُ مِن وَرَآئِهِم مُّحِيطٌ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"But the disbelievers are in denial — and God encompasses them from behind.\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">بَلِ</span> is a <span class=\"term\">حَرْف إِضْرَاب</span> (a pivoting particle — \"rather/but\"). It is built on سُكُون but its آخِر is given كَسْرَة to avoid التقاء الساكنين (double sukūn meeting) with the following أَلِف. <span class=\"ar-inline\">الَّذِينَ</span> is اسْم مَوْصُول in رَفْع as مُبْتَدَأ. <span class=\"ar-inline\">كَفَرُوا</span> = صِلَة الْمَوْصُول. <span class=\"ar-inline\">فِي تَكْذِيبٍ</span> is جَارّ وَمَجْرُور مُتَعَلِّق by the خَبَر. The sentence is <span class=\"term\">اسْتِئْنَافِيَّة</span>.</p>\n\n      <p>Verse 20: لَفْظ الْجَلَالَة = مُبْتَدَأ; <span class=\"ar-inline\">مِنْ وَرَائِهِمْ</span> = جَارّ وَمَجْرُور مُتَعَلِّق by الخَبَر; <span class=\"ar-inline\">مُحِيطٌ</span> = خَبَر in رَفْع by ضَمَّة. <span class=\"term\">اسْتِئْنَافِيَّة</span>.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">بَلِ</span><span>حَرْف إِضْرَاب مَبْنِيّ عَلَى السُّكُون — كُسِرَ آخِرُهُ لِالْتِقَاء السَّاكِنَيْن.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">الَّذِينَ كَفَرُوا</span><span>اسْم مَوْصُول = مُبْتَدَأ. كَفَرُوا = صِلَة الْمَوْصُول — لَا مَحَلَّ لَهَا. فِي تَكْذِيبٍ = خَبَر.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">وَاللَّهُ ... مُحِيطٌ</span><span>مُبْتَدَأ + جَارّ وَمَجْرُور مُتَعَلِّق بِالْخَبَر + خَبَر. اسْتِئْنَافِيَّة.</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verses 21–22</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">بَلْ هُوَ قُرْءَانٌ مَّجِيدٌ ۝ فِى لَوْحٍ مَّحْفُوظٍ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"But it is a glorious Qurʾān — in a Preserved Tablet.\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">بَلْ</span> is again حَرْف إِضْرَاب. <span class=\"ar-inline\">هُوَ</span> is ضَمِير رَفْع مُنْفَصِل as مُبْتَدَأ. <span class=\"ar-inline\">قُرْآنٌ</span> is خَبَر in رَفْع by ضَمَّة; <span class=\"ar-inline\">مَجِيدٌ</span> is صِفَة in رَفْع. The sentence is <span class=\"term\">اسْتِئْنَافِيَّة</span>.</p>\n\n      <p>Verse 22: <span class=\"ar-inline\">فِي لَوْحٍ</span> is جَارّ وَمَجْرُور مُتَعَلِّق by a <span class=\"term\">صِفَة ثَانِيَة</span> for قُرْآنٌ (implied: كَائِنٌ فِي لَوْحٍ). <span class=\"ar-inline\">مَحْفُوظٍ</span> is صِفَة for لَوْحٍ in جَرّ by كَسْرَة.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">هُوَ قُرْآنٌ مَجِيدٌ</span><span>مُبْتَدَأ + خَبَر + صِفَة. اسْتِئْنَافِيَّة.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">فِي لَوْحٍ</span><span>جَارّ وَمَجْرُور مُتَعَلِّقَان بِصِفَة ثَانِيَة لِـ\"قُرْآنٌ\".</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">مَحْفُوظٍ</span><span>صِفَة لِـ\"لَوْحٍ\" مَجْرُورَة بِكَسْرَة ظَاهِرَة.</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <hr class=\"divider\">\n\n  <div class=\"theme-box\">\n    <h3>Structural summary</h3>\n    <div class=\"theme-grid\">\n      <div class=\"theme-card\">\n        <div class=\"theme-card-label\">Verses 1–4</div>\n        Three-item oath chain (وَاو الْقَسَم × 4) with deleted جَوَاب الْقَسَم — inferred from v.4. فِعْل مَاضٍ لِلْمَجْهُول (قُتِلَ) + نَائِب فَاعِل.\n      </div>\n      <div class=\"theme-card\">\n        <div class=\"theme-card-label\">Verses 5–7</div>\n        بَدَل اشْتِمَال (النَّار ← الأُخْدُود). إِذْ as مَفْعُول بِهِ of deleted اذْكُرْ. جُمْلَة اسْمِيَّة inside the إِذْ clause in جَرّ position.\n      </div>\n      <div class=\"theme-card\">\n        <div class=\"theme-card-label\">Verses 8–10</div>\n        أَنْ مَصْدَرِيَّة + حَذْف النُّون. إِنَّ + الَّذِينَ with فَاء جَوَاب الشَّرْط الضِّمْنِيّ. الْمَمْنُوع مِن الصَّرْف: جَهَنَّمَ in جَرّ by فَتْحَة.\n      </div>\n      <div class=\"theme-card\">\n        <div class=\"theme-card-label\">Verses 12–16</div>\n        إِنَّ + لَام تَوْكِيد. هُوَ as تَوْكِيد (not فَصْل) in v.13. Four stacked أَخْبَار on هُوَ; ذُو with وَاو رَفْع (أَسْمَاء السِّتَّة). فِرْعَوْن / ثَمُود: بَدَل in جَرّ by فَتْحَة (مَمْنُوع).\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n</div>","adiyat":"<div class=\"book\" id=\"surah-textbook-book\" data-view=\"full\">\n\n  <div class=\"surah-header\">\n    <div class=\"surah-label\">Sūrah 100 · Makkī · 11 verses</div>\n    <div class=\"surah-title-en\">The Charging Mares</div>\n    <div class=\"surah-title-ar\">سُورَةُ الْعَادِيَاتِ</div>\n    <div class=\"surah-meta\">Named after the opening word <span style=\"font-family:'Amiri',serif;font-size:16px;\">الْعَادِيَاتِ</span> — the war-horses that gallop at a charge. The sūrah opens with five vivid oaths sworn by these horses, then pivots to a sharp accusation against ungrateful mankind, and closes with a reminder of the Day of Judgement.</div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"intro-box\">\n    Before studying the iʿrāb verse by verse, note the surah's rhetorical architecture: verses 1–5 form one long oath sworn by five images of warhorses in action; verses 6–8 state the answer to that oath (mankind's ingratitude); verses 9–11 provide the eschatological grounding — why gratitude matters.\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"section-head\">Part I — The Oath (Verses 1–5)</div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 1</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">وَٱلْعَـٰدِيَـٰتِ ضَبْحًا</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"By the charging mares, panting —\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>This verse opens with an oath (<span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">الْقَسَمُ</span>). The letter <span class=\"ar-inline\">وَ</span> here is not the conjunction “and” but <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">وَاوُ الْقَسَمِ</span> — a preposition meaning “by,” used specifically to introduce oaths. It is one of three letters that serve this function in Arabic (the others being <span class=\"ar-inline\">بـ</span> and <span class=\"ar-inline\">تـ</span>).</p>\n      <p>The noun <span class=\"ar-inline\">الْعَادِيَاتُ</span> (the charging ones) is grammatically in the genitive (<span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">الْجَرُّ</span>), governed by <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">وَاوُ الْقَسَمِ</span>. Its <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">عَلَامَةُ الْجَرِّ</span> is <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">الْكَسْرَةُ</span>. The full prepositional phrase hangs on an omitted verb of swearing — in classical analysis, the phrase “وَاللَّهِ” is understood to abbreviate “أُقْسِمُ بِاللَّهِ.” The same is true here: the oath-clause is said to have no syntactic position (<span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">لَا مَحَلَّ لَهَا مِنَ الْإِعْرَابِ</span>) because it is <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">جُمْلَةٌ ابْتِدَائِيَّةٌ</span> — an opening, independent sentence.</p>\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">الْعَادِيَاتِ</span><span lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">اسْمٌ مَجْرُورٌ بِوَاوِ الْقَسَمِ؛ وَعَلَامَةُ الْجَرِّ الْكَسْرَةُ.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">ضَبْحًا</span><span lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">حَالٌ مَنْصُوبٌ مِنْ فِعْلٍ مَحْذُوفٍ بِمَعْنَى «يَضْبَحْنَ»؛ وَالْجُمْلَةُ «يَضْبَحْنَ ضَبْحًا» فِي مَحَلِّ النَّصْبِ حَالًا.</span></div>\n      </div>\n      <div class=\"callout\">\n        <div class=\"callout-title\">What is ضَبْحًا exactly?</div>\n        Classical grammarians classify ضَبْحًا as <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">الْحَالُ</span> (a circumstantial accusative describing the state of the subject) rather than <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">الْمَفْعُولُ الْمُطْلَقُ</span>, because it is grounded in an implied verbal clause — the horses gallop while panting.\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 2</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">فَٱلْمُورِيَـٰتِ قَدْحًا</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"And the strike-fire sparkers —\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>The <span class=\"ar-inline\">فَ</span> is here a conjunction of sequence and continuation (<span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">حَرْفُ عَطْفٍ</span>). <span class=\"ar-inline\">الْمُورِيَاتُ</span> is coordinated (<span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">مَعْطُوفٌ</span>) on <span class=\"ar-inline\">الْعَادِيَاتِ</span> above and therefore takes the same full iʿrāb: <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">الْجَرُّ</span> by the implied <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">وَاوُ الْقَسَمِ</span>.</p>\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">قَدْحًا</span> functions exactly as <span class=\"ar-inline\">ضَبْحًا</span> did — a <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">حَالٌ</span> clause (<span class=\"ar-inline\">يَقْدَحْنَ قَدْحًا</span>) in <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">النَّصْبُ</span>. The image is of hooves striking rocks and throwing sparks.</p>\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">فَالْمُورِيَاتِ</span><span lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">مَعْطُوفٌ عَلَى «الْعَادِيَاتِ» بِالْفَاءِ؛ وَيَلْحَقُهَا نَفْسُ الْإِعْرَابِ.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">قَدْحًا</span><span lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">حَالٌ مَنْصُوبٌ؛ وَالْجُمْلَةُ الْمَقْدُورَةُ «يَقْدَحْنَ» فِي مَحَلِّ النَّصْبِ.</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 3</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">فَٱلْمُغِيرَٰتِ صُبْحًا</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"And the raiders at dawn —\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>The same structure continues: <span class=\"ar-inline\">الْمُغِيرَاتُ</span> is coordinated on the earlier oaths via <span class=\"ar-inline\">فَ</span> and carries the same <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">إِعْرَابُ الْجَرِّ</span>.</p>\n      <p>Here, however, <span class=\"ar-inline\">صُبْحًا</span> shifts grammatical function. Rather than a <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">حَالٌ</span> clause, it is <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">ظَرْفُ زَمَانٍ</span> (adverb of time) — “at the time of dawn” — in the accusative, dependent on a suppressed verb of raiding (<span class=\"ar-inline\">أَغِرْنَ</span>).</p>\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">فَالْمُغِيرَاتِ</span><span lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">مَعْطُوفٌ عَلَى «الْعَادِيَاتِ»؛ مَجْرُورٌ بِوَاوِ الْقَسَمِ الْمَقْدُورِ.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">صُبْحًا</span><span lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">ظَرْفُ زَمَانٍ مَنْصُوبٌ بِالْفَتْحَةِ؛ مُتَعَلِّقٌ بِالْفِعْلِ الْمَحْذُوفِ «أَغِرْنَ».</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 4</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">فَأَثَرْنَ بِهِۦ نَقْعًا</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"And they raise therewith a cloud of dust —\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>This verse introduces a full verb for the first time. <span class=\"ar-inline\">أَثَرْنَ</span> is a past tense verb (<span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">الْفِعْلُ الْمَاضِي</span>) built on the feminine plural <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">نُونُ النِّسْوَةِ</span>, making it indeclinable on sukūn. The nūn itself is the subject pronoun (<span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">الْفَاعِلُ</span>) in the position of <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">الرَّفْعُ</span>.</p>\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">بِهِ</span> is a prepositional phrase — the bāʾ is a preposition, and the hāʾ refers to the valley or battleground. The entire phrase relates to <span class=\"ar-inline\">أَثَرْنَ</span>. <span class=\"ar-inline\">نَقْعًا</span> (dust) is the direct object (<span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">الْمَفْعُولُ بِهِ</span>) in <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">النَّصْبُ</span>, marked by the visible fatḥa.</p>\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">أَثَرْنَ</span><span lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">فِعْلٌ مَاضٍ؛ مَبْنِيٌّ عَلَى السُّكُونِ لِأَجْلِ نُونِ النِّسْوَةِ؛ وَالنُّونُ فَاعِلٌ فِي مَحَلِّ الرَّفْعِ.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">بِهِ</span><span lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">جَارٌّ وَمَجْرُورٌ مُتَعَلِّقٌ بِ«أَثَرْنَ».</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">نَقْعًا</span><span lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">مَفْعُولٌ بِهٍ؛ مَنْصُوبٌ بِالْفَتْحَةِ الظَّاهِرَةِ.</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 5</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">فَوَسَطْنَ بِهِۦ جَمْعًا</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"And they plunge therewith into the midst of the assembled host —\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>This final image of the oath sequence mirrors verse 4 structurally. <span class=\"ar-inline\">وَسَطْنَ</span> is likewise <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">مَاضٍ</span> with <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">نُونُ النِّسْوَةِ</span> as <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">فَاعِلٌ</span>. <span class=\"ar-inline\">جَمْعًا</span> (a gathered host/crowd) is <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">مَفْعُولٌ بِهٍ</span> in <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">النَّصْبُ</span>. The entire clause is coordinated on what preceded it and sits in the position of <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">النَّصْبُ</span> (as the final <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">حَالٌ</span> clause in the long oath chain).</p>\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">وَسَطْنَ</span><span lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">فِعْلٌ مَاضٍ مَعْطُوفٌ عَلَى «أَثَرْنَ» بِالْفَاءِ؛ وَنَفْسُ الْإِعْرَابِ.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">جَمْعًا</span><span lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">مَفْعُولٌ بِهٍ؛ مَنْصُوبٌ بِالْفَتْحَةِ.</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <hr class=\"divider\">\n  <div class=\"section-head\">Part II — The Answer to the Oath (Verses 6–8)</div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 6</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">إِنَّ ٱلْإِنسَـٰنَ لِرَبِّهِۦ لَكَنُودٌ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"Indeed, mankind is ungrateful to his Lord —\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>Here the oath delivers its answer (<span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">جَوَابُ الْقَسَمِ</span>). In Arabic, the answer to an oath is often introduced by <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">إِنَّ</span> plus the emphatic <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">لَامُ التَّوْكِيدِ</span> — both present here, making this statement doubly emphatic.</p>\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">إِنَّ</span> is a particle that resembles a verb (<span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">حَرْفُ تَوْكِيدٍ مُشَبَّهٌ بِالْفِعْلِ</span>) — it governs its following noun in <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">النَّصْبُ</span> (like an accusative subject) and raises its predicate. <span class=\"ar-inline\">الْإِنسَانَ</span> is accordingly <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">اسْمُ إِنَّ</span> in <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">النَّصْبُ</span>, marked by visible fatḥa. <span class=\"ar-inline\">لِرَبِّهِ</span> is a prepositional phrase related to the predicate <span class=\"ar-inline\">كَنُودٌ</span>. The lām of <span class=\"ar-inline\">لَكَنُودٌ</span> is the emphatic <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">لَامُ التَّوْكِيدِ</span>, and <span class=\"ar-inline\">كَنُودٌ</span> is <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">خَبَرُ إِنَّ</span> in <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">الرَّفْعُ</span>, marked by visible ḍamma. The whole Inna-sentence has no syntactic position (<span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">لَا مَحَلَّ لَهَا مِنَ الْإِعْرَابِ</span>) because it is <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">جَوَابُ الْقَسَمِ</span>.</p>\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">إِنَّ</span><span lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">حَرْفُ تَوْكِيدٍ مُشَبَّهٌ بِالْفِعْلِ؛ يَنْصِبُ اسْمَهُ وَيَرْفَعُ خَبَرَهُ.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">الْإِنسَانَ</span><span lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">اسْمُ إِنَّ؛ مَنْصُوبٌ بِالْفَتْحَةِ.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">لِرَبِّهِ</span><span lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">جَارٌّ وَمَجْرُورٌ مُتَعَلِّقٌ بِخَبَرِ «كَنُودٍ»؛ وَالْهَاءُ ضَمِيرٌ مُتَّصِلٌ فِي مَحَلِّ الْجَرِّ بِالْإِضَافَةِ.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">لَكَنُودٌ</span><span lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">لَامُ التَّوْكِيدِ + خَبَرُ إِنَّ؛ مَرْفُوعٌ بِالضَّمَّةِ الظَّاهِرَةِ.</span></div>\n      </div>\n      <div class=\"callout\">\n        <div class=\"callout-title\">Key vocabulary: كَنُود</div>\n        كَنُود means one who is ungrateful and withholds generosity — used of both a stingy person and one who denies blessings. Its placement as <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">خَبَرُ إِنَّ</span> carries the full weight of the oath sworn over five vivid scenes.\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 7</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">وَإِنَّهُۥ عَلَىٰ ذَٰلِكَ لَشَهِيدٌ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"And indeed he himself is a witness to that —\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>The wāw is a conjunction. <span class=\"ar-inline\">إِنَّ</span> returns, and its <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">اسْمٌ</span> is the attached pronoun <span class=\"ar-inline\">هُ</span> (him/it) in the position of <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">النَّصْبُ</span> — a bound pronoun (<span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">ضَمِيرٌ مُتَّصِلٌ</span>) built on ḍamma. <span class=\"ar-inline\">عَلَىٰ ذَلِكَ</span> is a prepositional phrase: <span class=\"ar-inline\">ذَا</span> is an indeclinable demonstrative noun in the position of <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">الْجَرُّ</span> by <span class=\"ar-inline\">عَلَى</span>; the lām is for pointing to something distant, and the kāf addresses the listener. This phrase is related to <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">الْخَبَرُ</span> <span class=\"ar-inline\">شَهِيدٌ</span>. The whole sentence is coordinated on verse 6.</p>\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">إِنَّهُ</span><span lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">إِنَّ + ضَمِيرٌ مُتَّصِلٌ «هُ» اسْمُهَا فِي مَحَلِّ النَّصْبِ.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">عَلَىٰ ذَلِكَ</span><span lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">حَرْفُ جَرٍّ + اسْمُ إِشَارَةٍ مَبْنِيٌّ فِي مَحَلِّ الْجَرِّ؛ مُتَعَلِّقٌ بِ«شَهِيدٍ».</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">لَشَهِيدٌ</span><span lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">لَامُ التَّوْكِيدِ + خَبَرُ إِنَّ؛ مَرْفُوعٌ بِالضَّمَّةِ الظَّاهِرَةِ.</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 8</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">وَإِنَّهُۥ لِحُبِّ ٱلْخَيْرِ لَشَدِيدٌ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"And indeed he is intense in his love of wealth —\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>Structurally mirroring verse 6. <span class=\"ar-inline\">لِحُبِّ الْخَيْرِ</span> is a prepositional phrase related to <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">الْخَبَرُ</span> <span class=\"ar-inline\">شَدِيدٌ</span>. Within it, <span class=\"ar-inline\">حُبّ</span> is the <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">مُضَافٌ</span> and <span class=\"ar-inline\">الْخَيْرِ</span> is <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">مُضَافٌ إِلَيْهِ</span> in <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">الْجَرُّ</span> by <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">الْإِضَافَةُ</span>. <span class=\"ar-inline\">لَشَدِيدٌ</span> is <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">خَبَرُ إِنَّ</span> in <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">الرَّفْعُ</span>. The sentence is coordinated on verse 6 and likewise carries no syntactic position.</p>\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">لِحُبِّ الْخَيْرِ</span><span lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">جَارٌّ وَمَجْرُورٌ + إِضَافَةٌ؛ مُتَعَلِّقٌ بِ«شَدِيدٍ».</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">لَشَدِيدٌ</span><span lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">خَبَرُ إِنَّ؛ مَرْفُوعٌ بِالضَّمَّةِ.</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <hr class=\"divider\">\n  <div class=\"section-head\">Part III — The Reckoning (Verses 9–11)</div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 9</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">أَفَلَا يَعْلَمُ إِذَا بُعْثِرَ مَا فِى ٱلْقُبُورِ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"Does he not know — when what is in the graves is scattered —\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>This verse is rich in particles. The hamza (<span class=\"ar-inline\">أَ</span>) is a particle of rhetorical question (<span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">هَمْزَةُ الِاسْتِفْهَامِ</span>); the fāʾ is a resumptive/connective particle (<span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">حَرْفُ اسْتِنَافٍ</span>); and <span class=\"ar-inline\">لَا</span> is a negative particle with no grammatical effect of its own here.</p>\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">يَعْلَمُ</span> is a present-tense verb (<span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">الْفِعْلُ الْمُضَارِعُ</span>) in <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">الرَّفْعُ</span> — marked by visible ḍamma — with a concealed subject pronoun (<span class=\"ar-inline\">هُوَ</span>, “he”). <span class=\"ar-inline\">إِذَا</span> is a conditional temporal adverb (<span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">ظَرْفٌ لِمَا يُسْتَقْبَلُ مِنَ الزَّمَانِ</span>) built on sukūn in the position of <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">النَّصْبُ</span> as a <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">ظَرْفُ زَمَانٍ</span>, related to its own answer/apodosis. It carries a conditional meaning. The clause <span class=\"ar-inline\">بُعْثِرَ مَا فِي الْقُبُورِ</span> sits in the position of <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">الْجَرُّ</span> as <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">مُضَافٌ إِلَيْهِ</span> of <span class=\"ar-inline\">إِذَا</span>.</p>\n      <p>Inside that clause: <span class=\"ar-inline\">بُعْثِرَ</span> is a past passive verb (<span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">الْمَاضِي الْمَجْهُولُ</span>) built on fatḥ. <span class=\"ar-inline\">مَا</span> is a relative pronoun (<span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">الاسْمُ الْمَوْصُولُ</span>) in the position of <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">الرَّفْعُ</span> as <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">نَائِبُ الْفَاعِلِ</span>. <span class=\"ar-inline\">فِي الْقُبُورِ</span> is a prepositional phrase that forms the entire relative clause (<span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">صِلَةُ الْمَوْصُولِ</span>) — it is read as the implicit predicate meaning “what had settled/remained in the graves.”</p>\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">يَعْلَمُ</span><span lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">فِعْلٌ مُضَارِعٌ مَرْفُوعٌ بِالضَّمَّةِ؛ وَالْفَاعِلُ ضَمِيرٌ مُسْتَتِرٌ تَقْدِيرُهُ «هُوَ».</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">إِذَا</span><span lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">ظَرْفُ زَمَانٍ بِمَعْنَى الشَّرْطِ؛ فِي مَحَلِّ النَّصْبِ؛ وَالْجُمْلَةُ بَعْدَهَا مُضَافٌ إِلَيْهَا فِي مَحَلِّ الْجَرِّ.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">بُعْثِرَ</span><span lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">فِعْلٌ مَاضٍ مَجْهُولٌ؛ مَبْنِيٌّ عَلَى الْفَتْحَةِ.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">مَا</span><span lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">اسْمٌ مَوْصُولٌ فِي مَحَلِّ الرَّفْعِ نَائِبُ فَاعِلٍ.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">فِي الْقُبُورِ</span><span lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">صِلَةُ الْمَوْصُولِ؛ تَقْدِيرُ الْخَبَرِ «مَا اسْتَقَرَّ فِي الْقُبُورِ».</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 10</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">وَحُصِّلَ مَا فِى ٱلصُّدُورِ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"And what is in the breasts is laid bare —\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>The wāw coordinates this verse on verse 9. <span class=\"ar-inline\">حُصِّلَ</span> is another <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">الْمَاضِي الْمَجْهُولُ</span> — a passive past verb — on the pattern of <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">فَعَّلَ</span>, here meaning “to be extracted, sifted, brought to light.” <span class=\"ar-inline\">مَا</span> is again <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">اسْمٌ مَوْصُولٌ</span> as <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">نَائِبُ فَاعِلٍ</span>. The <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">صِلَةُ الْمَوْصُولِ</span> is again an implied <span class=\"ar-inline\">اسْتَقَرَّ فِي الصُّدُورِ</span> — “what had settled in the breasts.” This entire verse is coordinated on the preceding conditional clause.</p>\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">حُصِّلَ</span><span lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">فِعْلٌ مَاضٍ مَجْهُولٌ عَلَى وَزْنِ «فَعَّلَ»؛ بِمَعْنَى «نُقِّيَ/أُبْرِزَ».</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">مَا / فِي الصُّدُورِ</span><span lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">نَفْسُ إِعْرَابِ الْآيَةِ ٩: مَوْصُولٌ + صِلَةٌ بِخَبَرٍ مَقْدُورٍ.</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"ayah-block\">\n    <div class=\"ayah-num\">Verse 11</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-arabic\">إِنَّ رَبَّهُم بِهِمْ يَوْمَئِذٍ لَّخَبِيرٌ</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-translation\">\"Indeed their Lord, on that Day, is fully aware of them.\"</div>\n    <div class=\"ayah-body\">\n      <p>The surah closes with a final Inna-sentence that is <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">اسْتِنَافِيَّةٌ</span> — a fresh, independent conclusive statement with no syntactic position. <span class=\"ar-inline\">رَبَّهُمْ</span> is <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">اسْمُ إِنَّ</span> in <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">النَّصْبُ</span>: <span class=\"ar-inline\">رَبّ</span> is <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">مُضَافٌ</span> and the pronoun <span class=\"ar-inline\">هُمْ</span> (the mīm for plural) is <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">مُضَافٌ إِلَيْهِ</span> in <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">الْجَرُّ</span> by <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">الْإِضَافَةُ</span>.</p>\n      <p><span class=\"ar-inline\">بِهِمْ</span> is a prepositional phrase related to <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">الْخَبَرُ</span> <span class=\"ar-inline\">خَبِيرٌ</span>. <span class=\"ar-inline\">يَوْمَئِذٍ</span> is a compound temporal expression: <span class=\"ar-inline\">يَوْم</span> is <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">ظَرْفُ زَمَانٍ</span> in <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">النَّصْبُ</span> (by fatḥa) and is <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">مُضَافٌ</span>; <span class=\"ar-inline\">إِذٍ</span> is an indeclinable noun built on sukūn but vocalized with kasra to avoid a double-sukūn clash — it is <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">مُضَافٌ إِلَيْهِ</span> in the position of <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">الْجَرُّ</span>. The deleted sentence it stands for — “the day when the graves are scattered and the breasts are laid bare” — is itself <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">مُضَافٌ إِلَيْهِ</span> of <span class=\"ar-inline\">إِذ</span>, in the position of <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">الْجَرُّ</span> by <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">الْإِضَافَةُ</span>, compensated by tanwīn. <span class=\"ar-inline\">لَخَبِيرٌ</span> is <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">خَبَرُ إِنَّ</span> with <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">لَامُ التَّوْكِيدِ</span>; in <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">الرَّفْعُ</span> by visible ḍamma.</p>\n      <div class=\"grammar-note\">\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">رَبَّهُمْ</span><span lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">اسْمُ إِنَّ مَنْصُوبٌ؛ «رَبٌّ» مُضَافٌ + ضَمِيرٌ «هُمْ» مُضَافٌ إِلَيْهِ فِي مَحَلِّ الْجَرِّ.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">بِهِمْ</span><span lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">جَارٌّ وَمَجْرُورٌ مُتَعَلِّقٌ بِ«خَبِيرٍ».</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">يَوْمَئِذٍ</span><span lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">ظَرْفُ زَمَانٍ مَنْصُوبٌ؛ «يَوْمٌ» مُضَافٌ + «إِذٍ» مُضَافٌ إِلَيْهِ فِي مَحَلِّ الْجَرِّ؛ وَالتَّنْوِينُ عِوَضٌ عَنْ الْمَحْذُوفِ.</span></div>\n        <div class=\"grammar-row\"><span class=\"gkey\">لَخَبِيرٌ</span><span lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">لَامُ التَّوْكِيدِ + خَبَرُ إِنَّ؛ مَرْفُوعٌ بِالضَّمَّةِ.</span></div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <hr class=\"divider\">\n\n  <div class=\"theme-box\">\n    <h3>Structural Summary</h3>\n    <div class=\"theme-grid\">\n      <div class=\"theme-card\">\n        <div class=\"theme-card-label\">Verses 1–5</div>\n        Five sworn oaths by the warhorses. Grammatically one long oath-clause (<span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">جَارٌّ وَمَجْرُورٌ</span> + <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">حَالٌ</span> / <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">ظَرْفُ زَمَانٍ</span>) with no syntactic position — <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">جُمْلَةٌ ابْتِدَائِيَّةٌ</span>.\n      </div>\n      <div class=\"theme-card\">\n        <div class=\"theme-card-label\">Verses 6–8</div>\n        <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">جَوَابُ الْقَسَمِ</span>: three <span class=\"ar-inline\" dir=\"rtl\" style=\"font-size:15px\">إِنَّ</span>-sentences in succession, each with <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">لَامُ التَّوْكِيدِ</span> in <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">الْخَبَرِ</span>. No syntactic position — each is continuation of the oath-answer.\n      </div>\n      <div class=\"theme-card\">\n        <div class=\"theme-card-label\">Verses 9–10</div>\n        Rhetorical question with a conditional temporal clause (<span class=\"ar-inline\">إِذَا</span>) spanning two verses; two passive verbs (<span class=\"ar-inline\">بُعْثِرَ</span> / <span class=\"ar-inline\">حُصِّلَ</span>) with <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">اسْمٌ مَوْصُولٌ</span> as <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">نَائِبُ فَاعِلٍ</span>.\n      </div>\n      <div class=\"theme-card\">\n        <div class=\"theme-card-label\">Verse 11</div>\n        Closing <span class=\"ar-inline\">إِنَّ</span>-sentence (<span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">اسْتِنَافِيَّةٌ</span>): no syntactic position. Emphatic <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">لَامُ التَّوْكِيدِ</span> in <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">الْخَبَرُ</span>. The compound <span class=\"ar-inline\">يَوْمَئِذٍ</span> is the syntactic highlight — <span class=\"term\" lang=\"ar\" dir=\"rtl\">إِضَافَةٌ</span> + compensatory tanwīn.\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  </div>"};
